"Lopes A.M., Fam D., Williams J.","Designing sustainable sanitation: Involving design in innovative, transdisciplinary research",,"Design Studies",,,,,,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053341126&partnerID=40&md5=124acec81b6b7b8d38eda4f6b18c04b9","University of Western Sydney, Penrith NSW 2751, Australia; University of Technology, Sydney NSW 2007, Australia","Lopes, A.M., University of Western Sydney, Penrith NSW 2751, Australia; Fam, D., University of Technology, Sydney NSW 2007, Australia; Williams, J., University of Technology, Sydney NSW 2007, Australia","This paper introduces an innovative pilot project where an alternative system of sanitation to capture, treat and reuse urine in agricultural trials is being undertaken in a university setting. The paper outlines the emerging theory and practise of Transition Management (TM) and identifies a lack of attention to the end-user in transition experiments to date. This project situates design as a core component in the social process of transitioning to a novel system of sanitation. Students across two design schools developed visual prototypes to introduce the project to the target audiences, which were tested during a pre-pilot installation. Initial results support the guiding hypothesis that design has a critical role to play in facilitating social learning in system innovation. Crown Copyright © 2011.","Design education; Design research; Graphic design; Sustainable sanitation; User participation",,,,,,,,"Lopes, A.M.; University of Western Sydney, Penrith NSW 2751, Australiaemail: a.lopes@uws.edu.au",,,,,,,,0142694X,,DSSTD,10.1016/j.destud.2011.08.005,,"English","Design Studies",Article in Press,Scopus
"Silvestri A., Marcante A.","The glass of Nogara (Verona): A "" window"" on production technology of mid-Medieval times in Northern Italy",2011,"Journal of Archaeological Science",38,10,,2509,2522,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80051808490&partnerID=40&md5=f2a21e1e76cfb3d62a678eba8227ddda","Dipartimento di Geoscienze, Università di Padova, Via Gradenigo 6, 35131 Padova, Italy; Dipartimento di Archeologia e Storia delle Arti, Università di Siena, Via Roma 56, 53100 Siena, Italy","Silvestri, A., Dipartimento di Geoscienze, Università di Padova, Via Gradenigo 6, 35131 Padova, Italy; Marcante, A., Dipartimento di Archeologia e Storia delle Arti, Università di Siena, Via Roma 56, 53100 Siena, Italy","The site of Nogara (province of Verona, Italy) provides valuable insights into the complexities of the glass industry in mid-Medieval times, due to its timing, which ranges mainly between the 10th and 11th centuries AD, and to the great quantity of glass findings, mainly tableware. In the present paper, the combination of archaeological, chemical and textural data allows us to identify production technologies in a time-interval perceived to be a period of technological transition for glass. In particular, the frequent occurrence of recycled natron glass and only a few glass samples made with soda plant ash indicate that recycling of earlier glass was common in inland Northern Italy in the 10th-11th centuries AD. In addition, blue and reticello decorations were obtained by recycling earlier glass mosaic tesserae, as shown by much Co, Cu, Sn, Sb and Pb and the presence of crystallised calcium antimonates. A few glass samples with chemical compositions intermediate between natron and soda plant ash glass were also identified, suggesting a gradual change in glass composition from natron-based towards soda ash-based production technology, which prevailed in the 13th-14th centuries. In conclusion, the difficulty in describing mid-Medieval glass as a well-defined entity, due to the great propensity for recycling earlier glass samples which causes variability in chemical compositions, particularly those of trace elements, is clearly documented here. In any case, this paper contributes to a new type of chrono-typological scanning and to more detailed knowledge of glass production technology during mid-Medieval times in Northern Italy, little found in the literature until now. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Glass; Mid-Medieval times; Nogara; Production technology; Recycling","archaeology; chemical composition; glass; industrial technology; Medieval; productivity; recycling; Italy",,,,,,"Barkoundah, Y., Henderson, J., Plant ashes from Syria and the manufacture of ancient glass: ethnographic and scientific aspects (2006) Journal of Glass Studies, 48, pp. 297-321; Barrera, J., Velde, B., A study of French Medieval glass composition (1989) Archéologie Médiévale, 19, pp. 81-130; Baumgartner, E., Krueger, I., (1988) Phönix aus sand und asche. Glas des mittelalters, München; Bierbrauer, V., (1987) Invillino-Ibligo in Friaul. I. Die römische Siedlung und das spätantik-frühmittelalterliche Castrum, München, pp. 271-425; Bimson, M., Freestone, I.C., An analysis of blue glass from the enamel (2001) San Vincenzo al Volturno 3: the finds from the 1980-86 excavations, Centro Italiano di studi sull'alto Medioevo, Spoleto, pp. 285-286. , J. Mitchell, I.L. Hansen (Eds.); Brill, R.H., The chemical interpretation of the texts (1970) Glass and Glassmaking in Ancient Mesopotamia, Corning Museum of Glass, New York, pp. 105-128. , A.L. Oppenheim, R.H. Brill, D. Barag, A. von Saldern (Eds.); Brill, R.H., Scientific investigations of the Jalame glass and related finds (1988) Excavations at Jalame, site of a glass factory in late Roman Palestine, pp. 257-293. , University of Missouri Press, Columbia, G.D. Wienberg (Ed.); Brill, R.H., (1999) Chemical analyses of early glasses. Catalogue and Tables of Analyses, , The Corning Museum of Glass, Corning, New Yo