"Hurlbert M., McNutt K., Rayner J.","Pathways to power: Policy transitions and the reappearance of the nuclear power option in Saskatchewan",2011,"Energy Policy",39,6,,3182,3190,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955894590&partnerID=40&md5=e1a50fea7715c35baaf557249768c954","University of Regina, CL 235-3737 Wascana Parkway, Regina, SK S4S 0A2, Canada; Johnson-Shoyama Graduate School of Public Policy, University of Regina, 110-2 Research Drive, Regina, SK S4S 0A2, Canada; University of Regina, CL 211-3737 Wascana Parkway, Regina, SK S4S 0A2, Canada","Hurlbert, M., University of Regina, CL 235-3737 Wascana Parkway, Regina, SK S4S 0A2, Canada; McNutt, K., Johnson-Shoyama Graduate School of Public Policy, University of Regina, 110-2 Research Drive, Regina, SK S4S 0A2, Canada; Rayner, J., University of Regina, CL 211-3737 Wascana Parkway, Regina, SK S4S 0A2, Canada","Saskatchewan, a Canadian prairie province, has recently begun to restructure the provincial energy system. The institutional, technological and social bases of the Saskatchewan power regime have been disrupted by both exogenous pressures and endogenous problems, providing an opportunity for alternative energy options to be considered as possible power alternatives. As the province addresses the long-term socio-technical transition (STR) associated with a regime change in the power sector a number of alternative energy options have been identified. Using a transition management approach, this paper argues that the path taken will depend very much on whether these alternatives can be adopted as modifications of the existing STR - leaving the key actors, institutions and relationships essentially untouched - or whether they will necessitate a wholesale reconstruction of the regime itself. In this paper we analyze how, over time, the socio-technical configurations of the energy system became very durable as existing technologies become embedded in regulatory frameworks, infrastructure, users practices and expert communities. We then consider the potential of several alternative technological trajectories and the likelihood of one of these socio technical regimes emerging in Saskatchewan. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Policy change; Saskatchewan power; Transition management","Alternative energy; Canadian prairie; Energy systems; Key Actors; Nuclear power; Policy changes; Power alternatives; Power sector; Regulatory frameworks; Saskatchewan; Saskatchewan power; Socio-technical regimes; Sociotechnical; Transition management; Nuclear energy; alternative energy; energy policy; nuclear power; Canada; Saskatchewan",,,,,,"Appleton, B., (1994) Navigating NAFTA: A concise user's guide to the North American Free Trade Agreement, , Carswell Legal Publications; Avelino, F., Rotmans, J., Power in transition an interdisciplinary framework to study power in relation to structural change (2009) European Journal of Social Theory, 12 (4), pp. 543-569; Berkhout, F., Smith, A., Stirling, A., Understanding system innovations: a critical literature review and a conceptual synthesis (2004) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability: Theory, Evidence and Policy, pp. 48-75. , Edward Elgar, Cheltenham, Glos, B. Elzen, F. Geels, K. Green (Eds.); (2008), http://www.brucepower.com/docs/reports/corporate/Saskatchewan%202020%20-%20Clean%20energy%20New%20opportunity.pdf, Bruce Power, Saskatchewan 2020: Clean energy. New opportunity. Report on Bruce Power's Feasibility StudyCorrelje, A., Verbong, G., The Transition from coal to gas: radical change of the Dutch gas system (2004) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability: Theory, Evidence and Policy, pp. 114-136. , Edward Elgar, Cheltenham, Glos, B. Elzen, F. Geels, K. Green (Eds.); Environment Canada. National Inventory Report 1990-2006: Greenhouse Gas Sources and Sinks in Canada (2008), http://www.ec.gc.ca/pdb/ghg/inventory_report/2006/som-sum_eng.cfm, Ottawa 〈〉Geels, F.W., Technological transitions as evolutionary re