"Stirling A.","Pluralising progress: From integrative transitions to transformative diversity",2011,"Environmental Innovation and Societal Transitions",1,1,,82,88,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79958015917&partnerID=40&md5=e7321cc4e36951425bd4942089084587","SPRU - Science and Technology Policy Research, University of Sussex, Freeman Centre, Brighton BN1 9RF, United Kingdom","Stirling, A., SPRU - Science and Technology Policy Research, University of Sussex, Freeman Centre, Brighton BN1 9RF, United Kingdom","This paper examines key issues raised by consideration of diversity in the study of environmental innovation and societal transitions. In different ways and degrees, these implicate many contrasting perspectives, including innovation studies, evolutionary economics and transitions research. The paper therefore attends equally to the implications of plurality among disciplines as observing subjects and varieties of sociotechnical configurations as observed objects. Inspired by recent literatures in these fields, the argument focuses in turn on: contending social normativities concerning alternative directions for innovation; divergent disciplinary understandings of societal transitions; and disparate conceptualisations of sociotechnical diversity itself. In each area, the paper identifies some persistent forms of 'misplaced concreteness'. Recommendations are made as to how the implications of diversity might be addressed in more rigorous and reflective ways. In conclusion, it is shown how rigour and reflexivity themselves depend on plural analytical communities paying greater regard to diversity and striking their own balance between pluralism and concreteness. This highlights a series of specific, but hitherto unresolved, research questions. © 2011 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Diversity; Reflexivity; Transformation; Transition; Uncertainty","innovation; literature review; social change; sustainability; sustainable development; theoretical study; uncertainty analysis",,,,,,"Bijker, W.E., Social construction of technology (2009) A Companion to the Philosophy of Technology; Cf Geels, F.W., From sectoral systems of innovation to socio-technical systems: Insights about dynamics and change from sociology and institutional theory (2004) Research Policy, 33 (6-7), pp. 897-920; Collingridge, D., (1982) Critical Decision Making: A New Theory of Social Choice, , Pinter London; Daly, H., The circular flow of exchange value and the linear throughput of matter-energy: A case of misplaced concreteness (1985) Review of Social Economy, 43 (3), pp. 279-297; Dosi, G., (2000) Innovation, Organization and Economic Dynamics: Selected Essays, , Edward Elgar Cheltenham; Elzen, B., Geels, F.W., Green, K., (2005) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability: Theory, Evidence and Policy, , Edward Elgar Cheltenham; Feyerabend, P., (1970) Problems of Empiricism, , Cambridge University Press; Frenken, K., A complexity approach to innovation networks (2000) Research Policy, 29, pp. 257-272; Geels, F.W., Ontologies, socio-technical transitions (to sustainability), and the multi-level perspective (2010) Research Policy, 39, pp. 495-510; Geels, F.W., Schot, J., Typology of sociotechnical transition pathways (2007) Research Policy, 36 (3), pp. 399-417. , DOI 10.1016/j.respol.2007.01.003, PII S0048733307000248; Genus, A., Coles, A.-M., Rethinking the multi-level perspective of technological transitions (2008) Research Policy, 37 (9), pp. 1436-1445; Gieryn, T., Boundaries of science (1995) Handbook of Science and Technology Studies, pp. 393-443; Grabher, G., Stark, D., Organizing diversity: Evolutionary theory, network analysis and postsocialism (1997) Regional Studies, 31 (5), pp. 533-544; Jasanoff, S., (2005) Designs on Nature: Science and Democracy in Europe and the United States, , Princeton University Press Princeton; Kuhn, T., (2000) The Road since Structure, , University of Chicago Press; Landau, R., Taylor, T., 