"Wheeler J.","Charcoal analysis of industrial fuelwood from medieval and early modern iron-working sites in Bilsdale and Rievaulx, North Yorkshire, UK: Evidence for species selection and woodland management",2011,"Environmental Archaeology",16,1,,16,35,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960137324&partnerID=40&md5=d6b54a7f1865c7ea2258a2079527b564","Division of Archaeological, Geographical and Environmental Sciences (AGES), University of Bradford, Bradford BD7 1DP, United Kingdom","Wheeler, J., Division of Archaeological, Geographical and Environmental Sciences (AGES), University of Bradford, Bradford BD7 1DP, United Kingdom","This paper presents the results of species diversity and dendrological analyses of archaeological charcoal excavated from medieval and early modern iron production sites in Bilsdale, and at Rievaulx in the neighbouring valley of Ryedale, North Yorkshire, UK. Standard methods of quantification are used to assess species diversity, sampling sufficiency and taxa presence. The assessment of dendrological features provides additional evidence for growth trends and cutting cycles analogous with cyclical woodland management, as well as environmental and growing conditions. Analysis of archaeological charcoal from four medieval bloomery furnace sites in Bilsdale, and from the site of the hammersmithy and blast furnace at the early modern iron works at Rievaulx, provide comparable data-sets which indicate a change in cutting practise and dominant species selection for industrial fuelwood occurred between the 12th- and mid-16th centuries AD. Results show that dominant species presence changed from an admixture of predominantly birch (Betula sp.) and hazel (Corylus avellana) sourced from small calibre branchwood and stemwood used in the medieval bloomery furnaces, to a dominant oak (Quercus sp.) presence from standard sources used at the Rievaulx iron works by the mid-16th century. Whilst it is uncertain whether this change in dominant species composition and the source of industrial fuelwood is related to changes in local availability, or the result of the technological transition to blast furnace processing which occurred at this time, estate records reveal a woodland management campaign was instigated to supply and maintain fuelwood supplies to the iron works at Rievaulx which coincides with the introduction of Tudor arboricultural legislation in the 1540s. © Association for Environmental Archaeology 2011 Published by Maney.","Archaeological charcoal; Iron-smelting; Medieval early modern; Species selection; Woodland management",,,,,,,"Ashcroft, M.Y., Hill, A.M., (1980) Bilsdale Surveys 1637-1851, , Northallerton: North Yorkshire County Record Office; Asouti, E., Austin, P., Reconstructing woodland vegetation and its exploitation by past societies, based on the analysis and interpretation of archaeological wood charcoal macro-remains (2005) Environmental Archaeology, 10, pp. 1-18; Atkinson, J.C., Cartularium Abbathiæ de Rievalle ordinis Cisterciensis (1889) Publications of the Surtees Society, 83. , Durham: Andrews and Co./London: Whittaker and Co./Edinburgh: William Blackwood and Sons; Bernard, V., Renaudin, S., Margueire, D., Evidence of trimmed oaks (Quercus sp.) in north western France during the early middle ages (9th-11th centuries AD) (2006) BAR International Series, 1483, pp. 103-108. , Dufraisse, A. (ed.), Charcoal Analysis: New Analytical Tools and Methods for Archaeology (Papers from the Table-Ronde held in Basel 2004) Oxford: Archaeopress; Boyd, W.E., Analysis and interpretation of non-artefactual wood assemblages from archaeological sites (1988) Wood and Archaeology, pp. 311-318. , Hackens, T., Munaut, A. V. and Till, C. (eds.), Strasbourg: Council of Europe; Chabal, L., Fabre, L., Terral, J.-F., Théry-Parisot, J.-F., L'Anthracologie (1999) La Botanique, pp. 43-104. , Bourquin-Mignot, C., Brochier, J.-E. and Chabal, L. (eds.), France: Errance; Clark, A.J., Tarling, D.H., Noel, M., 