"Berkers E., Geels F.W.","System innovation through stepwise reconfiguration: The case of technological transitions in Dutch greenhouse horticulture (1930-1980)",2011,"Technology Analysis and Strategic Management",23,3,,227,247,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79951834061&partnerID=40&md5=ea22ffd72b57d4e7cc596c3cebf63469","Eindhoven University of Technology, School of Innovation Sciences, IPO Building, 5600 MB Eindhoven, Netherlands; SPRU, Science and Technology Policy Research, University of Sussex, Freeman Building, Brighton, BN1 9QE, United Kingdom","Berkers, E., Eindhoven University of Technology, School of Innovation Sciences, IPO Building, 5600 MB Eindhoven, Netherlands; Geels, F.W., SPRU, Science and Technology Policy Research, University of Sussex, Freeman Building, Brighton, BN1 9QE, United Kingdom","Although transitions are usually perceived as technological substitution processes, the article shows that stepwise reconfiguration is more likely for supplier-dominated sectors. In this transition pattern, novelties are initially adopted as 'modular innovation' into existing systems and subsequently reconfigure the basic architecture through new combinations of old and new elements. Incumbent actors survive these transitions through interactions with suppliers of knowledge and innovations. Using Pavitt's innovation typology, we selected a case study from his supplier-dominated category: greenhouse farming. The article makes a techno-economic analysis of the overall transition pattern in Dutch greenhouse horticulture (1930-1980) and a socio-institutional analysis of the knowledge flows and networks. 'Innovation cascades' are identified as a particularly important mechanism in reconfiguration transitions. © 2011 Taylor & Francis.","Greenhouse horticulture; Knowledge flows; Reconfiguration; Sectoral innovation system; Technological transition","agricultural technology; greenhouse gas; horticulture; innovation; knowledge; technology adoption",