"Waring J., Dixon-Woods M., Yeung K.","Modernising medical regulation: Where are we now?",2010,"Journal of Health, Organisation and Management",24,6,,540,555,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78049516795&partnerID=40&md5=963590dc6c60cdf116875d818fa21913","Nottingham University Business School, Nottingham, United Kingdom; Department of Health Sciences, University of Leicester, Leicester, United Kingdom; Centre for Technology, Ethics, Law and Society, School of Law, King's College London, London, United Kingdom","Waring, J., Nottingham University Business School, Nottingham, United Kingdom; Dixon-Woods, M., Department of Health Sciences, University of Leicester, Leicester, United Kingdom; Yeung, K., Centre for Technology, Ethics, Law and Society, School of Law, King's College London, London, United Kingdom","Purpose: This paper aims to outline and comment on the changes to medical regulation in the UK that provide the background to a special issue of the Journal of Health Organization and Management on regulating doctors. Design/methodology/approach: This paper takes the form of a review. Findings: Although the UK medical profession enjoyed a remarkably stable regulatory structure for most of the first 150 years of its existence, it has undergone a striking transformation in the last decade. Its regulatory form has mutated from one of state-sanctioned collegial self-regulation to one of state-directed bureaucratic regulation. The erosion of medical self-regulation can be attributed to: the pressures of market liberalisation and new public management reforms; changing ideologies and public attitudes towards expertise and risk; and high profile public failures involving doctors. The ""new"" UK medical regulation converts the General Medical Council into a modern regulator charged with implementing policy, and alters the mechanisms for controlling and directing the conduct and performance of doctors. It establishes a new set of relationships between the medical profession and the state (including its agencies), the public, and patients. Originality/value: This paper adds to the literature by identifying the main features of the reforms affecting the medical profession and offering an analysis of why they have taken place. © Emerald Group Publishing Limited.","Doctors; Medical sciences; Public administration; Regulation; Transition management","article; government regulation; health care delivery; health care policy; human; legal aspect; physician; United Kingdom; Delivery of Health Care; Government Regulation; Great Britain; Health Care Reform; Humans; Physicians",,,,,,"Ackroyd, S., Organization contra organizations: Professions and organizational change in the United Kingdom (1996) Organization Studies, 17, pp. 599-621; Allsop, J., Mulcahy, L., (1996) Regulating Medical Work: Formal and Informal Controls, , Open University, Buckingham; Arluke, A., Social control rituals in medicine: The case of the death rounds (1977) Health Care and Health Knowledge, , Dingwall, R., Heath, C., Reid, M., Stacey, M. (Eds.), Croom Helm, London; Beck, U., (1992) Risk Society, , Sage, London; Black, J., Decentring regulation: Understanding the role of regulation and self-regulation in a 'post-regulatory' world (2001) Current Legal Problems, 54, pp. 103-146; Campbell, S., McDonald, R., Lester, H., The experience of pay for performance in English family practice: A qualitative study (2008) Annals of Family Medicine, 6, pp. 228-234; Dent, M., Doctors, peer review and quality assurance (1995) Health Professionals and the State in Europe, , Johnson, T., Larkin, G., Saks, M. (Eds.), Routledge, London; DoH, (2000) An Organisation with a Memory, , TSO, London; DoH, (2008) Trust, Assurance and Safety, , TSO, London; Esmail, A., Physician as serial killer - the Shipman case (2005) New England Journal of Medicine, 352, pp. 1843-1844; Foster, C.D., (1992) Privatisation, Public Ownership and the Regulation of Natural Monopoly, , Blackwell, Oxfo