"Huetink F.J., der Vooren A.V., Alkemade F.","Initial infrastructure development strategies for the transition to sustainable mobility",2010,"Technological Forecasting and Social Change",77,8,,1270,1281,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956689502&partnerID=40&md5=02364fc38416430d355f566d1a6a71ac","Innovation Studies Group Utrecht, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584CS Utrecht, Netherlands","Huétink, F.J., Innovation Studies Group Utrecht, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584CS Utrecht, Netherlands; der Vooren, A.V., Innovation Studies Group Utrecht, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584CS Utrecht, Netherlands; Alkemade, F., Innovation Studies Group Utrecht, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584CS Utrecht, Netherlands","Within the Dutch transition policy framework, the transition to hydrogen-based transport is seen as a promising option towards a sustainable transport system. One aspect of such transition processes that is emphasized in transition management is learning about user behaviour and preferences. However, while earlier research on sustainable mobility acknowledges the importance of refuelling infrastructure, the question of how to unroll such an infrastructure and the role of user practices and user behaviour largely remains unanswered. In this paper we present an agent-based model to study the process of development from niche to market for hydrogen vehicles. We thereby focus on the role of users in this process and support our model by empirical data. Within this model the effects of different strategies for hydrogen infrastructure development on hydrogen vehicle fleet penetration are studied. More specifically, diffusion patterns for hydrogen vehicles are created through the interactions of consumers, refuelling stations and technological learning. The main result is that social network effects do influence the technological trajectory of hydrogen vehicles and thus should be taken into account by infrastructure developers and policymakers. © 2010 Elsevier Inc.","Agent-based modeling; Hydrogen; Infrastructure development; Technological change","Agent-based model; Agent-based modeling; Diffusion patterns; Empirical data; Hydrogen infrastructure; Hydrogen vehicles; Infrastructure development; Policy framework; Policy makers; Social Networks; Sustainable mobility; Sustainable transport systems; Technological change; Technological learning; Technological trajectories; Transition management; Transition process; User behaviour; User practices; Computational methods; Fleet operations; Planning; Vehicles; Hydrogen; development strategy; hydrogen; infrastructural development; mobility; numerical model; sustainable development; technological development; transport vehicle; transportation system; Netherlands",,,,,,"Kemp, R., Rotmans, J., Loorbach, D., Assessing the Dutch energy transition policy: how does it deal with dilemmas of managing transitions (2007) Journal of Environmental Policy and Planning, 9 (3-4), pp. 315-331; Loorbach, D., (2007) Transition management: new mode of governance for sustainable development, , (Utrecht: International Books); Kemp, R., Rotmans, J., Managing the transition to sustainable mobility (2004) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability: Theory, Evidence and Policy, pp. 137-167. , (Cheltenham: Edward Elgar), E. Boelie, F.W. Geels, K. Green (Eds.); Nill, J., Kemp, R., Evolutionary approaches for sustainable innovation policies: from niche to paradigm? (2009) Research policy, 38, pp. 668-680; Alkemade, F., Hekkert, M.P., (2009), Development paths for emerging innovation systems: implications for environmental innovations. ISU working paper 0908Klepper, S., Industry life cycles (1997) Industrial and Corporate Change, 6 (1), pp. 145-181; Dunn, S., Hydrogen futures: toward a sustainable energy system (2002) International Journal of Hydrogen Energy, 27 (2002), pp. 235-264; Phaal, R., Farrukh, C.J.P., Probert, D.R., Technology roadmapping-a p