"Foxon T.J., Hammond G.P., Pearson P.J.G.","Developing transition pathways for a low carbon electricity system in the UK",2010,"Technological Forecasting and Social Change",77,8,,1203,1213,,5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955943259&partnerID=40&md5=ef9a416754197d934bc57cda6d33a065","Sustainability Research Institute, School of Earth and Environment, University of Leeds, Leeds LS29 9HH, United Kingdom; Department of Mechanical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering and Design, University of Bath, Bath BA2 7AY, United Kingdom; Low Carbon Research Institute, Welsh School of Architecture, Cardiff University, Cardiff CF10 3NB, United Kingdom","Foxon, T.J., Sustainability Research Institute, School of Earth and Environment, University of Leeds, Leeds LS29 9HH, United Kingdom; Hammond, G.P., Department of Mechanical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering and Design, University of Bath, Bath BA2 7AY, United Kingdom; Pearson, P.J.G., Low Carbon Research Institute, Welsh School of Architecture, Cardiff University, Cardiff CF10 3NB, United Kingdom","This paper describes the approach to developing transition pathways for a low carbon electricity system in the UK, being pursued in a major new inter-disciplinary research project. The project aims (a) to learn from past transitions to help explore future transitions and what might enable or avoid them; (b) to design and evaluate transition pathways towards alternative socio-technical energy systems and infrastructures for a low carbon future; and (c) to understand and, where appropriate, model the changing roles, influences and opportunities of large and small 'actors' in the dynamics of transitions. The paper describes the approach, which builds on the work of Dutch researchers on transitions and transition management using a multi-level framework of niches, socio-technical regime and landscape, as well as on other parts of the innovation systems literature. It also describes its application to several outline transition pathways to a low carbon energy system in the UK. The pathways embrace both the evolution of the physical and institutional infrastructure changes and the roles of both large actors, e.g. multinational energy supply and distribution companies, national governments, major investors, and small actors, e.g. households, innovators and entrepreneurs. © 2010 Elsevier Inc.","Dynamic processes; Multi-level perspective; Technological innovation systems; Transition pathways; UK energy system","Dynamic process; Energy systems; Multi-level; Technological innovation; Transition pathway; Research; Technological forecasting; Innovation; alternative fuel; carbon; development project; electricity supply; infrastructural development; innovation; technological change; Netherlands; United Kingdom",,,,,,"Rip, A., Kemp, R., Technological change (1998) Human Choices and Climate Change, 2. , Battelle Press, Columbus, Ohio, S. Rayner, E.L. Malone (Eds.); Geels, F., Technological transitions as evolutionary reconfiguration processes: a multi-level perspective and a case-study (2002) Research Policy, 31, pp. 1257-1274; Geels, F., (2005) Technological Transitions and System Innovations: A Co-evolutionary and Socio-Technical Analysis, , Edward Elgar, Cheltenham; Kemp, R., Technology and the transition to environmental sustainability: the problem of technological regime shifts (1994) Futures, 26, pp. 1023-1046; Verbong, G., Geels, F., The ongoing energy transition: Lessons from a socio-technical, multi-level analysis of the Dutch electricity system (1960-2004) (2007) Energy Policy, 35, pp. 1025-1037; Kemp, R., Rotmans, J., The management of the co-evolution of technical, environmental and social systems (2005) Towards Environmental Innovation Systems, , Springer Verlag, Berlin, M. Weber, J. Hemmelskamp (Eds.); Loorbach, D., (2007) Transition Management: New Mode of Governance for Sustainable Development, , International Books, Utrecht, the Netherlands; Freeman, C., Louca, F., (2001) As Time Goes By, , Oxford University Press; Nelson, R., The co-evolution of technologies, industrial structures, and supporting institutions (1994) Industrial and Corporate Change, 3 (1), pp. 47-63; Nelson, R., (2005) Technology, Institutions and Economic Growth, , Harvard University Press; Murmann, J.P., (2003) Knowledge and Competitive Advantage: The Coevolution of Firms, Technology and National Institutions, , Cambridge University Press; Stenzel, T., Frenzen, A., Regulating technological change-the strategic reactions of utility companies towards subsidy policies in the German, Spanish and UK electricity markets (2008) Energy Policy, 36 (7), pp. 2645-2657; Hekkert, M., Suurs, R., Negro, S., Kuhlmann, S., Smits, R., Functions of innovation systems: a new approach for analyzing technological change (2007) Technological Forecasting & Social Change, 74, pp. 413-432; Jacobsson, S., Bergek, A., Transforming the energy sector: the evolution of technology systems in renewable energy technology (2004) Industrial and Corporate Change, 13 (5), pp. 815-849; (1992) National Systems of Innovation: Towards a Theory of Innovation and Interactive Learning, , Pinter Publishers, London, B.-A. Lundvall (Ed.); Negro, S., Hekkert, M., Smits, R., Explaining the failure of the Dutch innovation system for biomass digestion-a functional analysis (2007) Energy Policy, 35, pp. 925-938; Smith, A., Stirling, A., Berkhout, F., The governance of sustainable socio-technical transitions (2005) Research Policy, 34, pp. 1491-1510; Berkhout, F., Smith, A., Stirling, A., Socio-technical regimes and transition contexts (2004) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability: Theory, Evidence and Policy, , Edward Elgar, Cheltenham, B. Elzen, F. Geels, K. Green (Eds.); Geels, F., Schot, J., Typology of sociotechnical transition pathways (2007) Research Policy, 36, pp. 399-417; Shackley, S., Green, K., A conceptual framework for exploring transitions to decarbonised energy systems in the UK (2005) En