"de Bruijne M., van de Riet O., de Haan A., Koppenjan J.","Dealing with dilemma's: How can experiments contribute to a more sustainable mobility system?",2010,"European Journal of Transport and Infrastructure Research",10,3,,274,289,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78049409649&partnerID=40&md5=677f48b3a4255e08063ff8e00dea252c","Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands; Netherlands Institute for Transport Policy Analysis, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands; Department of Public Administration, Faculty of Social Sciences, Erasmus University, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands","de Bruijne, M., Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands; van de Riet, O., Netherlands Institute for Transport Policy Analysis, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands; de Haan, A., Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands; Koppenjan, J., Department of Public Administration, Faculty of Social Sciences, Erasmus University, PO Box 5015, 2600 GA, Delft, Netherlands","Sustainable mobility has proved to be a perennial challenge to realize. Scholars have argued that experiments could point the way forward towards sustainable mobility (cf. Loorbach, 2007, Markard and Truffer, 2008). In doing so, literature attributes a vital but complex task to those who engage in experiments. However, an important knowledge gap pertains to whether and how experiments contribute to learning about transitions and in what way they should be managed to break-up the more or less inertial mobility governance system. This paper aims to analyze how state-of-the-art literature on the governance of multi-actor systems considers experiments to contribute to transitions and highlight key dilemma's that professionals engaged in the management of experimental face in the day-to-day management and decision making processes during the experiment. The paper will highlight these dilemmas and choices and illustrate their importance for experiments in the field of transportation and more specifically in the specific context of the Dutch mobility system and the TRANSUMO research program. Identifying these dilemma's benefits practitioners who are engaged in the management of experiments to more consciously reflect on and include issues of second-order learning in the day-to-day management and decision making during the experiment to reach a more sustainable mobile system.","Experiment; Multi-actor governance; Project management; Transition management","Break-up; Complex task; Decision making process; Governance systems; Knowledge gaps; Mobile systems; Mobility systems; Multi-actor governance; Multi-actor systems; Research programs; Second orders; Sustainable mobility; Transition management; Experiments; Project management; Decision making",,,,,,"Avelino, F., Empowerment and the challenge of applying transition management to ongoing projects (2009) Policy Sciences, 42, pp. 369-390; Brown, H.S., Vergragt, P., Green, K., Berchicci, L., Learning for Sustainability Transition through Bounded Socio-technical Experiments in Personal Mobility (2003) Technology Analysis and Strategic Management, 15, pp. 291-315; Brown, H.S., Vergragt, P.J., Bounded socio-technical experiments as agents of systemic change: The case of a zero-energy residential building (2008) Technological Forecasting and Social Change, 75, pp. 107-130; De Bruijn, H., van der Voort, H., Dicke, W., De Jong, M., Veeneman, W., (2004) Creating System Innovation, How large scale transitions emerge, , Leiden, A.A. Balkema Publishers; De Bruijn, H., ten Heuvelhof, E., (2008) Management in Networks, On multi-actor decision making, , London, Routledge; De Bruijn, H., ten Heuvelhof, E., In 't Veld, R., (2002) Process Management, Why Project Management Fails in Complex Decision Making Proce