"Wilkins M.J.","Modular procedural automation addressing the post recession skills gap",2010,"10AIChE - 2010 AIChE Spring Meeting and 6th Global Congress on Process Safety",,,,,,12,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955998309&partnerID=40&md5=96a0695ad98034551825f42054e44c98","Yokogawa IA Global Marketing Center (USMK), 2155 Chenault Drive, Carrollton, TX 75006, United States","Wilkins, M.J., Yokogawa IA Global Marketing Center (USMK), 2155 Chenault Drive, Carrollton, TX 75006, United States","Procedural operation consists of a set of tasks that are conducted in a set way time after-time to achieve a certain goal such as starting or shutting down a unit or making a product. Procedural operations are used in continuous processes for many operations including grade changes, transition management, start-ups, shutdowns, and even emergency procedures. A discussion covers a definition of procedural operations; accepted ways to implement procedures; benefits of using prompted and automated procedural operations, e.g., improved safety; modular procedural automation (MPA), a flexible approach that provides benefits and good engineering practices to all process industries, e.g., pipelines, oil refining; benefits by using MPA to enforce the proper, consistent, and safe execution of procedures for both normal and exception conditions; and multi-industry applicability of MPA. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the 2010 Spring National Meeting (San Antonio, TX, 3/21-25/2010).","Modular procedural automation; Procedural automation standard; Procedures",,,,,,,"Fiske, T., (2008) Best Practices for Advanced Process Control, , ARC Advisory Group Report, January; McKenzie, P., S88 - It's not just for batch anymore! WBF NA Conference, , Baltimore; Yoksas, G., Surviving a process safety management inspection (2001) ACHMM Conference, , Chicago, IL; (2009) Safe Ups and Downs for Process Units, BP Process Safety Series, IChemE, Seventh Edition; Higuchi, F., Tani, T., A future vision of IT-based systematized control room operation (2005) NPRA Plant & Decision Support Conference, , Grapevine, TX","Wilkins, M.J.; Yokogawa IA Global Marketing Center (USMK), 2155 Chenault Drive, Carrollton, TX 75006, United States; email: maurice.wilkins@us.yokogawa.com",,,,"2010 AIChE Spring Meeting and 6th Global Congress on Process Safety, 10AIChE","21 March 2010 through 25 March 2010","San Antonio, TX",,,9780816910649,,,,"English","10AIChE - 2010 AIChE Spring Meeting and 6th Global Congress on Process Safety",Conference Paper,Scopus
"Munasinghe K.S., Jamalipour A.","NEtwork MObility (NEMO) support in interworking heterogeneous mobile networks",2010,"IEEE Wireless Communications and Networking Conference, WCNC",,, 5506517,,,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955029691&partnerID=40&md5=f3175339d543a180cdb92e9cfafbdf6c","School of Electrical and Information Engineering, University of Sydney, Australia","Munasinghe, K.S., School of Electrical and Information Engineering, University of Sydney, Australia; Jamalipour, A., School of Electrical and Information Engineering, University of Sydney, Australia","With the expansion of the Next Generation Mobile Network (NGMN), ubiquitous service access is increasingly becoming a reality. As a result, an increasing number of users are accessing applications and services while travelling, especially on public transportation systems, thus giving rise to group mobility scenarios. Therefore, it is essential for the NGMN to be equipped with group mobility management support for achieving seamless session handoffs for a group of users or devices moving together. For a group of members moving between two networks, location transition management was initially addressed in the Internet Engineering Task Force's (IETF) NEtwork MObility (NEMO) basic support protocol. However, the two networks in this case are homogeneous in nature. This paper proposes the integration of NEMO support for an NGMN architecture for enabling group mobility management between multiple heterogeneous networks. Results and analysis illustrate that by integrating NEMO support to an NGMN reduces handoff latency, transient packet loss, jitter, and signaling cost for both end users and service providers. ©2010 IEEE.","CDMA2000; IMS; MIP-NEMO; Mobile IP; NEMO; Network mobility; SIP; SIP-NEMO; UMTS; WiMAX","Cdma2000; End users; Group mobility; Handoff Latency; Internet engineering task forces; Interworking; MIP-NEMO; Mobile IP; Mobile networks; Network mobility; Public transportatio