"Meijerink S., Huitema D.","Policy entrepreneurs and change strategies: Lessons from sixteen case studies of water transitions around the globe",2010,"Ecology and Society",15,2,,17,,,2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954480392&partnerID=40&md5=c031f56d9ae53967f928345c522d1bc1","Nijmegen School of Management, Radboud University Nijmegen; Institute for Environmental Studies (IVM), VU University Amsterdam","Meijerink, S., Nijmegen School of Management, Radboud University Nijmegen; Huitema, D., Institute for Environmental Studies (IVM), VU University Amsterdam","This paper focuses on the role of policy entrepreneurs in realizing water policy transitions. The central questions are to what extent have policy entrepreneurs played a role in realizing major change in water policies, who are these policy entrepreneurs, and what strategies have they used to bring about change? The policy science literature suggests that policy entrepreneurs have an arsenal of possible strategies for achieving change. Based on a comparative analysis of water policy changes in 15 countries around the globe and the European Union, we investigate which strategies have in practice been used by policy entrepreneurs, to what effect, and which lessons for managing water transitions we can draw from this. The comparative case analysis shows that individuals play complementary roles; hence, entrepreneurship in water management is often collective entrepreneurship. Strategies of coalition building, the manipulation of decision making forums, and the strategic framing of issues and windows are crucial to understanding water policy change, which suggests that the management of water policy transitions is a highly political game. We conclude by listing recommendations for those who would like to direct water policy change. © 2010 by the author(s).","Change strategies; International comparison; Policy change; Policy entrepreneurs; Transition management; Water management","comparative study; decision making; entrepreneur; European Union; policy approach; strategic approach; water management; water planning",,,,,,"Anckar, C., On the applicability of the most similar systems design and the most different systems design in comparative research (2008) International Journal of Social Research Methodology, 11, pp. 389-401; Baumgartner, F.R., Berry, J.M., Hojnacki, M., Kimball, D.C., Leech, B.L., Lobbying and policy change. Who wins, who loses, and why (2009) The University of Chicago Press, , Chicago, Illinois, USA; Baumgartner, F.R., Jones, B.D., Agenda dynamics and policy subsystems (1991) Journal of Politics, 53, pp. 1044-1074; Becker, G., Germany: Transitions in flood management in the Rhine basin (2009) Water Policy Entrepreneurs: A Research Companion to Water Transitions Around the Globe, pp. 325-348. , D. Huitema and S. Meijerink, editors, Edward Elgar Publishing, Cheltenham, UK; Bhat, A., Mollinga, P.P., Transitions in Indonesian water policy: Policy windows through crisis, response through implementation (2009) Water policy entrepreneurs: A research companion to water transitions around the globe, pp. 158-174. , D. Huitema and S. Meijerink, editors, Edward Elgar Publishing, Cheltenham, UK; Birkland, T.A., (1997) After Disaster: Agenda Setting, Public Policy, and Focusing Events, , Georgetown University Press, Washington, D.C., USA; Boin, A., Hart, T.P., McConnell, A., Crisis exploitation: Political and policy impacts of framing contests (2009) Journal of European Public Policy, 16, pp. 81-106; Font, N., Subirats, J., Water management in Spain: The role of policy entrepreneurs in shaping change (2010) Ecology and Society, 15 (2), p. 25. , http://www.ecologyandsociety.org/vol15/iss2/art25/, online; Goldin, J., Kibassa, D., Past, present and future landscapes of water policy in Tanzania (2009) Water Policy Entrepreneurs: A Research Companion to Water Transitions Around the Globe, pp. 37-57. , D. Huitema and S. Meijerink, editors. Edward Elgar Publi