"Shove E., Walker G.","Governing transitions in the sustainability of everyday life",2010,"Research Policy",39,4,,471,476,,8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77950110299&partnerID=40&md5=845331f8891cb1b0dcfb978c232bd6d1","Department of Sociology, Bowland North, Lancaster University, Lancaster, United Kingdom; Department of Geography, LEC, Lancaster University, Lancaster, United Kingdom","Shove, E., Department of Sociology, Bowland North, Lancaster University, Lancaster, United Kingdom; Walker, G., Department of Geography, LEC, Lancaster University, Lancaster, United Kingdom","The literature on sociotechnical transitions and their governance tends to concentrate on the introduction of new technologies and systems of supply. In this paper we seek to extend the scope of debate, introducing aspects of practice theory as a means of also conceptualising the dynamics of demand. Rather than treating 'human need' or 'societal functions' as given, we consider how variously sustainable practices come into existence, how they disappear and how interventions of different forms may be implicated in these dynamics. We use the two cases of daily showering and the congestion charging scheme in London to consider the distinctive challenges of understanding transitions in practice and of governing these so as to engender more sustainable ways of life. © 2010 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Everyday practice; Governance; Sociotechnical transitions","Congestion charging schemes; Human needs; New technologies; Societal functions; Sociotechnical; Sustainable practices; Sustainable development",,,,,,"Armstrong, D., (1983) Political Anatomy of the Body: Medical Knowledge in Britain in the Twentieth Century, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Akrich, M., The description of technical objects (1992) Shaping Technology/Building Society: Studies in Sociotechnical Change, pp. 205-224. , Bijker W., and Law J. (Eds), MIT Press, London; Congestion charge comes into forc