"Akerman M., Kilpio A., Peltola T.","Institutional change from the margins of natural resource use: The emergence of small-scale bioenergy production within industrial forestry in Finland",2010,"Forest Policy and Economics",12,3,,181,188,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-74449084358&partnerID=40&md5=10390508cbc4003fdf0f49756bdc2221","Department of Regional Studies, University of Tampere, FI-33014, Finland; Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Helsinki University of Technology, P.O. Box 2100, FI-02015 TKK, Finland; Finnish Environment Institute, P.O. Box 140, FI-00251 Helsinki, Finland","Åkerman, M., Department of Regional Studies, University of Tampere, FI-33014, Finland; Kilpiö, A., Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Helsinki University of Technology, P.O. Box 2100, FI-02015 TKK, Finland; Peltola, T., Finnish Environment Institute, P.O. Box 140, FI-00251 Helsinki, Finland","There exists a growing interest in understanding the mechanisms of innovations in the forestry sector. This article contributes to that goal by presenting a detailed study of the emergence of small-scale wood energy production practices in Finland. Given the distinctive and institutionally strong orientation of Finnish forestry towards raw material production for the pulp and paper industry, such innovative ways of using forest resources seem somewhat improbable and surprising. Despite this, we argue that the development of these new production practices can be understood as a process of institutional renewal that combines elements of continuity and novelty. In our empirical analysis, we follow the emergence of a new forest management category of ""young forest"" and explore how its naturalization as part of various institutional rules, identities and practices enabled the birth of local wood energy production within the forestry sector. In order to elucidate this multidimensional change, we analyze the new forest category as a boundary object, a socio-technical category with multiple functions and identities, within the large technological system of forestry. These analytical concepts help us illuminate how various material and discursive practices-both in the forestry and energy sectors and at the local and national levels-were able to interact for innovation and institutional change. © 2009 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Boundary object; Classification; Forest management; Innovations; Institutions; Large technological system; Socio-technical category; Technological transition","Boundary objects; Forest management; Large technological system; Sociotechnical; Technological transition; Innovation; Paper and pulp industry; Societies and institutions; Timber; Forestry; Classification; Forest Management; Forestry; Innovation; Paper; Pulps",,,,,,"Åkerman, M., Risusavotasta maaseudun teknologiaihmeeseen: puun energiakäyttöä tukevat ""käännökset"" metsätalouden, energiapolitiikan ja maaseutupolitiikan kentillä (2005) Alue ja Ympäristö, 34, pp. 30-41. , (In Finnish with English summary); Åkerman, M., Jänis, L., Lähienergiaa puusta-maatalouden ja energiantuotannon synergiaeduista voimaa maaseudun kehitykseen (2005) Maaseudun Uusi Aika, 13, pp. 41-48; Åkerman, M., Kaljonen, M., Peltola, T., Integrating environmental policies into local practices-the politics of agri-environmental and energy policies in rural Finland (2005) Local Environment, 10, pp. 595-611; Bowker, G., Biodiversity datadiversity (2000) Social Studies of Science, 30, pp. 643-683; Bowker, G.C., Star, S.L., (2000) Sorting Things Out: Classification and Its Consequences, , The MIT Press, Cambridge, MA; Callon, M., Techno-economic networks and irreversibility (1991) A Sociology of Monsters: Essays on Power, Technology and Domination, pp. 132-161. , Law J. (Ed), Routledge, London; Demeritt, D., Scientific forest conservation and the statistical picturing of nature's limits in the progressive era United States (2001) Environment and Planning D: Soc