"Setzer T., Bhattacharya K., Ludwig H.","Change scheduling based on business impact analysis of change-related risk",2010,"IEEE Transactions on Network and Service Management",7,1, 5412873,58,71,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77249176157&partnerID=40&md5=fad46b596af5c9add24a22f877990c70","Department of Informatics, Technische Universität München, 85748 Garching, Germany; IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Business-driven IT Management Research Group, 19 Skyline Dr., Hawthorne, NY-10532, United States","Setzer, T., Department of Informatics, Technische Universität München, 85748 Garching, Germany; Bhattacharya, K., IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Business-driven IT Management Research Group, 19 Skyline Dr., Hawthorne, NY-10532, United States; Ludwig, H., IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Business-driven IT Management Research Group, 19 Skyline Dr., Hawthorne, NY-10532, United States","In today's enterprises, the alignment of IT service infrastructures to continuously changing business requirements is a key cost driver, all the more so as most severe service disruptions can be attributed to the introduction of changes into the IT service infrastructure. Change management is a disciplined process for introducing required changes with minimum business impact. Considering the number of business processes in an enterprise and the complexity of the dependency network of processes to invoked services, one of the most pressing problems in change management is the risk-aware prioritization and scheduling of vast numbers of service changes. In this paper we introduce a model for estimating the business impact of operational risk resulting from changes. We determine the business impact based on the number and types of business process instances affected by a change-related outage and quantify the business impact in terms of financial loss. The model takes into account the network of dependencies between processes and services, probabilistic change-related downtime, uncertainty in business process demand, and various infrastructural characteristics. Based on the analytical model, we derive decision models aimed at scheduling single or multiple correlated changes with the lowest expected business impact. The models are evaluated using simulations based on industry data. © 2010 IEEE.","Business impact analysis; Change management; Change scheduling; Risk management; Service networks; Service transition management","Analytical model; Business impact; Business impact analysis; Business Process; Business requirement; Change management; Change scheduling; Cost drivers; Decision models; Financial loss; IT services; Operational risks; Prioritization; Related risk; Service disruptions; Information technology; Losses; Risk analysis; Risk management; Risk perception; Scheduling",,,,,,"Sauve, J.P., Santos, R.A., Almeida, R.R., Moura, J.A.B., On the risk exposure and priority determination of changes in IT service management (2007) Managing Virtualization of Networks and Services, 4785, pp. 147-158. , Berlin/Heidelberg: Springer; (2000) Service Support (IT Nfrastructure Library Series), , OGC, London UK:; The bottom line project: IT change management challenges-results of 2006 web survey (2006) Tech. Rep. DSC005-06, , Computing Systems Department, Federal University of Campina Grande; Itil change management maturity benchmark study (2006) Evergreen Consulting, Tech. Rep., , OGC; (2009) Tivoli Change and Configuration Management Database, , http://www.ibm.com/software/tivoli/products/ccmdb/, [Online]. Available; Huehn, O., Markl, C., Performance modeling for SLA-compliant but cost-effective IT-service provisioning (2007) Proc. 17th Workshop Inf. Technol. Syst. (WITS), , Montreal, Canada; Setzer, T., Bhattacharya, K., Ludwig, H., Decision support for service transition management (2008) Proc. 11th IEEE Netw. Operations Management Symp. (NOMS), , Salvador, Brazil; (2007) Management of Risk, Guidance for Practioners, , OGC London, UK: 