"Gilligan I.","The prehistoric development of clothing: Archaeological implications of a thermal model",2010,"Journal of Archaeological Method and Theory",17,1,,15,80,,3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76349106427&partnerID=40&md5=3a02003ba8b548779ce29d774a40d0a3","School of Archaeology and Anthropology, The Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia","Gilligan, I., School of Archaeology and Anthropology, The Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia","This paper presents a thermal model for the prehistoric origin and development of clothing. A distinction is drawn between simple and complex forms of clothing, with broad implications for the interpretation of paleolithic technological transitions and the emergence of modern human behavior. Physiological principles and paleoenvironmental data are harnessed to identify conditions requiring simple, loosely draped garments and the more challenging conditions that demanded additional protection in the form of complex garment assemblages. No actual clothing survives from the Pleistocene, yet the archaeological record yields evidence for technological and other correlates of clothing-more evidence than is generally supposed. Major innovations and trends in the distributions and relative frequencies of lithic and other tool forms may reflect the changing need for portable insulation in the context of fluctuating ice age climates. Moreover, the nonthermal repercussions of complex clothing can be connected with archaeological signatures of modern human behavior, notably adornment. Alternative models are less parsimonious in accounting for the geographical and temporal variability of prominent technological and other behavioral patterns in association with environmental change. © Springer Science+Business Media, LLC 2009.","Climate; Clothing; Modern human behavior; Paleolithic technology",,,,,,,"Adovasio, J.M., Soffer, O., Klíma, B., Upper palaeolithic fibre technology: Interlaced woven finds from Pavlov I, Czech Republic, c. 26, 000 years ago (1996) Antiquity, 70, pp. 526-534; Aiello, L., Wheeler, P., Neanderthal thermoregulation and the glacial climate (2003) Neanderthals and Modern Humans in the European Landscape during the Last Glaciation: Archaeological Results of the Stage 3 Project, pp. 147-166. , T. H. Andelvan and W. Davies (Eds.), Cambridge: McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research; Aikens, C.M., Higuchi, T., (1982) Prehistory of Japan, , New York: Academic; Aitken, M.J., Valladas, H., Luminescence dating relevant to human origins (1992) Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London Series B, 337, pp. 139-144; Alexander, R.D., Some unanswered questions about naked mole-rats (1991) The Biology of the Naked Mole-Rat, pp. 446-465. , P. W. Sherman, J. U. M. Jarvis, and R. D. Alexander (Eds.), Princeton: Princeton University Press; Alexeeva, N.V., Erbajeva, M.A., Pleistocene permafrost in western Transbaikalia (2000) Quaternary International, 68-71, pp. 5-12; Ambrose, S.H., Paleolithic technology and human evolution (2001) Science, 291, pp. 1748-1753; Anikovich, M.V., Sinitsyn, A.A., Hoffecker, J.F., Holliday, V.T., Popov, V.V., Lisitsyn, S.N., Early upper paleolithic in eastern Europe and implications for the dispersal of modern humans (2007) Science, 315, pp. 223-226; Antoine, P., Rousseau, D.-D., Fuchs, M., Hatté, C., Gauthier, C., Marković, S.B., High-resolution record of the last climatic cycle in the southern Carpathian Basin (Surduk, Vojvodina, Serbia) (2009) Quaternary International, 198, pp. 19-36; Ascensi, A., Mallegni, F., Manzi, G., Segre, A.G., Segre Naldini, E., A re-appraisal of Ceprano calvaria affinities with Homo erectus, after the new reconstruction (2000) Journal of Human Evolution, 39, pp. 443-450; Ashton, N., Jacobi, R., White, M.J., The dating of Levallois sites in west London (2003) Quaternary Newsletter, 99, pp. 25-32; Ashton, N., Lewis, S., Parfitt, S., Candy, I., Keen, D., Kemp, 