"Ekins P., Hughes N.","The prospects for a hydrogen economy (2): Hydrogen transitions",2010,"Technology Analysis and Strategic Management",22,1,,1,17,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-74949084754&partnerID=40&md5=f0d5aaf9f9b2d28dc78a6920e3316e0b","University College London, United States; Imperial College London, United States","Ekins, P., University College London, United States; Hughes, N., Imperial College London, United States","Any transition to 'a hydrogen economy' will amount to a major technological transition. Four possible transitions are discussed in the context of the literature on technological transitions. Responses from both experts and focus groups to such projections of such transitions show that they raise major issues of public acceptability, which are also explored. It is clear that any kind of hydrogen transition is unlikely to come about without the systematic and determined implementation of public policy and the paper ends by examining the kinds of public policy that might be required for the hydrogen economy to become a reality. © 2010 Taylor & Francis.","Hydrogen economy; Hydrogen policies; Hydrogen transitions; Public acceptability","alternative energy; energy market; energy policy; future prospect; hydrogen; policy implementation; technological development; transitional economy",,,,,,"Agnolucci, P., Ekins, P., Technological transitions and strategic niche management: The case of the hydrogen economy (2007) International Journal of Environmental Technology and Management, 7 (5-6), pp. 644-671; Agnolucci, P., McDowall, W., Technological change in niches: Auxiliary power units and the hydrogen economy (2007) Technological Forecasting and Social Change, 74, pp. 1394-1410; Bellaby, P., Dresner, S., Flynn, R., Ricci, M., Tomei, J., Public acceptability of hydrogen: Lessons for policies and institutions (2007) Ukshec Social Science Working Paper No. 31, , http://www.psi.org.uk/ukshec/publications.htm, PSI, London. Available 