"Hendriks C.M.","Policy design without democracy? Making democratic sense of transition management",2009,"Policy Sciences",42,4,,341,368,,7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72449144656&partnerID=40&md5=987c0a58814ab50f234c026b916817df","Crawford School of Economics and Government, ANU College of Asia and the Pacific, Australian National University, JG Crawford Building No. 13, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia","Hendriks, C.M., Crawford School of Economics and Government, ANU College of Asia and the Pacific, Australian National University, JG Crawford Building No. 13, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia","This article explores the complex relationship between democracy and long-term policy design for sustainability. At one extreme, democracy can be framed as problematic for policy planning because of the myopia fostered by some democratic institutions, such as regular elections. Alternatively, democracy can be seen as an ally of long-term policy design to the extent that it can generate public legitimacy and accountability, and potentially foster more equitable and just outcomes. Recent debates on how to 'manage' policy transitions to sustainability have been curiously silent on democratic matters, despite their potential implications for democracy. To explore what democracy might mean for transition management this article considers empirically how actors engaged in the Dutch Energy Transition Program make democratic sense of their activities. The analysis finds that in practice transition policies promote implicit narratives or democratic storylines on how reforms should be developed, who should participate in these, and how they should be legitimised and accountable to the public. The dominant narrative, which espouses elite theory and technocracy, privileges epistemic matters over democratic considerations. Other democratic storylines draw on representative democracy and interest group pluralism. The paper considers some possible ways to foster more productive interfaces between the governance structures of transition management, and the polycentric context of contemporary democratic systems. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media, LLC.","Accountability; Democracy; Energy; Legitimacy; Long-term policy design; Network governance; Participation; Representative; Sustainability; Transition management","accountability; democracy; governance approach; local participation; management practice; policy making; policy reform; sustainability",,,,,,"Aars, J., Fimreite, A.L., Local government and governance in Norway: Stretched accountability in network politics (2005) Scandinavian Political Studies, 28 (3), pp. 239-256. , DOI 10.1111/j.1467-9477.2005.00131.x; Argyris, C., Putnam, R., McLain Smith, D., (1985) Action Science, Concepts, Methods, and Skills for Research and Intervention, , Jossey-Bass San Francisco; Auel, K., Multi-level governance, regional policy, and democratic legitimacy in Germany (2006) Governance and Democracy, pp. 44-62. , A. Benz Y. Papadopoulous (eds). Routledge Oxon; Baber, W.F., Bartlett, R.V., (2005) Deliberative Environmental Politics, , MIT Press Cambridge, MA; Bang, H., Sørensen, E., The everyday maker: Building political rather than social capital (2001) Social Capital and Participation in Everyday Life, pp. 148-161. , P. Dekker E. Uslaner (eds). Routledge London; Barber, B.R., (1984) Strong Democracy, , University of California Press Berkeley; Beetham, D., (1991) The Legitimation of Power, , Macmillan Bastingstoke; Beetham, D., Boyle, K., (1995) Introducing Democracy, , Polity Press Cambridge; Bekkers, V., Edwards, A., Legitimacy and democracy (2007) Governance and the Democratic Deficit, pp. 35-60. , V. Bekkers G. Dijkstra A. Edwards M. Fenger (eds). Ashgate Publishing Limited Aldershot; Benhabib, S., Toward a deliberative model of democratic legitimacy (1996) Democracy and Difference: Contesting Boundaries of the Political, pp. 67-94. , S. Benhabib (eds). Princeton University Press Princeton, 