"Voss J.-P., Smith A., Grin J.","Designing long-term policy: Rethinking transition management",2009,"Policy Sciences",42,4,,275,302,,12,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72449165827&partnerID=40&md5=ba987928c9abdf1f9a21eb3e73b1c5a1","Innovation in Governance Research Group, Institute of Sociology, Technische Universität Berlin (Secretariat ER 2-2), Berlin 10623, Germany; SPRU (Science and Technology Policy Research), Freeman Centre, Falmer, University of Sussex, Brighton, East Sussex BN1 9QE, United Kingdom; Faculty of Social and Behavioural Sciences, University of Amsterdam, OZ Achterburgwal 237, Amsterdam, DL 1012, Netherlands","Voß, J.-P., Innovation in Governance Research Group, Institute of Sociology, Technische Universität Berlin (Secretariat ER 2-2), Berlin 10623, Germany; Smith, A., SPRU (Science and Technology Policy Research), Freeman Centre, Falmer, University of Sussex, Brighton, East Sussex BN1 9QE, United Kingdom; Grin, J., Faculty of Social and Behavioural Sciences, University of Amsterdam, OZ Achterburgwal 237, Amsterdam, DL 1012, Netherlands","Long-term policy is enjoying something of a come-back in connection with sustainable development. The current revival tries to avoid the pitfalls of an earlier generation of positivistic long-range planning and control approaches. Instead, this new generation of policy design emphasises reflexive governance concepts. These aim at inducing and navigating complex processes of socio-technical change by means of deliberation, probing and learning. A practical expression of this move that is attracting growing international attention amongst researchers and practitioners is the policy of 'Transition Management' (TM) in the Netherlands. This article takes stock of TM implementation experience to date and discusses the critical issues it raises for long-term policy design. The article provides a framework and synthesis for this Special Issue, which comprises articles that address a range of those issues in more depth. We highlight three critical issues: the politics of societal learning, contextual embedding of policy design and dynamics of the design process itself. This leads us to propose a view on policy design as a contested process of social innovation. Our conclusion considers implications for continued work on designing transition management in practice as well as the reflexive capacities of democratic politics. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media, LLC.","Deliberation; Innovation in governance; Long-term planning; Policy design; Politics of learning; Reflexive governance; Socio-technical change; Sustainable development; Transition management","conceptual framework; governance approach; innovation; learning; management practice; policy approach; policy implementation; policy reform; sustainable development; Netherlands",,,,,,"Arts, B., Van Tatenhove, J., Policy and power: A conceptual framework between the ""old"" and ""new"" policy idioms (2005) Policy Sciences, 37 (34), pp. 339-356; Avelino, F., Empowerment and the challenge of applying transition management to ongoing projects (2009) Policy Sciences, 42 (4), pp. 369-390; Bardach, E., (1977) The Implementation Game: What Happens after A Bill Becomes A Law, , MIT Press Cambridge, MA; Beck, U., The reinvention of politics: Towards a theory of reflexive modernization (1994) Reflexive Modernization, pp. 1-55. , U. Beck A. Giddens S. Lash (eds). Polity Press Cambridge; Berkhout, F., Smith, A., Stirling, A., Socio-technical regimes and transition contexts (2004) System Innovation the Transition to Sustainability. Theory, Evidence, and Policy, pp. 48-75. , B. Elzen F.W. Geels K. Green (eds). Cheltenham Edward Elgar; Bobrow, D., Dryzek, J.S., (1987) Policy Analysis by Design, , University of Pittsburgh Press Pittsburg, PA; Derthick, M., (1972) New Towns In-town, , The Urban Institute Washington, DC; Dewey, J., (1927) The Public and Its Problems, , Holt New York; Dienel, P., Renn, O., Planning cells: A gate