"Taylor A., Helfat C.E.","Organizational linkages for surviving technological change: Complementary assets, middle management, and ambidexterity",2009,"Organization Science",20,4,,718,739,,13,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70350025284&partnerID=40&md5=dc0aeec52390f1a956bbce6793dfa11b","Tuck School of Business, Dartmouth College, Hanover, New Hampshire 03755, United States","Taylor, A., Tuck School of Business, Dartmouth College, Hanover, New Hampshire 03755, United States; Helfat, C.E., Tuck School of Business, Dartmouth College, Hanover, New Hampshire 03755, United States","Technological innovation sometimes requires industry incumbents to shift to a completely new core technology. To successfully navigate a technological transition, firms often face the ambidextrous challenge of ""exploiting"" existing complementary assets to support the new ""exploratory"" core technology. We argue that an industry incumbent attempting to make a transition to a new technology requires linkages between organizational units responsible for developing the new technology and units in charge of complementary assets needed to commercialize the innovation. These linkages are critical but overlooked elements of organizational ambidexterity. This paper develops a conceptual framework in which the ability to build and leverage organizational linkages involving the new technology and its complementary assets is essential for a successful technological transition. The framework also highlights the importance of middle management in creating and maintaining these linkages, which are critical to dynamic capabilities in technological transitions. We identify four critical influences-economic, structural, social, and cognitive-on managerial linking activity that enable firms to transition to a new technology while utilizing valuable preexisting capabilities. The technological transitions of IBM and NCR illustrate the importance of organizational linkages and managerial linking activity. © 2009 Informs.","Ambidexterity; Cognition; Complementary assets; Exploration and exploitation; Innovation",,,,,,,"Abernathy, W.J., Utterback, J., Patterns of industrial innovation (1978) Tech. Rev., 80, pp. 40-47; Adner, R., Helfat, C.E., Corporate effects and dynamic managerial capabilities (2003) Strategic Management J, 24 (10), pp. 1011-1025; Aldrich, H.E., Herker, D., Boundary spanning roles and organization structure (1977) Acad. Management Rev., 2, pp. 217-230; Allen, T.J., (1977) Managing the Flow of Technology, , MIT Press, Cambridge, MA; Allyn, S.C., (1967) My Half Century with NCR, , McGraw-Hill, Inc., New York; Amdahl, G., Interview OH 107, by A. L. Norberg (April 16, 1986, and January 17, and April 5, 1989), Cupertino, CA. Charles Babbage Institute (1986), The Center for the History of Information Processing, University of Minnesota, MinneapolisAnderson, P.A., Tushman, M.L., Technological discontinuities and dominant designs: A cyclical model of technological change (1990) Admin. Sci. Quart., 35, pp. 604-633; Argyris, C., Empowerment: The emperor's new clothes (1998) Harvard Bus. Rev., 76 (3), pp. 98-107; Baker, W., Market networks and corporate behavior (1990) Amer. J. Sociol., 6, pp. 589-625; Bechky, B.A., Sharing meaning across occupational communities: The transformation of understanding on a production floor (2003) Organ. Sci., 14 (3), pp. 312-331; Benjamin, B.A., Podolny, J.M., Status, quality and social order in the California wine industry (1999) Admin. Sci. Quart., 44, pp. 563-589; Birkenstock, J., (1980) Interview OH 4, by R. Stuewer and E. Tomash (August 12), Stamford, CT. Charles Babbage Institute, , The Center for the History of Information Processing, University of Minnesota, Minneapolis; Blau, P.M., (1977) Inequality and Heterogeneity, , Free Press, New York; Boland R.J., Jr., Singh, J., Salipante, P., Aram, J., Fay, S.Y., Kanawattanachai, P., Knowledge representations and knowledge transfer (2001) Acad. Management J., 44, pp