"Faber A., Frenken K.","Models in evolutionary economics and environmental policy: Towards an evolutionary environmental economics",2009,"Technological Forecasting and Social Change",76,4,,462,470,,7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-62849117143&partnerID=40&md5=a25db6d4d9ecc1f8e17cb96b60c9e504","Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (MNP), P.O. Box 303, 3720 AH Bilthoven, Netherlands; Section of Economic Geography, Urban and Regional research centre Utrecht (URU), Utrecht University, P.O. Box 80115, 3508 TC Utrecht, Netherlands","Faber, A., Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (MNP), P.O. Box 303, 3720 AH Bilthoven, Netherlands; Frenken, K., Section of Economic Geography, Urban and Regional research centre Utrecht (URU), Utrecht University, P.O. Box 80115, 3508 TC Utrecht, Netherlands","In this paper we review evolutionary economic modelling in relation to environmental policy. We discuss three areas in which evolutionary economic models have a particularly high added value for environmental policy-making: the double externality problem, technological transitions and consumer demand. We explore the possibilities to apply evolutionary economic models in environmental policy assessment, including the opportunities for making policy-making endogenous to environmental innovation. We end with a critical discussion of the challenges that remain. © 2008 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.","Agent-based modelling; Environmental innovation; Evolutionary economics; Technological regime; Technological transition","Environmental protection; Agent-based modelling; Environmental innovation; Evolutionary economics; Technological regime; Technological transition; Economics; consumption behavior; demand analysis; environmental economics; environmental policy; innovation; modeling; policy making",,,,,,"Jaffe, A.B., Newell, R.G., Stavins, R.N., Environmental policy and technological change (2002) Environ. Resour. Econ., 22, pp. 41-70; van den Bergh, J.C.