"Ford J.","APC-Productivity tool or shelfware? How YOU can improve the chances for success for your MPC project",2009,"Control (Chicago, Ill)",22,4,,48,52,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67649556283&partnerID=40&md5=d066f371cf915d2140bddfd6b473ec03","Strategic Initiatives, Global Business Unit, Maverick Technologies","Ford, J., Strategic Initiatives, Global Business Unit, Maverick Technologies","Advanced process control (APC) is a mature body of engineering technology, with model-predictive control (MPC) being accepted for most continuous refining, chemical and petrochemical processes. The hierarchical approach to APC design identifies the causes of disturbances in each part of the process, and then layers solutions that deal with disturbances on top of the basic control systems. APC's main goal is to isolate operating units from process disturbances by identifying the disturbances and determine its breadth of influence. APC performance can be tracked by calculating, historizing, and displaying a variable that indicates quality of control. These solutions are supposed to make greater use of inferred properties, and will be based on the physics and chemistry of the process. The whole sub-field of APC known as transition management will become more dominant in continuous process control.",,"Advanced process control; Continuous process; Hierarchical approach; Operating units; Petrochemical process; Process disturbances; Productivity tools; Quality of controls; Transition management; Chemical plants; Hierarchical systems; Intelligent control; Model predictive control; Predictive control systems; Quality control",,,,,,,"Ford, J.; Strategic Initiatives, Global Business Unit, Maverick Technologies",,,,,,,,10495541,,,,,"English","Control (Chicago, Ill)",Article,Scopus
"Ansari S., Garud R.","Inter-generational transitions in socio-technical systems: The case of mobile communications",2009,"Research Policy",38,2,,382,392,,5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-59649129986&partnerID=40&md5=64dc557d86d08a804f7fa4e51f2940bd","Department of Strategic Management and Business Environment, RSM Erasmus University, Burg. Oudlaan 50, 3062 PA Rotterdam, Netherlands; The Pennsylvania State University, 430 Business Building, University Park, PA 16802-3603, United States","Ansari, S., Department of Strategic Management and Business Environment, RSM Erasmus University, Burg. Oudlaan 50, 3062 PA Rotterdam, Netherlands; Garud, R., The Pennsylvania State University, 430 Business Building, University Park, PA 16802-3603, United States","Many technology studies have conceptualized transitions between technological generations as a series of S-curve performance improvements over time. Surprisingly, the interregnum between successive generations has received little attention. To understand what happens in the interregnum, we study the transition from 2G to 3G in mobile communications. Our study identifies the presence of forces for both change and continuity across heterogeneous social and technical elements shaping an uneven transition between 2G and 3G mobile communications technology platforms. Unanticipated misalignments and asynchronies that emerged during the journey shifted the incentives of the various actors involved to participate. Based on these observations, we offer several conjectures as to the dynamics that can give rise to temporal discords during inter-generational technological transitions. © 2008 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Collateral technologies; Mobile communications; S-curve; Socio-technical system; Technological transitions","Communication; Technology; Time series; Collateral technologies; Mobile communications; S-curve; Socio-technical system; Technological transitions; Mobile telecommunication systems",,