"Feder T.","Spilhaus's long run at AGU helm ends",2009,"Physics Today",62,2,,28,29,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-59749102023&partnerID=40&md5=203f4b2a873c0b0f461f67b23c7680cb","American Center for Physics, One Physics Ellipse, College Park, MD 20740-3842","Feder, T., American Center for Physics, One Physics Ellipse, College Park, MD 20740-3842","Fred Spilhaus was executive director of the American Geophysical Union for nearly 40 years. He stepped down at the end of last month, but will stay involved in an emeritus role. Robert van Hook, of Transition Management Consulting Inc, is serving as interim executive director until the post is filled. Says AGU president Tim Grove, a geologist at MIT, ""The AGU is indebted to Fred for his excellent service, his leadership, and his dedication. He has really shaped the union and helped us articulate our values. We are in good shape because of Fred."" © 2009 American Institute of Physics.",,,,,,,,,"Feder, T.; American Center for Physics, One Physics Ellipse, College Park, MD 20740-3842",,,,,,,,00319228,,PHTOA,10.1063/1.3086094,,"English","Physics Today",Article,Scopus
"Kuhn S.L., Stiner M.C., Gulec E., Ozer I., Yilmaz H., Baykara I., Acikkol A., Goldberg P., Molina K.M., Unay E., Suata-Alpaslan F.","The early Upper Paleolithic occupations at Üçaǧi{dotless}zli{dotless} Cave (Hatay, Turkey)",2009,"Journal of Human Evolution",56,2,,87,113,,18,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58649116695&partnerID=40&md5=a0b8a0459e79b88904418139008feaa5","Department of Anthropology, University of Arizona, P.O. Box 210030, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States; Antropoloji (Paleoantropoloji) Bölümü, Dil ve Tarih-Coǧrafya Fakültesi, Ankara Üniversitesi, 06100 Sihhiye, Ankara, Turkey; Department of Archaeology, Boston University, Boston, MA 02215, United States; Àrea de Prehistòria, Universitat Rovira i Virgili, Plaça Imperial Tarraco 1, 43005 Tarragona, Spain; Cumhuriyet Üniversitesi, Fen-Edebiyat Fakültesi, Antropoloji Bölümü, 58140 Sivas, Turkey","Kuhn, S.L., Department of Anthropology, University of Arizona, P.O. Box 210030, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States; Stiner, M.C., Department of Anthropology, University of Arizona, P.O. Box 210030, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States; Güleç, E., Antropoloji (Paleoantropoloji) Bölümü, Dil ve Tarih-Coǧrafya Fakültesi, Ankara Üniversitesi, 06100 Sihhiye, Ankara, Turkey; Özer, I., Antropoloji (Paleoantropoloji) Bölümü, Dil ve Tarih-Coǧrafya Fakültesi, Ankara Üniversitesi, 06100 Sihhiye, Ankara, Turkey; Yilmaz, H., Antropoloji (Paleoantropoloji) Bölümü, Dil ve Tarih-Coǧrafya Fakültesi, Ankara Üniversitesi, 06100 Sihhiye, Ankara, Turkey; Baykara, I., Antropoloji (Paleoantropoloji) Bölümü, Dil ve Tarih-Coǧrafya Fakültesi, Ankara Üniversitesi, 06100 Sihhiye, Ankara, Turkey; Açikkol, A., Cumhuriyet Üniversitesi, Fen-Edebiyat Fakültesi, Antropoloji Bölümü, 58140 Sivas, Turkey; Goldberg, P., Department of Archaeology, Boston University, Boston, MA 02215, United States; Molina, K.M., Àrea de Prehistòria, Universitat Rovira i Virgili, Plaça Imperial Tarraco 1, 43005 Tarragona, Spain; Ünay, E., Cumhuriyet Üniversitesi, Fen-Edebiyat Fakültesi, Antropoloji Bölümü, 58140 Sivas, Turkey; Suata-Alpaslan, F., Cumhuriyet Üniversitesi, Fen-Edebiyat Fakültesi, Antropoloji Bölümü, 58140 Sivas, Turkey","This paper summarizes results from excavations at Üçaǧi{dotless}zli{dotless} Cave (Hatay, Turkey) between 1999 and 2002 and 2005. This collapsed karstic chamber contains a sequence of early Upper Paleolithic deposits that span an interval between roughly 29,000 and 41,000 (uncalibrated) radiocarbon years BP. Lithic assemblages can be assigned to two major chronostratigraphic units. The earliest assemblages correspond with the Initial Upper Paleolithic, whereas the most recent ones fit within the definition of the Ahmarian. Substantial assemblages of stone tools, vertebrate faunal remains, ornaments, osseous artifacts, and other cultural materials provide an unusually varied picture of human behavior during the earliest phases of the Upper Paleolithic in the northern Levant. The sequence at Üçaǧi{dotless}zli{dotless} Cave documents the technological transition between Initial Upper Paleolithic and Ahmarian, with a high degree of continuity in foraging and technological activities. The sequence also documents major shifts in occupational intensity and mobility. © 2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Ahmarian; Bone tools; Early Upper Paleolithic; Late Pleistocene; Mediterranean; Prey choice; shell ornaments; Turkey; Use wear; Zooarchaeology","archaeological evidence; archaeology; artifact; documentary source; historical perspective; Paleolithic; settlement history; tool use; animal; archeology; article; evolution; fossil; history; hominid; human; occupation; paleontology; physical anthropology; radiometry; Turkey (republic); Animals; Archaeology; Evolution; Fossils; History, Ancient; Hominidae; Humans; Occupations; Paleodontology; Paleontology; Radiometric Dating; Turkey; Eurasia; Hatay; Levant; Mediterranean Region; Mediterranean Sea; Turkey; Meleagris gallopavo; Vertebrata",,,,,,"Açi{