"Chappin E.J.L., Dijkema G.P.J.","Agent-based modeling of energy infrastructure transitions",2008,"2008 1st International Conference on Infrastructure Systems and Services: Building Networks for a Brighter Future, INFRA 2008",,, 5439580,,,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77952402904&partnerID=40&md5=6ac82704183568dadaaa5283e5ff3d3f","Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, P.O. Box 5015, 2600 GA Delft, Netherlands; Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, Netherlands","Chappin, E.J.L., Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, P.O. Box 5015, 2600 GA Delft, Netherlands; Dijkema, G.P.J., Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, Netherlands","Transitions emerge over time as fundamental change of large-scale socio-technical systems such as energy infrastructures that are the backbone of society. To date, however, the body-of-knowledge on energy infrastructure transitions is largely descriptive. Transition management, however, does have a prescriptive character - not only can we understand transitions, we can also shape them. This implies technical system design is augmented with policy, regulation, R&D strategies: some coherent all-inclusive set of transition instruments or transition assemblage. We conjecture a transition management strategy may equate to collaborative design of such a transition assemblage. Using foundations of complex systems theory, agent-based modeling, engineering and policy design scenario analysis, design of experiments and statistical data analysis, a modeling framework has been developed that enables ex-ante assessment of alternative transition assemblage design-alternatives.",,"Agent-based modeling; Collaborative design; Complex systems; Energy infrastructures; Fundamental changes; Modeling frameworks; Policy design; Scenario analysis; Sociotechnical systems; Statistical data analysis; Technical systems; Transition management; Design of experiments",,,,,,"Geels, F., (2002) Understanding the Dynamics of Technological Transitions, , vol. PhD. Enschede: University of Twente; Geels, F.W., From sectoral systems of innovation to socio-technical systems insights about dynamics and change from sociology and institutional theory (2004) Research Policy, 33, pp. 897-920; (2004) Transitiemanagement: Sleutel Voor Een Duurzame Samenleving, , Rotmans, Assen: Van Gorcum; Rotmans, J., Kemp, R., Asselt, M.V., Geels, F., Verbong, G., Molendijk, K., Transities & transitiemanegement: De casus van emissiearme energievoorziening (2000) International Centre for Integrated Studies (ICIS) and Maastricht Economic Research Institute on Innovation and Technology (MERIT), Maastricht; Chappin, E.J.L., Dijkema, G.P.J., Towards The assessment of policy impacts on system transitions in Energy 31st IAEE International Conference, Bridging Energy Supply and Demand: Logistics, , Presented at, Competition and Environment, Istanbul, Turkey, submitted; Chappin, E.J.L., Dijkema, G.P.J., On the design of system transitions - Is transition management in the Energy domain feasible? Presented at IEEE IEMC: International Engineering Management Conference, Estoril, Portugal, Submitted; Herder, P.M., Bouwmans, I., Dijkema, G.P.J., Stikkelman, R.M., Weijnen, M.P.C., Designing infrastructures using a complex systems perspective (2008) Journal of Design Research, , to be published in; Nikolic, I., Dijkema, G.P.J., Dam, K.H.V., Understanding and shaping the evolution of sustainable large-scale socio-technical systems, towards a framework for action oriented industrial ecology Dynamics of Industrial Ecosystems, , Reviewed and accepted, in print; Hughes, T.P., The evolution of large technological systems (1987) The Social Construction of Technological Systems: New Directions in the Soc