"Nooteboom S.","Governance for sustainable development",2008,"2008 1st International Conference on Infrastructure Systems and Services: Building Networks for a Brighter Future, INFRA 2008",,, 5439646,,,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77952391036&partnerID=40&md5=3c083425167c8d81912e96583cf13283","Erasmus University, PO Box 1738, NL-3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands; DHV, Amersfoort, Netherlands","Nooteboom, S., Erasmus University, PO Box 1738, NL-3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands, DHV, Amersfoort, Netherlands","Theory of adaptive networks is applied to the Dutch policy making process about sustainable transport. In the Netherlands the intended policy approach has been termed 'transition management'. Political leaders and business leaders have looked for innovative solutions for wicked problems. They were prepared to develop trust by separating joint knowledge building from powering. Adaptive networks and power networks emerged as ideal types. The tension between both attracted change. The iteration between adaptive (reflexive, learning) interactions and power interactions leads to different, more sustainable outcomes, since the justification of policies is based on more complex ideas.",,"Adaptive networks; Business leaders; Innovative solutions; Knowledge building; Netherlands; Policy approach; Policy making; Power networks; Sustainable outcomes; Sustainable transport; Transition management; Wicked problems; Strategic planning; Sustainable development",,,,,,"(2001) Ministry of Housing, Spatial Planning and the Environment, , VROM Fourth National Environmental Policy Plan, Sdu: The Hague; Nooteboom, S.G., Adaptive networks (2006) The Governance of Sustainable Development, , Eburon, Delft; Teisman, G.R., (2005) Public Management on the Edge of Chaos and Order; About Leadership and Organizing in Complexity, , Dutch Publiek management op de grens van chaos en orde - Over leidinggeven en. organiseren in complexiteit, Academic Service: The Hague; Loorbach,