"Chappin E.J.L., Dijkema G.P.J.","On the design of system transitions is transition management in the energy domain feasible?",2008,"IEMC-Europe 2008 - 2008 IEEE International Engineering Management Conference, Europe: Managing Engineering, Technology and Innovation for Growth",,, 4617998,,,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-53149149080&partnerID=40&md5=4539d7e803c8c6f3f5a11edbd3dbe603","Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, P.O. Box 5015, 2600 GA Delft, Netherlands; Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology","Chappin, E.J.L., Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology, P.O. Box 5015, 2600 GA Delft, Netherlands; Dijkema, G.P.J., Energy and Industry Group, Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, Delft University of Technology","The primary objective of Transition Management appears to be 'to manage transitions towards sustainability.' The emerging body-of-knowledge on system transitions to date remains largely descriptive, however. We propose a research agenda to develop a prescriptive system transition body-ofknowledge, which eventually will provide handles for policy makers to push and pull transitions. This agenda is developed by focusing on energy systems. We conjecture it is always sociotechnical systems that are the subject of transition. We define a system transition as a structural change in both technical and social subsystems. We conclude that shared definitions must be developed of indicators of sustainability performance of systems in transition. Secondly, an understanding and recognition of the socio-technical design space is required. The design space for energy systems includes technological structure and content, policy, regulation and market design and social innovation. The combination and interrelation of these must be recognized and its use suitably underpinned, for example by exploratory simulation models and games that would allow ex-ante testing of transition policies and management. © 2008 IEEE.","Energy; Simulation modeling and gaming; System transition; Transition Management","Design; Management; Models; Sustainable development; Technological forecasting; Energy; Simulation modeling and gaming; System transition; Transition Management; Innovation",,,,,,"Rotmans, (2004) Transitie management: Sleutel voor een duurzame samenleving, , Assen: Van Gorcum; Rotmans, J., Kemp, R., Asselt, M.V., Geels, F., Verbong, G., Molendijk, K., (2000) Transities & Transitiemanegement: De casus van emissiearme energivoorziening, , International Centre for Integrated Studies (ICIS) and Maastricht Economic Research Institute on Innovation and Technology MERIT, Maastricht; Geels, F.W., Processes and patterns in transitions and system innovations: Refining the co-evolutionary multi-level perspective (2005) Technological Forecasting & Social Change, 72, pp. 681-696; Dijkema, G.P.J., (2004) Process System Innovation by Design, , Delft: Delft University of Technology; Ehrlich, P.R., Holdren, J.P., Impact of population growth (1971) Science, 171, pp. 1212-1217; Ehrlich, P.R., Holdren, J.P., One-dimensional economy (1972) Bull At Sci, 28, pp. 16-27; Working Group III (2001) Climate change 2001: Mitigation, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, Cambridge; New York: Published for the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change [by] Cambridge University Press; Working Group III (2007) Climate Change 2007: Mitigation of Climate Change Summary for Policymakers, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, Geneva: IPCC; (1998) Kyoto Protocol to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, , UNFCCC; More with Energy, Opportunities for the Netherlands (2006) SenterNovem, , Task Force Energietransitie, Utrecht; Ministerie van Economische Zaken, Nu voor later, Energierapport 2005, Ministerie van Economische Zaken