"Williams P.","Transition and people with learning disabilities: Reflections on the quality of content that emerges from the process of involving service users in information provision",2008,"Aslib Proceedings: New Information Perspectives",60,5,,474,492,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-52349088826&partnerID=40&md5=68d4581b38d9eff23e8772f604bc0d59","Rix Centre, University of East London, Docklands Campus, University Way, London, United Kingdom","Williams, P., Rix Centre, University of East London, Docklands Campus, University Way, London, United Kingdom","Purpose - The paper's purpose is to describe the information content of web sites developed by and for people with learning disabilities around the theme of transition from school to adulthood. Design/methodology/approach - The paper adopts a content analysis approach, in which subject experts evaluate user-generated content produced as part of a project on inclusion and people with learning disabilities. Findings - Despite being only one theme of a number pertaining to transition, leisure, entertainment and hobby-related information dominated the web sites. Other issues elicited included that of writing about one's personal experiences providing limited information of use to others, the key role of carers/supporters in information provision, and some material being too difficult for people with learning disabilities to understand. Practical implications - The paper shows that for the information service to be valuable and relevant to the target audience, much training and considerable time investment are required for both people with learning disabilities and their supporters. The practice of creating and uploading information on to the web site holds benefits to the creator beyond mere information provision. Originality/value - The development of information services for people with learning disabilities by the service users themselves is an important innovation. This paper points out how such an inclusive approach could work in the future. © Emerald Group Publishing Limited.","Disabled people; Information facilities; Internet; Learning disabilities; Leisure facilitites; Transition management","Education; Information retrieval; Information science; Information services; Internet; World Wide Web; Content-analysis; Design/methodology/approach; Disabled people; Information contents; Information facilities; Information provisioning; Learning disabilities; Leisure facilitites; Limited information; Personal experiences; Practical implications; Service users; Target audience; Transition management; User-generated contents; Web site; Quality of service",,,,,,"Aspis, S., Self-advocacy for people with learning difficulties: Does it have a future? (1997) Journal of Disability & Society, 12 (4), pp. 647-54; Bartlett, C., Bunning, K., The importance of communication partnerships: A study to investigate the communicative exchanges between staff and adults with learning disabilities (1997) British Journal of Learning Disabilities, 25 (4), pp. 148-53; Bradshaw, J., Complexity of staff communication and reported level of understanding skills in adults with intellectual disability (2001) Journal of Intellectual Disability Research, 45 (3), pp. 233-43; Broome, G., Automated testing - How useful is it? (2005) Guild of Accessible Web Designers Website, , available at: www.gawds.org/show.php?contentid = 147 (accessed 24 March 2008); Burke, A., McMillan, J., Cummins, L., Thompson, A., Forsyth, W., Setting up participatory research: A discussion of the initial stages (2003) British Journal of Learning Disabilities, 31 (2), pp. 65-9; Equalise It A Manifesto for Disability Equality in Development Cooperation, , available at: www.disabilityequality.org/downloads/Equalise%201%21.doc (accessed 4 June 2008); (2001) Valuing People: A New Strategy for Learning Disability for the 21st Century, , White Paper The Stationary Office London available at: www.archive.official-documents.co.uk