"Setzer T., Bhattacharya K., Ludwig H.","Decision support for service transition management: Enforce change scheduling by performing change risk and business impact analysis",2008,"NOMS 2008 - IEEE/IFIP Network Operations and Management Symposium: Pervasive Management for Ubiquitous Networks and Services",,, 4575135,200,207,,4,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-51849131654&partnerID=40&md5=5d69a7b88ed0c9ea6ef186485e13f826","Technische Universität München, Department of Internet-based Information Systems, 85748 Garching, Germany; IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Business-driven IT Management, 19 Skyline Dr., Hawthorne, NY-10532, United States","Setzer, T., Technische Universität München, Department of Internet-based Information Systems, 85748 Garching, Germany; Bhattacharya, K., IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Business-driven IT Management, 19 Skyline Dr., Hawthorne, NY-10532, United States; Ludwig, H., IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, Business-driven IT Management, 19 Skyline Dr., Hawthorne, NY-10532, United States","In IT Service Delivery, alignment of service infrastructures to continuously changing business requirements is a primary cost driver, all the more as most severe service disruptions can be attributed to poor change impact and risk assessment. An IT service, defined as a means to provide value to a consumer, may be realized by a network of shared application and other resources that are invoked in the context of business processes. In the spirit of Service-Oriented Architecture (SOA) we consider each application or resource as a service. Changing services or service definitions in such an environment includes exceptionally high risk and complexity, as various business processes might depend on a service. In this paper we propose a model for analyzing the business impact of operational risks resulting from change related service downtimes of uncertain duration. The proposed solution takes into account the network of dependencies between services where services may or may not be realized through business processes. Based on the analytical model, we derive decision models in terms of deterministic and probabilistic mathematical programming formulations to schedule single or multiple correlated changes efficiently. Preliminary experiments are described to illustrate the efficiency of the proposed models. Using these decisions models, organizations can schedule service changes with the lowest expected impact on the business. ©2008 IEEE.","Business impact analysis; Business-driven IT management; Change management; Change scheduling; Service transition management; Service-oriented architectures","Chlorine compounds; Decentralized control; Decision support systems; Information services; Information technology; Management; Mathematical programming; Production control; Risk analysis; Risk assessment; Risk management; Safety engineering; Scheduling; Ubiquitous computing; Analytical modelling; Business impact; Business impact analysis; Business processes; Business requirements; Business-driven IT management; Change management; Change scheduling; Cost drivers; Decision modeling; Decision supports; Network operations; Operational risks; Service delivery; Service disruptions; Service transition management; Service-Oriented Architecture; Service-oriented architectures; Transition management; Ubiquitous networks; Network management",,,,,,"Change Control Management, , http://www.crm2day.com/news/crm/118482.php, CRM Today:, URL; Office of Government Commerce: ITIL Service Support. The Stationery Office, London, 2000www.ibm.com/software/tivoli/products/ccmdb, IBM Tivoli Change and Configuration Management Database, URL(2007) Management of Risk: Guidance for Practioneers, , Office of Government Commerce:, The Stationery Office, London; Kaplan, S., Garrick, B.J., On the Quantitative Definition of Risk (1981) Risk Analysis, 1; OGC's, Official ITIL Website, , http://www.best-management-practice.com/IT-Service-Management-