"Park J.-S., Chunag A., Gelegdorj E.","A technological transition in Mongolia evident in microstructure, chemical composition and radiocarbon age of cast iron artifacts",2008,"Journal of Archaeological Science",35,9,,2465,2470,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-47249107269&partnerID=40&md5=1767eccb02eda6a27624bc358ee2262b","Department of Metallurgical Engineering, Hongik University, Chochiwon, Choongnam, 339-701, South Korea; Institute of Archaeology, Mongolian Academy of Sciences, Ulaanbaatar 51, Mongolia; Seoul National University, Seoul, 151-745, South Korea; The National Museum of Mongolian History, Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia","Park, J.-S., Department of Metallurgical Engineering, Hongik University, Chochiwon, Choongnam, 339-701, South Korea; Chunag, A., Institute of Archaeology, Mongolian Academy of Sciences, Ulaanbaatar 51, Mongolia; Gelegdorj, E., Seoul National University, Seoul, 151-745, South Korea, The National Museum of Mongolian History, Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia","Metallurgical examination of cast iron objects from the Khitan period (AD 10th-12th) in Mongolia shows that they might be classified into two groups. The first is based on Fe-C alloys of near eutectic composition and the second is based on Fe-C-Si alloys with reduced carbon content and numerous sulfide inclusions. By contrast, all the objects from the succeeding Mongolian empire period (AD 12th-15th) belong to the second group, indicating that a technological transition had occurred during the Khitan period. Accelerator mass spectrometry (AMS) on carbon samples extracted from artifacts in both groups and measurement of alloy compositions suggest that the use of mineral coal in smelting was a major factor for this transition. © 2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Cast iron; Chemical composition; Microstructure; Mineral coal; Mongolia; Radiocarbon age; Technological transition","alloy; artifact; chemical composition; metallurgy; microstructure; radiocarbon dating; technological 