"Tripsas M.","Customer preference discontinuities: A trigger for radical technological change",2008,"Managerial and Decision Economics",29,2-3,,79,97,,9,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-41449109728&partnerID=40&md5=a8601f1eff14906992167311203d818a","Harvard Business School, MA, United States; Harvard Business School, 219 Rock Center, Soldiers Field Road, Boston, MA 02163, United States","Tripsas, M., Harvard Business School, MA, United States, Harvard Business School, 219 Rock Center, Soldiers Field Road, Boston, MA 02163, United States","What factors cause a mature industry to re-enter a period of technological turbulence? This paper addresses this question by developing a model of technological evolution that incorporates both technological trajectories and a new concept: preference trajectories, which are cycles of incremental and discontinuous change in preferences. Preference discontinuities turn out to play an important role in triggering technological transitions in an industry. I illustrate the model with an historical study of the typesetter industry, which underwent three major technological transitions, each of which was driven by preference discontinuities. Copyright © 2007 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.",,,,,,,,"Abernathy, W.J., (1978) The Productivity Dilemma, , Johns Hopkins University Press: Baltimore; Abernathy, W.J., Clark, K.B., Innovation: Mapping the winds of creative destruction (1985) Research Policy, 14, pp. 3-22; Abernathy, W.J., Utterback, J.M., Patterns of industrial innovation (1978) Technology Review, 80 (7), pp. 40-47; Adner, R., When are technologies disruptive? A demand-based view of the emergence of competition (2002) Strategic Management Journal, 23, pp. 667-688; Adner, R., Levinthal, D., Demand heterogeneity and technology evolution: Implications for product and process innovation (2001) Management Science, 47, pp. 611-628; Agarwal, R., Gort, M., The evolution of markets and entry, exit and survival of firms (1996) Revi