"Janicke M.","Ecological modernisation: new perspectives",2008,"Journal of Cleaner Production",16,5,,557,565,,37,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-36448962742&partnerID=40&md5=0669e17bae427938456e3d22f87ffc1d","Environmental Policy Research Center, Freie Universitaet Berlin, Ihnestrasse 22, D-14195 Berlin, Germany","Jänicke, M., Environmental Policy Research Center, Freie Universitaet Berlin, Ihnestrasse 22, D-14195 Berlin, Germany","""Ecological modernisation"" - understood as systematic eco-innovation and its diffusion - has by far the largest potential to achieve environmental improvements. In general, the market logic of modernisation and competition for innovation combined with the market potential of global environmental needs serve as important driving forces behind ""ecological modernisation"". In recent times, however, additional factors like rising energy prices or fears from climate change have favoured the rise of this innovation-based approach to environmental policy. The article deals with two special driving forces: first, there is growing evidence for the importance of ""smart"" environmental regulation. Secondly, the increasingly complex actor constellation of global environmental governance leads to mounting business risks for polluters and thereby exerts pressure for eco-innovation. Despite these favourable framework conditions, the strategy of ""ecological modernisation"" nonetheless faces a number of inherent limitations. These include the unavailability of marketable technological solutions for relevant environmental problems like the loss of species, the rebound effect neutralising the incremental environmental improvements through economic growth (the dilemma of the ""N-curve"") as well as resistance by ""modernisation losers"". Against this background, structural solutions seem indispensable. Here, eco-innovations should be supported by transition management or ecological structural policy. © 2007 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Eco-innovation; Ecological modernisation; Energy prices; Global environmental governance; Smart environmental regulations","Climate change; Competition; Diffusion; Environmental protection; Problem solving; Business risks; Ecological modernisation; Energy prices; Environmental policy; Global environmental governance; Smart environmental regulations; Ecology",,,,,,"(1997) European environmental policy - the pioneers, , Andersen M.S., and Liefferink D. (Eds), Manchester University Press, Manchester, New York; Ashford, N.A., Ayers, C., Stone, R.F., Using regulation to change the market for innovation (1985) Harvard Environmental Law Review, 9 (2), pp. 419-466; Ashford, N.A., Government and innovation in Europe and North America (2002) American Behavioral Scientist, 45 (9), pp. 1417-1434; (2000) Green industrial restructuring - international case studies and theoretical interpretations, , Binder M., Petschow U., and Jänicke M. (Eds), Springer-Verlag, Berlin, Heidelberg, New York; Cohen, M.J., Science and the environment: assessing cultural capacity for ecological modernisation (1998) Public Understanding of Science, 7, pp. 149-167; Deutsch, K.W., (1963) The nerves of government: models of political communication and control, , Free Press, New York; Drezner, D.W., Globalization and policy convergence (2001) The International Studies Review, 3 (1), pp. 53-78; (2006) Eco-industry, its size, employment, perspectives and barriers to growth (final report), , EC - DG Environment, Brussels, European Commission/Ernst and Young; Foljanty-Jost, G., (1995) Ökonomie und Ökologie in Japan. Politik zwischen Wachstum und Umweltschutz, , Leske + Budrich, Opladen; International Energy Agency (IEA), (2003) World energy investment outlook, , IEA, Paris; Jacob, K., Beise, M., Blazejczak, J., Edler, D., Haum, R., Jänicke, M., (2005) Lead markets for environmental innovations, , Physica, Heidelberg; Jänicke, M., Jörgens, H., Neue Steuerungskonzepte in der Umweltpolitik (2004) Zeits