"Shim D.-S., Yang C.-K., Park J.-W., Chang S.","Hierarchical position control of expedition robots",2007,"Proceedings of the SICE Annual Conference",,, 4420978,208,215,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-50249090342&partnerID=40&md5=73d68c59b3e9d279e354f20ab1e2fdb7","School of Electrical and Electronics Engineering, Chung-Ang University, Seoul, South Korea; Department of Electrical Engineering, Yuhan College, Gyeonggi-do, South Korea","Shim, D.-S., School of Electrical and Electronics Engineering, Chung-Ang University, Seoul, South Korea; Yang, C.-K., Department of Electrical Engineering, Yuhan College, Gyeonggi-do, South Korea; Park, J.-W., School of Electrical and Electronics Engineering, Chung-Ang University, Seoul, South Korea; Chang, S., School of Electrical and Electronics Engineering, Chung-Ang University, Seoul, South Korea","Position control of expedition robots are considered. The robots are controlled to follow pre-determined paths via fixed way-points. The speed and heading are controlled to follow reference values calculated from the next way point and current position. Hybrid control is used for speed loop and heading loop, respectively. Depending on the parameter change of speed and heading model due to unexpected situation such as fault or road condition, an appropriate controller is selected by transition management. For speed loop, PID control, adaptive PI control, and neural network are used. For direction, PID control, adaptive PID control are used. Transition management selects an appropriate controller after the parameter estimation. © 2007 SICE.","Expedition robot; Hierarchical control; Hybrid control; Open control platform; Transition management","Neural networks; Parameter estimation; Position control; Proportional control systems; Robotics; Robots; Speed; Three term control systems; Time varying control systems; Two term control systems; Annual conference; Control engineers; Expedition robot; Hierarchical control; Hybrid c