"Straus L.G., Morales M.R.G.","Further radiocarbon dates for the upper paleolithic of el mirón cave (Ramales De La Victoria, Cantabria, Spain)",2007,"Radiocarbon",49,3,,1205,1214,,8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-57849154544&partnerID=40&md5=934c982281856d4fb5da67b02b0515d5","Department of Anthropology, MSC01 1040, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131-0001, United States; Instituto Internacional de Investigaciones Prehistóricas, Universidad de Cantabria, Avda. de los Castros, 39005 Santander, Spain","Straus, L.G., Department of Anthropology, MSC01 1040, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131-0001, United States; Morales, M.R.G., Instituto Internacional de Investigaciones Prehistóricas, Universidad de Cantabria, Avda. de los Castros, 39005 Santander, Spain","This article expands the date list from the Stone Age cave site of El Mirón in the Cantabrian Cordillera of northern Spain to a total of 62 radiocarbon determinations, one of the longest series from a single prehistoric site in Iberia. All the assays (accelerator mass spectrometry [AMS] and conventional, run on charcoal and bone collagen) were done by a single laboratory (Geochron, GX). The 11 new dates confirm 1) the late spread of Neolithic economy and technology into the Atlantic environment of Cantabrian Spain by about 4500 cal BC; 2) the horizontally extensive, but not intensive, use of the whole cave vestibule by Upper Magdalenian foragers about 12,000-14,000 cal BC; 3) extensive and very intensive, repeated occupations of the cave during the Middle and Lower Cantabrian Magdalenian about 14,200-17,000 cal BC; and 4) a long, gradual technological transition from the Solutrean to the Archaic Magdalenian between about 20,000-17,000 cal BC. El Mirón joins a list of culturally very rich, frequently occupied, Lower Magdalenian residential hub sites-most of the rest of which (including Altamira) are located in the coastal lowlands of Cantabria-which have yielded distinctive red deer scapulae that are decorated with striated engraved images of game animals (mainly red deer hinds), now most precisely dated at El Mirón between 16,200-17,200 cal BC. © 2007 by the Arizona Board of Regents on behalf of the University of Arizona.",,"Animalia; Cervus elaphus",,,,,,"Alday Ruiz, A., The transition between the last huntergatherers and the first farmers in southwestern Europe: The Basque perspective (2005) Journal of Anthropological Research, 61 (4), pp. 469-94; Altuna, J., Cuenca, G., Elorza, M., García, J., Lobo, J., Mariezkurrena, K., Pérez, M., Straus, L.G., Post-Pleistocene faunas from the archaeological site of El Mirón Cave: A preliminary summary (2002) Miscelánea En Homenaje a Emilio Aguirre, 2, pp. 40-49. , In: Baquedano E, Rubio S, editors, (Zona Arqueológica 4), Alcalá: Museo Arqueológico Regional; Arias, P., The origins of the Neolithic along the Atlantic coast of continental Europe: A survey (1999) Journal of World Prehistory, 13 (4), pp. 403-64; Barandiarán, I., Datation C14 de l'art mobilier magdalénien cantabrique (1988) Bulletin De La Société Préhistorique Ariège-Pyrénées, 43, pp. 63-84; Bernaldo de Quirós, F., Cabrera Valdés, V., Cronología del arte paleolítico (1994) Complutum, 5, pp. 265-76. , In Spanish; Cattelain, P., Propulseurs magdaléniens: Marqueurs culturels régionaux? (2005) Industrie Osseuse Et Parures Du Solutréen Au Magdalénien En Europe, 39, pp. 301-17. , In: Dujardin V, editor., Paris: Mémoires de la Société Préhistorique Française, In French; Conkey, M.W., The identification of prehistoric huntergatherer aggregation sites: The case of Altamira (1980) Current Anthropology, 21 (5), pp. 609-30; Corchón, M., Europa 16500-14000 a.C.: Un lenguaje común (2005) La Materia Del Lenguaje Prehistórico. Santander, pp. 105-26. , In: Arias P, Ontañón R, editors, Gobierno de Cantabria, In Spanish; Freeman, L., González Echegaray, J., The Magdalenian site of El Juyo (Cantabria, Spain) (1995) Artistic Documents In Context. Bolleti