"Khan M.S., Iravani M.R.","Supervisory hybrid control of a micro grid system",2007,"2007 IEEE Canada Electrical Power Conference, EPC 2007",,, 4520300,20,24,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-49249133199&partnerID=40&md5=8d54873295c9192acab3ecb92d8da875","IEEE; Energy Systems Group, Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, University of Toronto","Khan, M.S., IEEE, Energy Systems Group, Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, University of Toronto; Iravani, M.R., IEEE, Energy Systems Group, Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, University of Toronto","This paper presents a systematic approach for the design and analysis of a supervisory hybrid control scheme for a micro grid system using hybrid control techniques. A generic micro grid configuration is assumed. The approach is elaborated with a specific micro grid configuration containing a self-excited induction machine based wind energy conversion system. By definition a micro grid operates in both grid-connected and in isolated modes. In each mode of operation there could be different combinations of the available energy sources in the system that are catering to the load demand. A hybrid control scheme which utilizes different control mechanisms for optimal control of a system under different operating conditions and in different operating states, presents an attractive paradigm for the control design of such a system. By partitioning a micro grid into different modules along suitable axis, the complexity of a Multiple Input Multiple Output (MIMO) control problem of the system can be significantly reduced. The control of the different modules of a micro grid system can then be tackled using the well established linear control theory which could then be combined using suitable transition, load and power management strategies to achieve optimal control of the micro grid system in all its desirable operating states. Supervisory hybrid control of a wind energy conversion and storage system is presented to illustrate the supervisory hybrid control design and analysis philosophy outlined in this paper. © 2007 IEEE.","Finite hybrid automata; Micro grid; Supervisory hybrid control; Transition management; Wind energy conversion system","Control designs; Control mechanisms; Control problems; Design and analysis; Different operating conditions; Electrical power; Energy sourcing; Finite hybrid automata; Grid-connected; Hybrid control; Hybrid control design; Hybrid control scheme; Induction machines; Isolated modes; Linear control theory; Load demand; Micro grid; Micro grids; Mode of operations; Multiple input multiple output MIMO); Operating states; Optimal control; Power management strategies; Storage systems; Supervisory hybrid control; Systematic approaches; Transition management; Wind energy conversion; Wind energy conversion system; Automation; Cellular radio systems; Chlorine compounds; Control system analysis; Crack propagation; Electric power supplies to apparatus; Energy conversion; Energy management; Energy storage; Intersections; Linear control systems; Machine design; MIM devices; Philosophical aspects; Wind power; Control theory",,,,,,"Larsen, H., Petersen, L.S., (2002) New and Emerging Technologies - Options for the Future, , Riso: Energy Report 1, Riso National Laboratory, Denmark, Oct; J. Aabakken, W. Short, Domestic Energy Scenarios, US National Renewable Energy Laboratory's Technical Report 'NREL/TP-620-32742', Jan. 2003Lee, T.-T., Chun-Fei Hsu, S.L., Robust Hybrid Control for Antilock Braking Systerns (2003) (IEEE Intl. Conference, on Systems, 1, pp. 84-89. , Man and Cybernetics; Kohn, W., Remmel, J.B., Nerod, A., James, J., Multiple Agent Hybrid Control for Manufacturing Systems (1996) (IEEE International Symposium on Intelligent Control, pp. 348-353; Jeyaraman, S., Tsourdos, A., Zbikowski, R., White, B., Bruyere, L., Formalized Hybrid Control Scheme for a UAV Group using Dubins Set and Model Checking (2004) (43rd