"Ferri B.H., Perrin N., Ferri A.","Adaptive length HR filters implemented with imprecise computing",2007,"Proceedings of the American Control Conference",,, 4283103,2887,2892,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-46449091472&partnerID=40&md5=b8842c6dc727550848420c5a222fadb4","School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; George Woodruff School of Mechanical Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States","Ferri, B.H., School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; Perrin, N., School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; Ferri, A., George Woodruff School of Mechanical Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States","This paper explores the use of imprecise computing to implement adaptive length NR filters in order to meet real-time constraints. An adaptive-length filter can provide a resource manager with alternatives that can be used if resources become scarce. This paper discusses the use of standard IIR filters used in controls applications, such as a Butterworth filter, and how this filter can be implemented in prioritized stages that can be skipped if necessary. The paper also examines the use of filter banks with different size filters. In both cases, transition management methods such as bumpless transfer are investigated to mitigate the transients induced when switching between filters. © 2007 IEEE.",,"Bumpless transfer; Butterworth filtering; Different sizes; In order; Real-time constraints; resource managers; Transition management; Filter banks; IIR filters; Standards; Wave filters",,,,,,"Murthy, C.S.R., Manimaran, G., (2001) Resource Management in Real-Time Systems and Networks, , MIT Press, Cambridge, MA; Bartha, S., Gabriel, Z., Mezofi, L., Péceli, G., Signal Proce