"Inoue H., Ikeno A., Abe T., Sakai J., Edahiro M.","Dynamic security domain scaling on symmetric multiprocessors for future high-end embedded systems",2007,"CODES+ISSS 2007: International Conference on Hardware/Software Codesign and System Synthesis",,,,39,44,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38849196107&partnerID=40&md5=4db78d7e7b2555743d3f01489d668d16","System IP Core Research Laboratories, NEC Corporation, 1120, Shimokuzawa, Sagamihara, Kanagawa, 229-1198, Japan; NEC Informatec Systems, Ltd., 3-2-1, Sakado, Takatsu-ku, Kawasaki, Kanagawa, 213-0012, Japan","Inoue, H., System IP Core Research Laboratories, NEC Corporation, 1120, Shimokuzawa, Sagamihara, Kanagawa, 229-1198, Japan; Ikeno, A., NEC Informatec Systems, Ltd., 3-2-1, Sakado, Takatsu-ku, Kawasaki, Kanagawa, 213-0012, Japan; Abe, T., System IP Core Research Laboratories, NEC Corporation, 1120, Shimokuzawa, Sagamihara, Kanagawa, 229-1198, Japan; Sakai, J., System IP Core Research Laboratories, NEC Corporation, 1120, Shimokuzawa, Sagamihara, Kanagawa, 229-1198, Japan; Edahiro, M., System IP Core Research Laboratories, NEC Corporation, 1120, Shimokuzawa, Sagamihara, Kanagawa, 229-1198, Japan","We propose a method for dynamic security domain scaling on SMPs that offers both highly scalable performance and high security for future high-end embedded systems. Its most important feature is its highly efficient use of processor resources, accomplished by dynamically changing the number of processors within a security domain in response to application load requirements. Two new technologies make this scaling possible without any virtualization software: 1) self-transition management and 2) unified virtual address mapping. Evaluations show that this domain control provides highly scalable performance and incurs almost no performance overhead in security domains. The increase in binary code size is less than 40KB, and the time required for individual state transitions is of a single-millisecond order. This scaling is the first in the world to make possible dynamic changing of the number of processors within a security domain on an ARM SMP. Copyright 2007 ACM.","AMP; Dynamic security domain scaling; SMP","Embedded systems; Multiprocessing systems; Program processors; Requirements engineering; Virtual reality; Dynamic security domain scaling; Processor resources; Virtualization software; Security of data",,,,,,"ARM11 MPCore Processor Technical Reference Manual (2006) Revision r1p0, , ARM, August; Armstrong, W.J., Advanced Virtualization Capabilities of POWER5 Systems (2005) IBM Journal of Research and Development, 49 (4-5), pp. 523-532. , July/September; Barham, P., Xen and the Art of Virtualization (2003) Proceeding of the ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles, pp. 164-177. , October; Dike, J., A User-Mode Port of the Linux Kernel (2000) Proceedings of the 4th Annual Linux Showcase & Conference, pp. 63-72; eSOL. eT-Kernel Multi-Core Edition, http://www.esol.co.jp/english/ embedded/et-kemel_multicore-edition.htmlInoue, H., FIDES: An Advanced Chip Multiprocessor Platform for Secure Next Generation Mobile Terminals (2005) Proceedings of the IEEE/ACM/IFIP International Conference on Hardware/Software Codesign and System Synthesis, pp. 178-183. , September; Inoue, H., VIRTUS: A New Processor Virtualization Architecture for Security-Oriented Next-Generation Mobile Terminals (2006) Proceedings of the ACM/IEEE Design Automation Conference, pp. 484-489. , July; Intel, and NTT DoCoMo. Open and Secure Terminal Initiative (OSTI) Architecture Specification. Revision 1.00, November 2006. http://www.nttdocomo.co.jp/binary/pdf/corporate/technology/osti/OSTI_Arch_R1_00. pdfLoscocco, P., Smalley, S., Integrating Flexible Support for Security Policies into the Linux Operating System (2001) Proceedings of the FREENIX Track of the USENIX Annual Technical Conference, pp. 29-42; McVoy, L., Staelin, C., lmbench: Portable Tools for Performance Analysis (1996) Proceedings of th