"Pirson L., Christy J., Udrea B.","ICC2 study: GNC development in formation flying and testbench implementation",2007,"Advances in the Astronautical Sciences",128,,,169,181,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38549097604&partnerID=40&md5=97bf9f829fdf4a1c21c530ee5a4238a5","Alcatel Alenia Space, 100 Boulevard du Midi, 06156 Cannes La Bocea Cedex, France; European Space Agency, ESTEC, Noordwijk, Netherlands","Pirson, L., Alcatel Alenia Space, 100 Boulevard du Midi, 06156 Cannes La Bocea Cedex, France; Christy, J., Alcatel Alenia Space, 100 Boulevard du Midi, 06156 Cannes La Bocea Cedex, France; Udrea, B., European Space Agency, ESTEC, Noordwijk, Netherlands","The implementation of a formation flying concept is being considered by ESA for the Darwin space interferometer mission. In order to prepare this mission, some studies are led to demonstrate the feasibility of the global project. The ICC2 project aimed at elaborating a full GNC system for a DARWIN precursor mission composed of an interferometric arm (2 telescopes and a hub recombiner). During this study a representative Matlab simulation tool was developed to validate the GNC design, this validation was completed by the implementation of the GNC Design on a real-time testbench which involves three LEON processors and dSPACE facilities. The software was mainly developed from the simulation tool using Matlab automatic code generation facilities. On this basis, AAS has carried on the development of these both tools in the frame of additional contracts with ESA. Thus the Matlab simulator allows today to run very complete sequences including : RF integer ambiguity resolution manoeuvre, convergence from coarsest stage until fringe acquisition, observation with OPD control, scanning manoeuvres. A FDIR strategy with different levels and collision avoidance algorithm have also been added. All the logic and the transition management between the different phases are realised thanks to Stateflow.","Darwin; FDIR; Formation flying; GNC","Collision avoidance; Global positioning system; Interferometers; MATLAB; Project management; Space applications; Formation flying; Global project; Interferometric arm; Spacecraft",,,,,,"Frenkiel, R., Mehlen, C., Radio-frequency technology and GNC for formation flying (2006), IAC-06-C1.3.7Mehlen, Radio frequency metrology and data-link instrument for formation flying missions (2006) 30th annual AAS Guidance and Control Conference, , to be published; Pirson L., Charbonnel C. (2005), Darwin precursor demonstration mission : the ICC2 study, from GNC design to real-time test bench validation, AAS 06-051, in Guidance and Control 2006, S. D Jolly and R. D. Culp, eds., 125, Advances in the Astronautical Sciences, pp.531-537, 2006(paper presented at the 29th Annual AAS Guidance and Control Conference, February 2006)","Pirson, L.; Alcatel Alenia Space, 100 Boulevard du Midi, 06156 Cannes La Bocea Cedex, France",,,,"30th Annual AAS Rocky Mountain Guidance and Control Conference","3 February 2007 through 7 February 2007","Breckenridge, CO",71340,00653438,9780877035428,ADASA,,,"English","Advances in the Astronautical Sciences",Conference Paper,Scopus
"Agnolucci P., Ekins P.","Technological transitions and Strategic Niche Management: The case of the hydrogen economy",2007,"International Journal of Environmental Technology and Management",7,5-6,,644,671,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-36849007686&partnerID=40&md5=7b2d3710075ca07631b35f8a87d7e73c","Environment Group, Policy Studies Institute, 50 Hanson St., W1W 6UP London, United Kingdom","Agnolucci, P., Environment Group, Policy Studies Institute, 50 Hanson St., W1W 6UP London, United Kingdom; Ekins, P., Environment Group, Policy Studies Institute, 50 Hanson St., W1W 6UP London, United Kingdom","There is considerable interest in the prospects for a large-scale transition to hydrogen as an energy source. This paper assesses these prospects through consideration of technological transition theory and especially the likelihood of hydrogen use becoming widespread through Strategic Niche Management (SNM). The paper shows that current niches show few signs of the characteristics that are necessary for niche expansion to the extent required, and concludes that at present hydrogen technologies still need substantial R&D support resulting in a number of scientific breakthroughs before they will become viable in competitive markets. Copyright © 2007 Inderscience Enterprises Ltd.","Hydrogen technologies; SNM; Strategic niche management; Technological transition","Competitive intelligence; Hydrogen; Research and development management; Technology transfer; Hydrogen technologies; Hydrogen use; Strategic niche management (SNM); Technological transition; Energy management; energy resource; hydrogen; resource use; technological change",,,,,,"Adamson, K.-A., Calculating the price trajectory of adoption of fuel cell vehicles (2005) International Journal of Hydrogen Energy, 30, pp. 341-350; Agnolucci, P., McDowall, W., Technological change in niches: Auxiliary power units and the hydrogen economy (2007) Technological Forecasting and Social Change, , in press; 