"Geels F.W.","Feelings of discontent and the promise of middle range theory for STS: Examples from technology dynamics",2007,"Science Technology and Human Values",32,6,,627,651,,7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35548979462&partnerID=40&md5=95ca6eb55ffcb63db5fc67732fe50c6e","Eindhoven University of Technology, Eindhoven, Netherlands","Geels, F.W., Eindhoven University of Technology, Eindhoven, Netherlands","This article critically discusses the state of STS, expressing feelings of discontent regarding four aspects: policy relevance, conceptual language, too much focus on complexity, theoretical styles. Middle range theory is proposed as an alternative, promising avenue. Middle range theories focus on delimited topics, make explicit efforts to combine concepts, and search for abstracted patterns and explanatory mechanisms. The article presents achievements in that direction for technology dynamics, particularly with regard to the role of expectations, niche theory and radical innovation, and the multi-level perspective on sociotechnical transitions. © 2007 Sage Publications.","Emerging trajectories; Expectations; Mechanisms; Sociotechnical transitions; Technology dynamics",,,,,,,"Bijker, W.E., Do not despair: There is life after constructivism (1993) Science, Technology, & Human Values, 18 (1), pp. 113-138; Bijker, W.E., (1995) Of Bicycles, Bakelites and Bulbs: Towards a Theory of Sociotechnical Change, , Cambridge, MA: The MIT Press; Boudon, R., What middle-range theories are (1991) Contemporary Sociology, 20 (4), pp. 519-522; Brown, N., Michael, M., The sociology of expectations: Retrospecting prospects and prospecting retrospects (2003) Technology Analysis & Strategic Management 15, (1), pp. 3-18; Callon, M., The sociology of an actor-network: The case of the electric vehicle (1986) Mapping the Dynamics of Science and Technology, pp. 19-34. , In edited by M. Callon, J. Law and A. Rip, London: MacMillan; Callon, M., Latour, B., Don't throw the b