"Newig J., Voss J.-P., Monstadt J.","Editorial: Governance for sustainable development in the face of ambivalence, uncertainty and distributed power: An introduction",2007,"Journal of Environmental Policy and Planning",9,3-4,,185,192,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-51049104848&partnerID=40&md5=68f326c6441a19f1075b6cc4b6e34606","Institute of Environmental Systems Research, University of Osnabrück, Germany; Öko-Institut, Berlin, Germany; City Institute, York University, Toronto, ON, Canada; Institute of Environmental Systems Research, University of Osnabrück, Barbarastr. 12, 49069 Osnabrück, Germany","Newig, J., Institute of Environmental Systems Research, University of Osnabrück, Germany, Institute of Environmental Systems Research, University of Osnabrück, Barbarastr. 12, 49069 Osnabrück, Germany; Voß, J.-P., Öko-Institut, Berlin, Germany; Monstadt, J., City Institute, York University, Toronto, ON, Canada","Three fundamental observations on the contemporary debate on governance and steering for sustainable development are outlined. First, sustainable development as a highly normative, yet extremely vague concept inescapably raises issues of governance and political steering. Second, the many contributions, approaching sustainability governance from multiple angles, have in common that they assume sustainability goals to a certain extent as given. Third, sustainability poses specific challenges to governance that are different from other policy fields. In this context, exiting contributions highlight issues of complexity, uncertainty or ambivalence, albeit in a rather cursory manner. Against this background, a specific approach is introduced, exploring the complexities that arise from limits to rational steering in three dimensions: Sustainability goals are ambivalent in that they are subject to controversies based on heterogeneous perceptions, values and interests of individuals and societal groups. Moreover, the knowledge of the complex dynamics involving society, technology and nature typically remains highly uncertain. Finally, the power to shape structural change in society and technology is distributed across a multitude of actors and societal subsystems. The article concludes by outlining the structure of the present collection of papers and by summarising each contribution. © 2007 Taylor & Francis.","Complexity; Innovations; Participation; Policy; Political steering; Reflexive governance; Socio-technical transitions",,,,,,,"Bäckstrand, K., Civic Science for Sustainability: Reframing the Role of Experts, Policy-Makers and Citizens in Environmental Governance (2003) Global Environmental Politics, 3 (4), pp. 24-41; Bäckstrand, K., Democratizing Global Environmental Governance? Stakeholder Democracy after the World Summit on Sustainable Development (2006) European Journal of International Relations, 12 (4), pp. 467-498; Beck, U., Bonß, W., Lau, C., The Theory of Reflexive Modernization: Problematic, Hypotheses and Research Programme (2003) Theory, Culture, Society, 20, pp. 1-33; (1994) Reflexive Modernization. Politics, Tradition and Aesthetics in the Modern Social Order, , Beck, U, Giddens, A. & Lash, S, Eds, Cambridge: Polity Press; Bressers, H.T.A., Implementing sustainable development: How to know what works, where, when and how (2004) Governance for Sustainable Development. The Challenge of Adapting Form to Function, pp. 284-318. , W. M. Lafferty Ed, Cheltenham, Northampton: Edward Elgar; (2002) Politik der Nachhaltigkeit. Voraussetzungen, Probleme, Chancen - eine kritische Diskussion, , Ed, Berlin: edition sigma; Bulkeley, H., Betsill, M.M., (2003) Cities and Climate Change. Urban Sustainability and Global Environmental Governance, , London/New York: Routledge; Elzen, B., Geels, F., Green, K., (2004) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability. Theory, Evidence and Policy, , Cheltenham, Northampton: Edward Elgar; Farrell, K.N., Kemp, R., Hinterberger, F., Rammel, C., Ziegler, R., From