"Yarime M.","Promoting green innovation or prolonging the existing technology: Regulation and technological change in the chlor-alkali industry in Japan and Europe",2007,"Journal of Industrial Ecology",11,4,,117,139,,7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-36849001244&partnerID=40&md5=aa8e37be3f08a5f7597b973af17eab2e","Department of Human and Engineered Environmental Studies, Graduate School of Frontier Sciences, University of Tokyo, Kashiwanoha 5-1-5, Kashiwa-shi, Chiba 277-8563, Japan; Department of Human and Engineered Environmental Studies, Graduate School of Frontier Sciences, University of Tokyo, Japan","Yarime, M., Department of Human and Engineered Environmental Studies, Graduate School of Frontier Sciences, University of Tokyo, Kashiwanoha 5-1-5, Kashiwa-shi, Chiba 277-8563, Japan, Department of Human and Engineered Environmental Studies, Graduate School of Frontier Sciences, University of Tokyo, Japan","A case study of the chlor-alkali industry in Western Europe and Japan is presented examining the effects of environmental regulation on technological change. In Western Europe, standards were set for mercury emissions from chlor-alkali plants, which were gradually tightened subsequently. Research and development (R&D) efforts were directed to end-of-pipe technologies as well as process improvements for reducing mercury emissions, rather than to clean technologies, which eliminate mercury from within the production process. With a significant reduction in mercury emissions with end-of-pipe technologies, new plants continued to be built that relied on the mercury process. As long as these relatively new plants could be utilized, technological transition to the clean ion-exchange membrane process remained slow. The success in reducing mercury emissions with end-of-pipe technologies, in effect, helped to prolong the lifetime of the existing mercury process. In Japan, the government introduced policies to phase out the existing mercury process. The strict approach encouraged innovative companies to make R&D efforts on clean technologies, instead of end-of-pipe technologies for pollution abatement. Applied in a hasty and inflexible way, however, the stringent regulation initially induced most of the chloralkali producers to choose the diaphragm process, which later turned out to be inappropriate. After the regulatory schedule was modified to allow more time for process conversion, the remaining mercury-based plants were converted directly to the most efficient ion-exchange membrane process. The technological transition, however, was costly, as most of the diaphragm-based plants introduced following the regulatory mandate were operated only for a short period of time, with the large investment wasted. © 2007 by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Yale University.","Diaphragm; Industrial ecology; Institution; Ion-exchange membrane; Mercury; Research and development (R&D)","Diaphragms; Environmental regulations; Ion exchange membranes; Pollution control; Research and development management; Standards; Chlor-alkali plants; Industrial ecology; Mercury emissions; Chemical industry; emission control; environmental policy; industrial emission; innovation; ion exchange; mercury (element); pollution control; standard (regulation); technological change; Asia; Eurasia; Europe; Far East; Japan",,,,,,"(1998) Chemicals and long-term economic growth: Insights from the chemical industry, , Arora, A, R. Landau, and N. Rosenberg, eds, New York: Wiley; Arthur, W.B., Competing technologies, increasing returns, and lock-in by historical small events (1989) Economic Journal, 99 (394), pp. 116-131; Asahi Chemical Industry. 1998. Chlor-alkali plant capacity employing Asahi Chemical bipolar process. Tokyo: Asahi Chemical IndustryGlass, A., (1999) AZEC electrolyzer supply record, , Tokyo: Asahi Glass; Asahi Shinbun, , 1973a. An allegation of the Minamata disease in the Tokuyama Bay area. Morning Edition, June 18, 22; Asahi Shi