"Keppo I., Rao S.","International climate regimes: Effects of delayed participation",2007,"Technological Forecasting and Social Change",74,7,,962,979,,13,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34547888724&partnerID=40&md5=96305f69e7286fb2232665917c65f8e6","International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, Schlossplatz 1, A-2361 Laxenburg, Austria","Keppo, I., International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, Schlossplatz 1, A-2361 Laxenburg, Austria; Rao, S., International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, Schlossplatz 1, A-2361 Laxenburg, Austria","This paper analyses how delayed participation by regions can affect international climate regimes in terms of the feasibility, costs, timing, magnitude and nature of the long-term mitigation response. We use the energy-systems optimization model MESSAGE to construct several climate change mitigation scenarios with various levels of regional participation in short-to-mid term. By comparing these with a global scenario that assumes full spatial and temporal flexibility throughout the century, we are able to evaluate how participatory decisions affect the mitigation response as well as the costs and technology choices. We find that short-term postponement of participation from some regions can often lead to a delay of mitigation measures on the global level. However, if the regional delay lasts until mid-century, participants of the regime are likely to increase their efforts in the short term. Mitigation costs are found to substantially increase as a result of delayed participation-the extent of the increase depends on the relative importance of the region that postpones its participation, the stringency of the climate target and the ability to reorganize mitigation measures. Our analysis also shows that a region's decision to delay its participation in an international climate regime can lead to accumulated inertia in its energy system and thus to a delayed 'technological transition' toward a low-carbon future. © 2006 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.","Abatement cost; Climate change; Delayed participation; Energy modeling","Climatology; Computer simulation; Mathematical models; Optimization; Abatement cost; Climate energy-systems; Delayed participation; Energy modeling; Climate change; abatement cost; climate change; decision making; environmental legislation; environmental planning; mitigation; modeling; participatory approach",,,,,,"(1992) Convention text, UNEP/WMO Information Unit of Climate Change (IUCC) on behalf of the Interim Secretariat of the Convention, , IUCC, Geneva; Haites, E., Missfeldt, F., Liability rules for international trading of greenhouse gas emissions quotas (2001) Clim. Policy, 1 (1), pp. 85-108; Nentjes, A., Klaassen, G., On the quality of compliance mechanisms in the Kyoto protocol (2004) Energy Policy, 32 (4), pp. 531-544; Manne, A., Richels, R., (1992) Buying Greenhouse Insurance: The Economic Costs of CO2 Emissions Limits, p. 194. , MIT Press, Cambridge; Asheim, G.B., Froyn, C.B., Hovi, J., Menz, F.C., Regional versus global cooperation for climate control (2006) J. Environ. Econ. Manage., 51 (1), pp. 93-109; Kemfert, C., Climate coalitions and international trade: assessment of cooperation incentives by issue linkage (2004) Energy Policy, 32 (4), pp. 455-465; (2000) Special Report on Emissions Scenarios. Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, p. 612. , Nakićenović N., and Swart R. (Eds), Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Manne, A., Richels, R., US rejection of the Kyoto protocol: the impact on compliance costs and CO2 emissions (2004) Energy Policy, 32 (4), pp. 447-454; Buchner, B., Carraro, C., Cersosimo, I., Economic consequences of the US withdrawal from the Kyoto-Bonn protocol (2002) Clim. Policy, 2 (4), pp. 273-292; Valverde, L.J., Webster, M.D., Stabilizing atmospheric CO2 concentrations: technical, political, and economic dimensions (1999) Energy Policy, 27 (10), pp. 613-622; Berk, M.M., den Elzen, M.G.J., Op