"Hamilton R.H., Rupp W.T.","Opportunities and challenges in the wireless world",2007,"Journal of Internet Commerce",6,3,,29,44,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34548860627&partnerID=40&md5=9cd4a8df317926b365b5a4919307eaba","Department of Management, University of Mississippi, DeSoto Center, 5197 W.E. Ross Parkway, Southhaven, MS 38671, United States; Stephens College of Business, University of Montevallo, Montevallo, AL 35115, United States","Hamilton, R.H., Department of Management, University of Mississippi, DeSoto Center, 5197 W.E. Ross Parkway, Southhaven, MS 38671, United States; Rupp, W.T., Stephens College of Business, University of Montevallo, Montevallo, AL 35115, United States","The technology driving the wireless world is moving at warp speed and the consequences affecting the organization are immense. As the technology is assimilated, the changes in the relationship between the employer and employee are morphing requiring more trust, more communication, and a major change in the supervisory thinking and function. This adoption leads to cost reductions for the organization, a required 24-7 mentality for the employee, and the realization that while the physical strings have been cut, the wireless strings that bind the relationship between employer and employee are tighter than ever. The paper presents a model that includes a set of organizational processes that may reduce individual resistance, facilitate technological transition, and result in a greater understanding of the technology assimilation process. © Copyright (c) by The Haworth Press, Inc. All rights reserved.","Change; Communications; Convergence process; Culture; Process model; Wireless technology",,,,,,,"Apgar, M., The alternative workplace: Changing where and how people work (1999) Harvard Business Review, 76 (3), pp. 121-139; Telework Case Study (2005) Telework Leadership Initiative, , Atlanta Regional Commission Report, July; Bailey, D.E., Kurland, N.B., A review of tel