"Ostlie I.L., Dale O., Moller A.","From childhood to adult life with juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA): A pilot study",2007,"Disability and Rehabilitation",29,6,,445,452,,6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34249676154&partnerID=40&md5=6ff546aa2088a5eab591bcdb7a269ab5","Department of Nursing, Gjö University College, Gjövik, Norway; National Insurance Administration, Oslo, Norway; The Nordic School of Public Health, Göteborg, Sweden","Östlie, I.L., Department of Nursing, Gjö University College, Gjövik, Norway; Dale, O., National Insurance Administration, Oslo, Norway; Möller, A., The Nordic School of Public Health, Göteborg, Sweden","Purpose. To explore the experiences of the health service provision in the transition process from childhood to adult life from the perspective of young patients with juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA) and health professionals working in this field. Method. Two groups of young persons with JIA and two groups of health professionals were interviewed in focus groups. The data were analysed according to approved guidelines for qualitative analysis. Results. 'Capability to lead a meaningful adult life' emerged as a core category; capability as a consequence of 'being enabled' from the youths' point of view, and 'enabling the young patients' from the health professionals' perspective. Preparation for the transition and transfer process was perceived as inadequate and seemed dependent on enthusiastic health professionals both in the children's and adult wards. Suggestions for formal improvements were required in four main areas. Conclusion. This pilot study has identified in adequacies in the transition management provided for young people with JIA. Acceptance of the young persons as active participants in their own transition process might strengthen these young persons' experience of an autonomous identity and enable participation socially and in society, thus enhancing the ability to achieve a meaningful adult life. Further investigations should focus on adults living with JIA, how they lead their lives physically and psychosocially.","Adolescent; Adult; Empowerment; Juvenile idiopathic arthritis; Transition","adolescent; adult; adulthood; article; childhood; clinical article; controlled study; empowerment; female; health personnel attitude; health practitioner; human; interview; juvenile rheumatoid arthritis; male; Norway; patient attitude; patient autonomy; physical performance; pilot study; priority journal; qualitative analysis; quality of life; social interaction; social psychology; daily life activity; information processing; personal autonomy; psychological aspect; Activities of Daily Living; Adolescent; Adult; Arthritis, Juvenile Rheumatoid; Attitude of Health Personnel; Female; Focus Groups; Humans; Interviews; Male; Norway; Personal Autonomy; Pilot Projects; Quality of Life",,,,,,"McDonagh, J., Foster, H.E., Hall, M.A., Chamberlain, M.A., Audit of rheumatology services for adolescents and young adults in the UK. British Paediatric Rheumatology Group (2000) Rheumatology (Oxford), 39 (6), pp. 596-602; White, P., Transition to adulthood (1999) Curr Opin Rheumatol, 11, pp. 408-411; White, P., Success on the road to adulthood. Issues and hurdles for adolescents with disabilities (1997) Rheum Dis Clin North Am, 23, pp. 697-707; Davidson, J., Juvenile idiopathic arthritis: A clinical overview (2000) Eur J Radiol, 33 (2), pp. 128-134; Gare, B.A., Epidemiology (1998) Baillieres Clin Rheumatol, 12 (2), pp. 191-208; Flatø, B., Outcome and predictive factors in juvenile arthritis and allied disorders (1999), p. 77. , [dissertation] University of Oslo, Oslo, NorwayZak, M., Pedersen, F.K., Juvenile chronic arthritis into adulthood: A long-term follow-up study (2000) Rheumatology (Oxford), 39 (2), pp. 198-204; Wallace, C., Levinson, J.E., Juvenile rheumatoid arthritis: Outcome and treatment for the 1990s (1991) Rheum Dis Clin North Am, 17 (4), pp. 891-905; Gare, B.A., Fasth, A., The na