"Hekkert M.P., Suurs R.A.A., Negro S.O., Kuhlmann S., Smits R.E.H.M.","Functions of innovation systems: A new approach for analysing technological change",2007,"Technological Forecasting and Social Change",74,4,,413,432,,109,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34147185181&partnerID=40&md5=3748c06ab50bed7895c060e37cddcf1b","Utrecht University, Copernicus Institute for Sustainable Development and Innovation, Department of Innovation Studies, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS Utrecht, Netherlands; Fraunhofer Institute for Systems and Innovation Research ISI, Breslauer Strasse 48, 76139 Karlsruhe, Germany","Hekkert, M.P., Utrecht University, Copernicus Institute for Sustainable Development and Innovation, Department of Innovation Studies, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS Utrecht, Netherlands; Suurs, R.A.A., Utrecht University, Copernicus Institute for Sustainable Development and Innovation, Department of Innovation Studies, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS Utrecht, Netherlands; Negro, S.O., Utrecht University, Copernicus Institute for Sustainable Development and Innovation, Department of Innovation Studies, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS Utrecht, Netherlands; Kuhlmann, S., Utrecht University, Copernicus Institute for Sustainable Development and Innovation, Department of Innovation Studies, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS Utrecht, Netherlands, Fraunhofer Institute for Systems and Innovation Research ISI, Breslauer Strasse 48, 76139 Karlsruhe, Germany; Smits, R.E.H.M., Utrecht University, Copernicus Institute for Sustainable Development and Innovation, Department of Innovation Studies, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS Utrecht, Netherlands","The central idea of this paper is that innovation systems are a very important determinant of technological change. We describe that the emergence of a new innovation system and changes in existing innovation systems co-evolve with the process of technological change. Therefore, it is necessary to create more insight in the dynamics of innovation systems. Traditional methods of innovation system analysis that mainly focus on the structure of innovation systems have proven to be insufficient. Therefore, we propose a framework that focuses on a number of processes that are highly important for well performing innovation systems. These processes are labeled as 'functions of innovation systems'. After explaining this framework and embedding it in existing literature, we propose a method for systematically mapping those processes taking place in innovation systems and resulting in technological change. This method can be characterized as a process analysis or history event analysis. Clarifying examples are taken from the empirical field of Sustainable Technology Development. © 2006 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.","Innovation system dynamics; Transition management","Management; Sustainable development; Systems analysis; Technological forecasting; History event analysis; Process analysis; Technological change; Transition management; Innovation; innovation; technological change",,,,,,"Smits, R., Kuhlmann, S., The rise of systemic instruments in innovation policy (2004) Int. J. Foresight Innov. Policy, 1 (1-2), pp. 4-32; Grübler, A., (1998) Technology and Global Change, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Weaver, P., Jansen, L., Grootveld, G., Spiegel, E., van, P., (2000) Sustainable Technology Development, , Greenleaf Publishing, Sheffield, UK; Geels, F., Technological Transitions as evolutionary reconfiguration processes: a multi level perspective and a case study (2002) Res. Policy, 31, pp. 1257-1274; Sagar, A.D., Holdren, J.P., Assessing the global energy innovation system: some key issues (2002) Energy Policy, 30 (6), pp. 465-469; Lundvall, B.-A., (1992) National Systems of Innovation: Towards a Theory of Innovation and Interactive Learning, , Pinter, London; Nelson, R., Winter, S.G., (1982) An Evolutionary Theory of Economic Change, , Harvard University Press, Cambridge, MA; van de Ven, A.H., Polley, D.E., Garud, 