"Kemp R., Loorbach D., Rotmans J.","Transition management as a model for managing processes of co-evolution towards sustainable development",2007,"International Journal of Sustainable Development and World Ecology",14,1,,78,91,,34,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34247274634&partnerID=40&md5=f523223484318face325b3518b92eba8","UNU-MERIT, Maastricht, Netherlands; DRIFT, Burgemeester Oudlaan 50, 3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands","Kemp, R., UNU-MERIT, Maastricht, Netherlands, DRIFT, Burgemeester Oudlaan 50, 3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands; Loorbach, D., UNU-MERIT, Maastricht, Netherlands; Rotmans, J., UNU-MERIT, Maastricht, Netherlands","Sustainable development requires changes in socio-technical systems and wider societal change - in beliefs, values and governance diat co-evolve with technology changes. In this article we present a practical model for managing processes of co-evolution: transition management. Transition management is a multilevel model of governance which shapes processes of co-evolution using visions, transition experiments and cycles of learning and adaptation. Transition management helps societies to transform themselves in a gradual, reflexive way through guided processes of variation and selection, the outcomes of which are stepping stones for further change. It shows that societies can break free from existing practices and technologies, by engaging in co-evolutionary steering. This is illustrated by the Dutch waste management transition. Perhaps transition management constitutes the third way that policy scientists have been looking for all the time, combining the advantages of incrementalism (based on mutual adaptation) with the advantages of planning (based on long-term objectives).","And goal-oriented modulation; Co-evolution; Incrementalism; Multi-level governance; Planning; Sustainable development","adaptation; coevolution; learning; planning method; selection; social change; sustainable development; Benelux; Eurasia; Europe; Netherlands; Western Europe",,,,,,"Beck, U., The Reinvention of Politics. Towards a Theory of Reflexive Modernization (1994) Reflexive Modernization. Politics, Tradition and Aesthetics in the Modern Social Order, pp. 1-55. , Beck U, Giddens A and Lash S eds, Oxford: Polity Press;; Bleischwitz, R., Governance of sustainable development: Co-evolution of corporate and political strategies (2004) International Journal Of Sustainable Development, 7 (1), pp. 27-43; Eising, R., Kohler-Koch, B., (1999) The Transformation of EU Governance, , London: Roudedge;; Etzioni, A., Mixed Scanning Revisited (1986) Public Administration Review, pp. 8-14. , Jan/Feb; Geels, F.W., Technological transitions as evolutionary reconfiguration processes: A multi-level perspective and a case-study (2002) Research Policy, 31 (8-9), pp. 1257-1274; Geels, F.W., (2005) System Innovation and the Transition to Sustainability. Theory, Evidence and Policy, , Cheltenham: Edward Elgar;; Giddens, A., (1984) The constitution of society. Outline of the theory of structuration, , Cambridge: Polity Press;; Gowdy, J., (1994) Coevolutionary Economics: The Economy, Society and the Environment, , Dordrecht: Kluwer;; Gunderson, L.H., Holling, C.S., (2002) Panarchy: Understanding transformations in human and natural systems, , Washington DC: Island Press;; Grunwald, A., Technology Policy between Long-term Planning Requirements and Short-ranged Acceptance Problems. New Challenges for Technology Assessment (2000) Vision Assessment: Shaping Technology in the 21st Century Society. Towards a Repertoire for Technology assessment, , Grin J and Grunwald A eds, Berlin-Heidelberg: Springer;; Hadfield, L., Seaton, R., A co-evolutionary model of change in environmental management (1999) Futures, 31, pp. 577-592; Hooghe, L., Marks, G., (2001) Multi-level governance and European integration, , Oxford: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers;; Hoogma, R., Kemp, R., Schot, J., Truffer, B., (2002) Experimenting for Sustainable Transport. 