"Lesko D.","Polish financial reporting principles in transition",2007,"Baltic Journal of Management",2,1,,55,66,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-75649116138&partnerID=40&md5=ac0ab87dbb3b04d83a7cfed10c0b565c","Department of Economics I, Warsaw School of Economics (SGH), Warsaw, Poland","Leśko, D., Department of Economics I, Warsaw School of Economics (SGH), Warsaw, Poland","Purpose - The purpose of this paper is to deal with the evolution of Polish financial reporting principles in its historical context, this providing the reader with basic understanding of what has been influencing the shape of Polish accounting rules and how they evolved from the communist times until the accession of Poland to the European Union. This in turn should help in understanding the way in which Polish corporate governance system has evolved. Design/methodology/approach - The approach taken is a general review and analysis of the issues surrounding Polish accounting rules transition. Findings - Throughout the transition period Polish financial reporting principles managed to successfully convert from socialistic to financial-market oriented thus providing both financial managers and investors with a powerful governance tool. Practical implications - Full understanding of the development of modern financial reporting principles, especially in the transition/emerging economies, is not possible without sound knowledge of the socio-economic context of their formation. Originality/value - Both business practitioners interested in collaboration with companies from Poland (or another transition country) as well as academics working on financial reporting/management issues in international setting should find the paper useful. © Emerald Group Publishing Limited.","Financial management; Financial reporting; Poland; Transition management",,,,,,,"Balcerowicz, L., (2001) Post-communist Transition: Some Lessons (31st Wincott Lecture), , The Institute of Economic Affairs, London; 