"Foxon T.","Bounded rationality and hierarchical complexity: Two paths from Simon to ecological and evolutionary economics",2006,"Ecological Complexity",3,4,,361,368,,2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34147187787&partnerID=40&md5=7520bfde011ad7f87ddaf96d5454f862","4CMR - Cambridge Centre for Climate Change Mitigation Research, Department of Land Economy, University of Cambridge, CB3 9EP, United Kingdom; Centre for Environmental Policy, Imperial College, South Kensington, London, SW7 2AZ, United Kingdom","Foxon, T., 4CMR - Cambridge Centre for Climate Change Mitigation Research, Department of Land Economy, University of Cambridge, CB3 9EP, United Kingdom, Centre for Environmental Policy, Imperial College, South Kensington, London, SW7 2AZ, United Kingdom","This paper examines two paths by which the work of Herbert Simon has influenced the development of ecological and evolutionary economics: bounded rationality and hierarchical complexity. It argues that there is scope for further consideration of the implications of these ideas, particularly their inter-relation. This is illustrated through some recent ideas on the co-evolution of technologies and institutions. This is related to understanding transitions of technological systems, and how these might be steered or modulated towards greater sustainability. © 2007 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Bounded rationality; Co-evolution of technologies and institutions; Hierarchical complexity; Technological transitions",,,,,,,"Arrow, K., The economic implications of learning by doing (1962) Rev. Econ. Stud., 29, pp. 155-173; Arthur, W.B., Self-reinforcing mechanisms in economics (1988) The Economy as an Evolving Complex System, SFI Studies in the Sciences of Complexity, , Anderson P.W., Arrow K.J., and Pines D. (Eds), Addison Wesley, Reading, MA; Arthur, W.B., Competing technologies, increasing returns, and lock-in by historical events (1989) Econ. J., 99, pp. 116-131; Arthur, W.B., (1994) Increasing