"Nguyen-Dac B., Crebier J.-C.","MOS controlled AC switches implemented with full driver power supplies and dead time management circuits",2006,"IECON Proceedings (Industrial Electronics Conference)",,, 4153470,2049,2054,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-50249124645&partnerID=40&md5=78eec8ef27b17e4962d67c5b96877c84","Laboratoire d'Electrotechnique de Grenoble (LEG), INPG/UJF-CNRS UMR 5529, ENSIEG, BP 46, 38402 St Martin d'Hères cedex GRENOBLE, France","Nguyen-Dac, B., Laboratoire d'Electrotechnique de Grenoble (LEG), INPG/UJF-CNRS UMR 5529, ENSIEG, BP 46, 38402 St Martin d'Hères cedex GRENOBLE, France; Crebier, J.-C., Laboratoire d'Electrotechnique de Grenoble (LEG), INPG/UJF-CNRS UMR 5529, ENSIEG, BP 46, 38402 St Martin d'Hères cedex GRENOBLE, France","The paper presents an original technique to power supply transistors gate drivers in AC-AC MOS controlled power converters. The technique is based on power side energy source to self-supply the transistors. AC-AC MOS controlled converters are well known for their complex practical Implementation due to numerous transistor use with numerous potential references. This requires many gate drivers and gate driver supplies. In addition, the MOS-MOS switching transition that takes place in this kind of converter is complex to manage and leads often to over voltages or over currents. The presented gate driver powering technique allows to simplify both, the global implementation of the converter and the MOS-MOS switching transition management. The self-powering technique simplifies the implementation and the technique can be fully integrated with the power switch to be controlled. This leads to a cost effective solutions. In addition, the very specific operation of the self powering technique is used to simplify switching transitions. In fact, the gate driver power supplies are sensitive to dv/dt and this is used to perform self powering during dead time switching transitions, leading to minimum dead time duration and reduced over voltages. The paper recalls at first how the self powering technique operates. Then, MOS controlled AC switch configurations are discussed with respect to monolithic integration issues. Then, the operation of a single phase AC-AC MOS controlled converter with self-powering technique and dead time management is presented. The very specific operation during switching transitions is underlined. A final part of the paper is dedicated to practical validation with numerous practical results and explanation. © 2006 IEEE.",,"Chlorine compounds; Cost effectiveness; Electric power distribution; Electric power transmission networks; Electric power utilization; Electronics industry; Industrial electronics; Management; Monolithic integrated circuits; Switches; Switching; Three term control systems; Time switches; Transistors; AC switches; AND gates; Annual conference; Cost-effective solutions; Dead time; Energy sourcing; Fully integrated; Gate drivers; Global implementation; Monolithic integrations; Over currents; Over voltages; Power supplies; Power switching; Practical implementation; Self powering; Single phasing; Switching transitions; Automobile drivers",,,,,,"B.D. Nguyen, et al AC switches with integrated gate driver supplies, EPE'05, 11-14 Septembre 2005, Dresde, AllemagneR. Pezzani et al, Functional integration of power devices: a new approach, EPE'95, Sevilla, Spain, September 95, 2p219Bauer, Bidirectional semiconductor device that can be turned OFF United States patent No5040042; Mehrotra, M., A planar MOS-gated AC switch structure, IEDM1195, pp. 349-352. , IEEE; J.C. Crébier. G. Verneau, L. Aubard, R. Mitova, C. Schaeffer, Integrated Driver Power Supply for Power Switch, EPE'03. 3-5 Septembre 2003, Toulouse, FranceO. Causse et al, Achievement of a new peripherical planar structure supporting a symmetrical blocking voltage, EPE'01, 27-29 August 2001, Graz, AustriaMitova, R., Crébier, J.C., Aubard, L., Schaeffer, C., Gate Driver Supply Of Power Switches Without Galvanic Insulation (2004) IEEE IAS'04, , 5-7 Octobre, Seattle, USA; F.D. Hobart et al, Characterization of a bidirectional double side double gate IGBT fabricated by wafer bonding, ISPSD'01, OsakaSeguier, G., (1986) Power Electronic Converters - AC/DC Conversion, p. 152. , McGraw-Hill; Nicolas Rouger, Jean-Christophe Crébier, Laurent Aubard, Christian Schaeffer, Toward Generic Fully Integrated Gate Driver Power Supplies, IECON 2006, Paris","Nguyen-Dac, B.; Laboratoire d'Electrotechnique de Grenoble (LEG), INPG/UJF-CNRS UMR 5529, ENSIEG, BP 46, 38402 St Martin d'Hères cedex GRENOBLE, France; email: Binh.Nguyen-Dac@leg.ensieg.inpg.fr",,,,"IECON 2006 - 32nd Annual Conference on IEEE Industrial Electronics","6 November 2006 through 10 November 2006","Paris",73084,,1424401364; 9781424401369,IEPRE,10.1109/IECON.2006.347741,,"English","IECON Proceedings (Industrial Electronics Conference)",Conference Paper,Scopus
"Lei B., Xu L.-Q.","Real-time outdoor video surveillance with robust foreground extraction and object tracking via multi-state transition management",2006,"Pattern Recognition Letters",27,15,,1816,1825,,18,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33748663558&partnerID=40&md5=9f107839025c13ae78142f688438d1af","Broadband Applications Research Centre, BT Research, Martlesham Heath, Ipswich IP5 3RE, United Kingdom","Lei, B., Broadband Applications Research Centre, BT Research, Martlesham Heath, Ipswich IP5 3RE, United Kingdom; Xu, L.-Q., Broadband Applications Research Centre, BT Research, Martlesham Heath, Ipswich IP5 3RE, United Kingdom","In this paper we present an effective and flexible real-time video analysis system aiming at a wide range of outdoor surveillance and monitoring scenarios, in which robust detection and tracking objects of interest (pedestrians and/or vehicles) are essential to detecting events and understanding scene changes. The approaches employed address properly the challenges found in typical outdoor scenes such as localised and global lighting changes, variations in object size and views, occlusions, and complex object motion and so on. The contributions include use of an effective two-layer shadow removal scheme based on brightness distortion in different colour channels, blob-based object tracking and occlusion handling via multi-state transition management. The system works equally well on highly compressed (JPEG + MPEG-4) video streams as well as raw video data; in the former case, it achieves about 18 frames per second with software MPEG-4 decoder in a modern PC. And the real-time constraint renders most complex tracking algorithms less attractive. © 2006 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Change detection; Illumination invariance; Moving shadow removal; Multi-state representation; Object tracking; Real-time system; Video surveillance","Algorithms; Computer software; Feature extraction; Object recognition; Robustness (control