"Molenkamp J.B.","Model-based transition management",2006,"Journal of Portfolio Management",33,1,,37,45+4,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33845335878&partnerID=40&md5=731fc0d552e8775018df7cc995b9e221","Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Kempen Capital Management","Molenkamp, J.B., Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam, Amsterdam, Netherlands, Kempen Capital Management","Once the optimal strategic benchmark is set for institutional assets, given the characteristics of the liabilities, the challenge is to reallocate all the assets to the benchmark weights. Transitions typically increase transaction costs and tracking error beyond the risk of the normal investment processes, and both transaction costs and tracking error have a significant influence on performance. Suggested here is a model to deal more systematically with transition issues that is independent of the trigger of the transition (such as a rebalancing strategy). The model is less complex than others suggested so far and is well-suited to deal with multiple assets. A multi-asset example shows it is easy to implement this approach.",,,,,,,,"Bertsimas, D., Lo, A., Optimal control of execution costs (1998) Journal of Financial Markets, 1, pp. 1-50; Donohue, C., Yip, K., Optimal portfolio rebalancing with transaction costs (2003) The Journal of Portfolio Management, pp. 49-63. , Summer; Leland, H.E., (2000) Optimal Portfolio Implementation with Transactions Costs and Capital Gains Taxes, , Haas School of Business, University of California, Berkeley, December 20; Madhavan, A., Market microstructure: A practitioner's guide (2002) Financial Analysts Journal, pp. 28-42. , September/October; Mulvey, J.M., Simsek, K., (2001) Rebalancing Strategies for Long-term Investors, , EDHEC Risk and Management Research Centre, March 20; Sun, W., Fan, A., Chen, L.W., Schouwenaars, T., Albota, M., Optimal rebalancing strategy using dynamic programming for institutional portfolios (2005) Working Pap