"De Vries J.L., Te Riele H.R.M.","Playing with hyenas: Renovating environmental product policy strategy",2006,"Journal of Industrial Ecology",10,3,,111,127,,5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33750607302&partnerID=40&md5=2c169695b03225cc3d3a4936d1cbe7af","2eco, 7427 RA Deventer, Netherlands; Dutch Research Institute for Transitions (DRIFT), Erasmus University, Rotterdam, Netherlands; Delft University of Technology, Faculty of Product Design","De Vries, J.L., 2eco, 7427 RA Deventer, Netherlands, ; Te Riele, H.R.M., Dutch Research Institute for Transitions (DRIFT), Erasmus University, Rotterdam, Netherlands, Delft University of Technology, Faculty of Product Design","The 1990s policy trend of intervening at the specification level over a broad range of products has ended. Today's environmental product policies focus, rather, on a few arbitrary product groups. Selectiveness should serve absolute environmental impact reduction, which asks for a rational product-selection and target framework. The authors propose ""life-cycle impact per consumer expenditure"" as a key criterion. This criterion helps to connect macro environmental impact reduction aims with product innovation targets, even under continuous economic growth, consumption pattern shifts, and rebound threats. The authors analyze the Dutch economy as an exercise. This results in 44 product groups, labeled ""Hyenas"" by the authors, that need to improve their ratio score drastically between now and 2040. Some magnitudes of desired change are given. Finally, intervention processes at the Hyena group level along the lines of sustainable transition management are proposed. Joint visioning, experimental portfolios, interaction between micro, meso, and macro change levels, and gradual pressure building are crucial elements in this concept of complex change management. © 2006 by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Yale University.","Decoupling; Eco-design; Hybrid life-cycle assessment; Innovation; Rebound effect; Sustainable transition","Costs; Ecology; Economic and social effects; Environmental impact; Strategic planning; Ecodesign; Hybrid life cycle assessment; Product policy strategy; Rebound effects; Sustainable transition; Environmental engineering; economic growth; environmental impact; environmental policy; policy strategy; product development; Benelux; Eurasia; Europe; Netherlands; Western Europe",,,,,,"(2004) Vier Vergezichten Op Nederland. [Four Outlooks on the Netherlands.], , CPB (Centraal Planbureau). The Hague, the Netherlands: CPB; (2004) Four Futures for Energy Markets and Climate Change, , CPB and RIVM (Rijksinstituut voor Volksgezondheid en Milieu). The Hague, the Netherlands: CPB; De Vries, J.L., Te Riele, H.R.M., (2005) Consumption Sustained, or ""Playing with Hyenas"", , www.natuurenmilieu.nl/consumptionsustained.pdf, Utrecht, the Netherlands: Accessed December 2005; Elzen, B., Geels, F.W., Hofman, P., Sociotechnical scenarios as an instrument for transition policies (2004) Milieubeleid en Technologische Ontwikkeling in de Nederlandse Economie [Environmental Policy and Technological Development in the Dutch Economy], , edited by H. R. J. Vollebergh. The Hague, the Netherlands: SDU; (2001) Our Future, Our Choice, , European Commission (EC). 6th EU Environment Action Programme. Brussels, Belgium: EC; (2005) Directive 2005/32/EC on the Eco-design of Energy-using Products, , EC. Brussels, Belgium: EC; Geels, F.W., (2002) Understanding the Dynamics of Technological Transitions, a Co-evolutionary and Sociotechnical Analysis, , Enschede, the Netherlands: Twente University Press; Geels, F.W., Kemp, R., Technological transitions and sustainability (2004) Milieubeleid en Technologische Ontwikkeling in de Nederlandse Economie [Environmental Policy and Technological Development in the Dutch Economy], , edited by H. R. J. Vollebergh. The Hague, the Netherlands: SDU; Goedkoop, M., (1995) Eco-indicator 95, Handleiding Voor Ontwerpers, , www.pre