"Van Der Brugge R., Rotmans J., Loorbach D.","The transition in Dutch water management",2005,"Regional Environmental Change",5,4,,164,176,,46,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-29144524824&partnerID=40&md5=9361b0a88bd60d7c80c196f036de4769","Dutch Research Institute for Transitions (DRIFT), P.O. Box 1738, 3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands","Van Der Brugge, R., Dutch Research Institute for Transitions (DRIFT), P.O. Box 1738, 3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands; Rotmans, J., Dutch Research Institute for Transitions (DRIFT), P.O. Box 1738, 3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands; Loorbach, D., Dutch Research Institute for Transitions (DRIFT), P.O. Box 1738, 3000 DR Rotterdam, Netherlands","Over the past decades, the Dutch people have been confronted with severe water-related problems, which are the result of an unsustainable water system, arising from human interventions in the physical infrastructure of the water system and the water management style. The claims of housing, industry, infrastructure and agriculture have resulted in increasing pressure on the water system. The continuous subsidence of soil and climate change has put pressure on the land. Hence, the nature and magnitude of water-related problems have changed. Longitudinal research of relevant national policy documents reveals that the water management regime has changed its water management style over the past 30 years from a technocratic scientific style towards an integral and participatory style. We have investigated if the historical development in Dutch Water management can be characterized as a transition. Based on longitudinal research through an integrated systems analysis, document research and expert interviews, we have reconstructed the historical narrative by using the transition concepts of multi-level and multi-phase. This research indicates that the shift in Dutch Water management can be characterized as a transition. This transition is currently in the take-off stage and near the acceleration stage. This is a crucial stage as long as the considerable gap between the strategic macro-vision and the practical implementation at the micro-level remains. As long as these levels are not compatible (modulation), the transition will not be completed successfully. Transition management as multi-level governance model should therefore be adopted to facilitate the modulation.","Sustainability; Transition management; Transitions; Water management",,,,,,,"Berkhout, F., Smith, A., Stirling, A., Socio-technical regimes and transitions contexts (2003) SPRU Electronic Working Paper Series; Bosch, A., Van Der Ham, W., (1998) Twee Eeuwen Rijkswaterstaat, 1798-1990 (Two Centuries Rijkswaterstaat, 1798-1990) Europese Bibliotheek, Zaltbommel; De Bruijn, D., Hamhuis, D., Van Nieuwenhuijze, L., Overmars, W., Sijmons, D., Vera, F., (1987) Ooievaar: de Toekomst Van Het Rivierengebied. (Ooievaar; the Future of the Riverland), , Gelderse Milieufederatie. Arnhem, The Netherlands; (2000) Anders Omgaan Met Water. Waterbeleid voor de 21eeeuw. (Dealing Differently with Water, Water Management for the 21st Century), , CW21 Committee Tielrooy, Ministry of Transport, Public Works and Water management/Union of Waterboards. The Hague, The Netherlands; Dirven, J., Rotmans, J., Verkaik, A.P., (2002) Samenleving in Transitie, Een Vernieuwend Gezichtpunt. (Society in Transition: An Innovative Viewpoint), , Essay, The Hague; Geels, F., Kemp, R., (2000) Transities Vanuit Sociotechnisch Perspectief (Transitions from a Sociotechnical Perspective), , Maastricht, The Netherlands; Van Der Ham, W., (1999) Heersen en Beheersen, Rijkswaterstaat in de Twintigste Eeuw. (Rule and Control, Rijkswaterstaat in the 20th Century), , European Library, Zaltbommel, The Netherlands; Kemp, R., Schot, J., Hoogma, R., Regime shifts to sustainability through the process of niche formation. The approach of strategic niche management (1998) Technol Anal Strateg Manage, 10 (2), pp. 175-195; Lintsen, H., Two centuries of 