"Levine R.A.","Drilling for reality",2005,"2005 International Oil Spill Conference, IOSC 2005",,,,2082,2084,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646035471&partnerID=40&md5=b9a7c372ab07ad5658305b87130ad27b","Alaskan Maritime Affairs, ARCO Marine, Inc., 700 G Street, ATO-906, Anchorage, AK 99501; AMI, AK","Levine, R.A., Alaskan Maritime Affairs, ARCO Marine, Inc., 700 G Street, ATO-906, Anchorage, AK 99501, AMI, AK","ARCO Marine, Inc. (AMI) has been holding regular oil spill drills for its spill team members since the mid-1970s. Over the years the drills have gotten more elaborate and more costly, employing equipment and testing initial response and transition management. By the 1993 drill, it was found, the drills were losing their educational benefits and for the most part had become well-rehearsed stage plays, with spill team members and other participants as actors and equipment as props. The drills were not providing the education necessary to develop team members for their roles as response managers. AMI rethought the drill process and, with the concurrence of the U.S. Coast Guard, the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation, and the Ship Escort and Response Vessel System, decided that it was time to ""drill for reality."".",,"Conservation; Costs; Drilling machines (machine tools); Environmental protection; Ships; Underwater drilling; ARCO Marine (CO); Oil spill drills; Response Vessel System; Transition management; Oil spills",,,,,,,"Levine, R.A.; Alaskan Maritime Affairs, ARCO Marine, Inc., 700 G Street, ATO-906, Anchorage, AK 99501, United States",,"API;IMO;IPIEGA;MMS;NOAA",,"2005 International Oil Spill Conference, IOSC 2005","15 May 2005 through 19 May 2005","Miami Beach, FL",67046,,,,,,"English","2005 International Oil Spill Conference, IOSC 2005",Conference Paper,Scopus
