"Rees C.J., Jarvalt J., Metcalfe B.","Career management in transition: HRD themes from the Estonian civil service",2005,"Journal of European Industrial Training",29,7,,572,592,,3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-25444433826&partnerID=40&md5=d861c0e9ea3900f918a9dbefb1b0c76f","IDPM, University of Manchester, Manchester, United Kingdom; Department of Personnel, State Chancellery, Tallinn, Estonia","Rees, C.J., IDPM, University of Manchester, Manchester, United Kingdom; Järvalt, J., Department of Personnel, State Chancellery, Tallinn, Estonia; Metcalfe, B., IDPM, University of Manchester, Manchester, United Kingdom","Purpose - To explore, through a case study, some of the key career-related HRD issues that senior managers are currently facing in the Estonian civil service. Design/methodology/approach - Presents primary empirical research into career management in the Estonian civil service since 1991, that is, in the post-Soviet era. The research involved in-depth interviews with a group of 12 senior staff employed by the Estonian civil service. Findings - The interview data reveal the ways in which downsizing and de-layering in the Estonian public sector have led to shortened career paths, increased functional flexibility, increased spans of control and shifts towards open job systems. Research limitations/implications - The research explored career-related issues solely within the Estonian civil service. Further research would be needed in a wider range of organisations and countries before the transferability of the findings could be established to transitional economies more generally. Practical implications - Provides practical insights into the difficulties of career management in transitional economies situations from an HR perspective. Originality/value - Offers a valuable contribution by demonstrating that, within certain parameters, Western-based career management strategies and techniques may be adapted to fit transitional public services in Estonia but only as one element of a comprehensive HR modernisation programme. © Emerald Group Publishing Limited.","Careers; Estonia; Public sector organizations; Transition management",,,,,,,"Arthur, M.B., Hall, D.T., Lawrence, B.S., Generating new directions in career theory: The case for a transdisciplinary approach (1989) Handbook of Career Theory, pp. 7-25. , Arthur, M.B. Hall, D.T. Lawrence, B.S. Cambridge University Press Cambridge; Benedict, B., Sociological characteristics of small territories and their implications for economic development (1966) The Social Anthropology of Complex Societies, pp. 23-35. , Banton, M. Tavistock Publications London; Bray, M., The organization and management of ministries of education in small states (1991) Public Administration and Development, 11, pp. 67-78; Drechsler, W., Estonia in transition (1995) World Affairs, 157 (3), pp. 111-18; Fey, C., Engström, P., Björkman, I., Effective human resource management practices for foreign firms in Russia (1999) Organizational Dynamics, pp. 69-79; Jankowicz, A.D., Issues in human resource management in Central Europe (1998) Personnel Review, 27 (3), pp. 169-76; Koubek, J., Brewster, C., Human resource management in turbulent times: HRM in the Czech Republic (1995) The International Journal of Human Resource Management, 6 (2), pp. 223-47; Lauristin, M., Contexts of transition (1997) Return to the Western World, pp. 25-40. , Lauristin, M. Vihalemm, P. Tartu University Press Tartu; Lauristin, M., Vihalemm, P., Recent historical developments in Estonia: Three stages of transition (1987-1997) (1997) Return to the Western World, pp. 73-126. , Lauristin, M. Vihalemm, P. Tartu University Press Tartu; Martin, R., (1999) Transforming Management in Central and Eastern Europe, , Oxford University Press Oxford; Mayo, A., (1991) Managing Careers: Strategies for Organizations, , IPM London; Murray, D.J., Microstates: Public administration for the small and beautiful (1981) Public Administration an