est viewed as a socially instituted process of adaptive change in which innovation is a necessary element. We discuss four key elements of governance for sustainability, which are integrated into the concept of transition management. The result is a conceptual framework for policy-making and action-taking aimed at progress towards sustainability. Copyright © 2005 Inderscience Enterprises Ltd.","Governance; Innovation; Sustainable development; Trade-offs","Decision making; Industrial management; International trade; Public policy; Governance; Innovation; Sustainability; Trade-offs; Sustainable development; governance approach; sustainable development",,,,,,"Abaza, H., Baranzini, A., (2002) Implementing Sustainable Development: Integrated Assessment and Participatory Decision-making Processes, , Edward Elgar, Cheltenham; Berkes, F., Folke, C., A systems perspective on the interrelationahips between natural, human-made and cultural capital (1993) Ecological Economics, 5 (1), pp. 1-8; Berkes, F., George, P., Preston, R.J., Co-management: The evolution in theory and practice of the joint administration of living resources (1991) Alternatives, 18 (2), pp. 12-18; Bleischwitz, R., Governance of sustainable development: Co-evolution of corporate and political strategies (2004) International Journal of Sustainable Development, 7 (1), pp. 27-43; Boyle, M., Gibson, R.B., Curran, D., If not here, then perhaps not anywhere: Urban growth management as a tool for sustainability planning in British Columbia's capital regional district (2004) Local Environment, 9 (1), pp. 21-43; Burrows, M., Just transition (2001) Alternatives Journal, 27 (1), pp. 29-32; Our commitment to sustainable development (1997) The Sustainable Development Framework, , chapter 2, CIDA, Ottawa/Hull; (2001) European Governance: A White Paper, , European Commission, Brussels; Coenen, F., The role of stakeholders in changing consumption and production patterns (2002) OECD Seminar on Improving Governance for Sustai