"Van Den Bosch S.J.M., Brezet J.C., Vergragt Ph.J.","How to kick off system innovation: A Rotterdam case study of the transition to a fuel cell transport system",2005,"Journal of Cleaner Production",13,10-11,,1027,1035,,9,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-14844347324&partnerID=40&md5=0e000fa80e55b17e0a35db3c8c5313f4","Delft University of Technology, Landbergstraat 15, 2628 CE Delft, Netherlands; IIIEE - Intl. Inst. Indust. E., Lund University, P.O. Box 196, SE-221 00 Lund, Sweden; Tellus Institute, 11 Arlington Street, Boston, MA 02116-3411, United States","Van Den Bosch, S.J.M., Delft University of Technology, Landbergstraat 15, 2628 CE Delft, Netherlands; Brezet, J.C., IIIEE - Intl. Inst. Indust. E., Lund University, P.O. Box 196, SE-221 00 Lund, Sweden; Vergragt, Ph.J., Tellus Institute, 11 Arlington Street, Boston, MA 02116-3411, United States","Fuel cells in combination with hydrogen are expected to play an important role in a future sustainable transport system. Recent studies have provided insight into how technological transitions may come about and may be managed. However, there is a lack of methodologies aimed at starting off transitions or system innovations, in practice. This paper addresses this issue by presenting a methodology characterized by a bottom-up approach to generate a roadmap for short-term projects within a long-term perspective. The methodology is applied in a Rotterdam case study of the transition to a fuel cell transport system. The outcome of this case study leads to recommendations for setting up a framework to facilitate and stimulate kicking off system innovation. © 2005 Published by Elsevier Ltd.","Fuel cells; Hydrogen; Roadmapping; System innovation; Transitions","Diffusion in gases; Electron transitions; Gas emissions; Greenhouse effect; Hydrogen; Internal combustion engines; Natural gas; Particulate emissions; Problem solving; Project management; Propulsion; Public policy; Fuel cell transport system (FCTS); Lear