"Duncan J.","The three laws of business dynamics",2005,"Chemical Engineer",,768,,36,37,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38349011454&partnerID=40&md5=9a699e0153b03966484c5a09d23fbf7a","Huxley Strategic Choice","Duncan, J., Huxley Strategic Choice","John Duncan, the director of Huxley Strategic Choice and specialist in transition management and executive coaching presents three laws of business dynamics for solving problems in businesses. All management initiatives must be accompanied by a measurable output because a decision has been consciously and carefully made to effect a change for the better. Motivation can overcome the barriers to success that some individuals build for themselves. Third buisness dynamics states that businesses must be able to respond to events to avoid disintegration. It is suggested that the strategies for achievement must be continuously reviewed to ensure that they are flexible enough to cope with the ever-changing world outside the organization.",,"Automotive industry; Commerce; Marketing; Personnel; Problem solving; Professional aspects; Societies and institutions; Strategic planning; Business dynamics; Mechanical devices; Middle management; Public sector; Industrial management",,,,,,,"Huxley Strategic Choice",,,,,,,,03020797,,CMERA,,,"English","Chemical Engineer",Review,Scopus
"Beaudry P., Collard F., Green D.A.","Demographics and recent productivity performance: Insights from cross-country comparisons",2005,"Canadian Journal of Economics",38,2,,309,344,,5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-19944388624&partnerID=40&md5=3be3849057fdeb44202d2cfff66b6d01","Department of Economics, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada; CNRS-GREMAQ, IDEI, University of Toulouse, Toulouse, France","Beaudry, P., Department of Economics, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada; Collard, F., CNRS-GREMAQ, IDEI, University of Toulouse, Toulouse, France; Green, D.A., Department of Economics, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada","Over the last few decades, countries have experienced quite different patterns of productivity growth. In this paper, we emphasize the role of country level demographics in explaining these differences. In particular, looking over the period 1960-2002, we show that cross-country data support the notion that, starting in the late 1970s, countries went through a period of technological transition that lasted at least until the mid-1990s for the fastest adjusting countries and is still proceeding for the slower adjusting countries. The main claim of the paper is that the country-level rate of labour growth was a key factor driving the speed of adjustment to the new technological paradigm, implying that much of the cross-country difference in economic performance over recent decades can be explained by demographic differences across countries as opposed to the many other factors emphasized in the literature. © Canadian Economics Association.",,"demography; economic development; productivity",,,,,,"Aghion, P., Howitt, P.W., 'On the macroeconomic effects of major technological change' (1998) General Purpose Technologies and Economic Growth, , ed. E. Helpman (Cambridge MA: MIT Press); Barro, R.J., Lee, J.W., 'International Data on Educational Attainment Updates and Implications' (2000