"Tuomi M.T.","Agents of social change in education",2005,"Community Development Journal",40,2,,205,211,,2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-18644380279&partnerID=40&md5=b6c0a8c960fb658f6351cd5057d586f0","National Institute for Educational Research, Teacher Training College, University of Jyväskylä, Jyväskylä, Finland","Tuomi, M.T., National Institute for Educational Research, Teacher Training College, University of Jyväskylä, Jyväskylä, Finland","The impact of the arrival of refugees and other immigrants in areas previously considered culturally homogeneous has influenced the school community. It has created an awareness of new needs and stimulated the development in both pre- and in-service teacher training. The ability to adapt to societal transitions is a skill to be developed in teachers. Rather than working for the socialization of students into the status quo, schools can educate students to be proactive agents of social change. Volunteer educators have participated in workgroup consultations to create appealing and realistic training that captures teachers' and student teachers' interests and enhances the creation of diversity-positive learning environments. A two-pronged approach is needed that promotes the world citizenship education of all students and meets the life long needs of immigrants. © Oxford University Press and Community Development Journal. 2005 All rights reserved.",,"education; immigrant population; refugee; social change; teaching",,,,,,"Bahá'u'lláh, (1983) Gleanings from the Writings of Bahá'u'lláh, , Bahá'í Publishing Trust, Wilmette, Illinois; (2002) Population 2003, 8. , Foreigners and International Migration Statistics Finland, Helsinki, Finland; Ghosn, I.-K., Partnership in education: Lebanese evolution of a Finnish educational model (2004) Scandinavian Journal of Educational Research, 48 (1), pp. 35-50; Izadi, P., (2003) In Quest of the Science of Education: From Reductionistic Discourse to Systemic Theory, , Univers