"Chen X., Cen G., Li D., He Y.","Social functioning and adjustment in Chinese children: The imprint of historical time",2005,"Child Development",76,1,,182,195,,51,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-14844290285&partnerID=40&md5=03bd7c66d0ea36af793d8ec3c9c1565a","University of Western Ontario; Shanghai Teachers' University; Hong Kong University; Department of Psychology, University of Western Ontario, London, Ont. N6A 5C2, Canada","Chen, X., University of Western Ontario, Department of Psychology, University of Western Ontario, London, Ont. N6A 5C2, Canada; Cen, G., Shanghai Teachers' University; Li, D., Shanghai Teachers' University; He, Y., Hong Kong University","This study examined, in 3 cohorts (1990, 1998, and 2002) of elementary school children (M age = 10 years), relations between social functioning and adjustment in different phases of the societal transition in China. Data were obtained from multiple sources. The results indicate that sociability- cooperation was associated with peer acceptance and teacher-rated competence, whereas aggression was associated with social and school difficulties in all 3 cohorts. The effect of different social contexts was reflected mainly in the relations between shyness-sensitivity and adjustment. Whereas shyness was associated with social and academic achievement in the 1990 cohort, the associations became weaker or nonsignificant in the 1998 cohort. Furthermore, shyness was associated with peer rejection, school problems, and depression in the 2002 cohort. © 2005 by the Society for Research in Child Development, Inc. All rights reserved.",,"achievement; adaptive behavior; aggression; article; child behavior; China; cohort analysis; cooperation; cultural anthropology; female; human; male; preschool child; psychologic test; psychological aspect; recreation; sex difference; social behavior; social change; Achievement; Adaptation, Psychological; Aggression; Child Behavior; Child, Preschool; China; Cohort Studies