"McGuirk S.M., Collins M.","Managing the production, storage, and delivery of colostrum",2004,"Veterinary Clinics of North America - Food Animal Practice",20,3 SPEC. ISS.,,593,603,,26,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-4744346042&partnerID=40&md5=4fec19d4d3d61f82831511205f82f934","Department of Medical Sciences, Univ. Wisconsin-Madison Sch. Vet. M., 2015 Linden Dr., Madison, W.; Dept. of Pathobiological Sciences, Univ. Wisconsin-Madison Sch. Vet. M., 2015 Linden Dr., Madison, W.","McGuirk, S.M., Department of Medical Sciences, Univ. Wisconsin-Madison Sch. Vet. M., 2015 Linden Dr., Madison, W.; Collins, M., Dept. of Pathobiological Sciences, Univ. Wisconsin-Madison Sch. Vet. M., 2015 Linden Dr., Madison, W.","Provision of an adequate immunoglobulin mass to dairy calves is an essential component for survival, health, and future productivity. To prevent FPT of immunity due to suckling of the dam, newborn dairy calves should be removed from the calving area within 30 minutes of birth. First and later lactation cows are suitable colostrum donors, provided they are healthy, well-vaccinated, have had optimal transition management, and an appropriate dry-period length. Early colostrum collection yields an adequate immunoglobulin mass provided that 3 to 4 L of colostrum is fed to the newborn calf. Regular testing for the adequacy of the dairy's colostrum feeding program is an excellent way to prevent calf health problems and identify potential need for CSs or replacement products.",,"immunoglobulin; animal health; animal product; cattle; colostrum; cow; feeding behavior; immunity; lactation; nonhuman; passive transport; review; survival; vaccination; Animals; Animals, Newborn; Cattle; Colostrum; Female; Food Handling; Health Status; Immunity, Maternally-Acquired; Immunoglobulin G; Lactation; Animalia; Bos taurus",,"immunoglobulin, 9007-83-4; Immunoglobulin G",,,,"Barrington, G.M., Parish, S.M., Bovine neonatal immunology (2001) Vet Clin North Am Food Anim Pr