"Skarderud F.","The communicating body: Eating disorders and culture [Den kommuniserende kroppen - Spiseforstyrrelser og kultur]",2004,"Tidsskrift for den Norske Laegeforening",124,18,,2365,2368,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-5444241601&partnerID=40&md5=f583c030ebfd6a524b3c8a77be0ef2a6","Regionsenteret Barne-/Ungdomspsykt., Helseregion Øst og Sør, Postboks 23, Tåsen, 0801 Oslo, Norway","Skårderud, F., Regionsenteret Barne-/Ungdomspsykt., Helseregion Øst og Sør, Postboks 23, Tåsen, 0801 Oslo, Norway","What is «culture» in eating disorders as culture-bound syndromes? The human body is a flesh-and-blood entity, but it also functions as a symbolic instrument. The body communicates about culture itself, about norms and boundaries. In this paper one central aspect in the phenomenology of eating disorders is emphasised: The subjective experience of lack of control and the sense of an overwhelming «chaos», both on the inner and outer level. On this basis rapid societal transitions are discussed as specific pathogenic factors. Sociocultural instability represents insecure conditions for construction of a healthy and stable identity. «The open body» is a relevant metaphor, with its dialectical relationship to the isolation and delimitation represented by eating disordered behaviour. With reference to history and geography the paper also discusses the pathoplasticity of eating disorders; how they change in time and space. Cultural analysis of eating disorders can contribute to a richer understanding of the complexity of the construction of meaning in these disorders, both across cultures and within our own cultural contexts.",,"anorexia nervosa; appetite; bulimia; comprehension; cultural anthropology; cultural factor; defense mechanism; diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders; eating disorder; geography; history; human; literature; mental patient; obsession; phenomenology; phobia; psychodynamics; religion; review; risk factor; self control; social aspect; symbolism; symptom; time; art; body image; cosmetic industry; female; male; psychological aspect; self concept; Beauty Culture; Body Image; Cross-Cultural Comparison; Culture; Eating Disorders; Female; Human Body; Humans; Male; Metaphor; Self Concept; Symbolism",,,,,,"Gordon, R.A., Eating disorders East and West: A culture-bound syndrome unbound (2001) Eating Disorders and Cultures in Transition, pp. 1-16. , Nasser M, Katzman MA, Gordon RA, red. New York: Brunner-Routledge; Barlow, D.H., Duran, V.M., (1999) Abnormal Psychology. 2 Utg., , Pacific Grove, CA: Brooks Cole; Sours, J.A., (1980) Starving to Death in a Sea of Objects, , New York: Jason Aronson; Polivy, J., Herman, C.P., Dieting and binging: A causal analysis (1985) Am Psychol, 40, pp. 193-201; Hsu, L.K.G., Can dieting cause an eating disorder? (1997) Psychol Med, 27, pp. 509-513; Herold, R.Z., (2001) Anorexia Nervosa. Et Kulturbundet Syndrorn? Psykologisk Studieskriftserie, , Århus: Aarhus Universitet; Yap, P.M., Mental diseases peculiar to certain cultures: A survey of comparative psychiatry (1951) J Ment Sci, 97, pp. 313-327; Hughes, C., Culture-bound or construct-bound? The syndromes of DSM-III (1985) The Culture-bound Syndromes: Folk Illnesses of Psychiatric and Anthropological Interest, pp. 3-24. , Simon R, Hughes C, red. Dordrecht: Reidel; Prince, R., Is anorexia nervosa a culture-bound syndrome? (1983) Transcult Psychiatry, 20, pp. 299-300; Isdahl, P.J., Skårderud, F., En introduksjon (1998) Kroppstanker. Kropp, Kjønn, Idéhistorie, pp. 7-17. , lsdahl PJ, Skårderud F, red. Oslo. Universitetsforlaget; Skårderud, F., Hvern har sett nøtter blø? et essay orn føde og fett (2003) Tidsskrift for Norsk Psykologforening, 40, pp. 412-417; Lakoff, G., Johnson, M., (1999) Philosophy in the Flesh. The Embodied Mind and Its Challenge to Western Thought, , New York: Basic Books; Lakoff, G., Johnson, M., (1980) Metaphors We Live by, , Chicago, IL: University of Chicago Press; Merleau-Ponty, M., (1962