"Kunreuther F.","The changing of the guard: What generational differences tell us about social-change organizations",2003,"Nonprofit and Voluntary Sector Quarterly",32,3,,450,457,,10,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0042328120&partnerID=40&md5=db9ac9d4b674fc3d984e111d9fccf70e",,"Kunreuther, F.","Accounts by executive directors and staff working in progressive social change organizations allude to generation-gap problems in the nonprofit sector that threaten the future work of these groups as they attempt to change ""the system"", To see how generational issues might be affecting social-change nonprofits, we conducted a series of in-depth interviews with executive directors (falling into two age groups') and with young staff (under 40 years old). The findings of the study refute the notion of large generational differences. Both older and younger people involved in these organizations have many of the same qualities: commitment, concern, energy, interest, and a strong belief in justice. However, differences are evident between those born in the Baby Boom generation and those who identify with Generation X in respect to their motivations to enter social change work, their concerns about the work/personal life divide, and their views of the future. Understanding these differences can help build strong leadership for the future.","Baby Boomer; Generation gap; Generation X; Leadership transition; Management; Nonprofit; Nonprofit leadership; Organizational form; Social change; Work-family balance",,,,,,,"Filipczak, B., Raines, C., Zemke, R., (2000) Generations at Work, , New York: AMACOM; Halstead, T., A politics for generation X (1999) The Atlantic Monthly, 284 (2), pp. 33-42. , August; Hornblower, M., Great xpectations (1997) Time, p. 58. , June 9; Kaminow, B., X, lies, and social signs: Defining generation X (1999) Problems and Issues of Diversity in the United States, pp. 147-160. , L. L. Naylor (Ed.). Westport, CT: Bergin and Garvey; Kitwana, B., (