"Guler M., Clements S., Wills L.M., Heck B.S., Vachtsevanos G.J.","Transition management for reconfigurable hybrid control systems",2003,"IEEE Control Systems Magazine",23,1,,36,49,,14,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037296212&partnerID=40&md5=a430155eb307774b87ef273d00eb8705","Sch. of Elec. and Comp. Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States","Guler, M., Sch. of Elec. and Comp. Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States; Clements, S., Sch. of Elec. and Comp. Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States; Wills, L.M., Sch. of Elec. and Comp. Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States; Heck, B.S., Sch. of Elec. and Comp. Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States; Vachtsevanos, G.J., Sch. of Elec. and Comp. Engineering, Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332-0250, United States","The generic aspects of transition management that are identified in hybrid system reconfiguration, as well as from the experience in building hybrid systems are described. It focuses on one particular generic pattern that recurs in hybrid system designs to smooth transitions when switching from one configuration to another. Thus, it shows how the pattern is supported on the open control platform (OCP), a real-time middleware-based substrate for integrating and reconfiguring control systems. This paper illustrates how this pattern can be instantiated in multiple different contexts that require configuration transitioning.",,"Computer aided software engineering; Computer architecture; Computer simulation; Computer software reusability; Finite automata; Formal logic; Large scale systems; Mathematical models; Middleware; Open systems; Robustness (control systems); Software prototyping; Component based software architecture; Generic patterns; Hybrid control systems