"Guler M., Clements S., Wills L., Heck B., Vachtsevanos G.","Generic transition management for reconfigurable hybrid control systems",2001,"Proceedings of the American Control Conference",5,,,3439,3444,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034855430&partnerID=40&md5=77ea4f4b9b840313b5febc56920807f1","School of Elec. and Computer Eng., Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States","Guler, M., School of Elec. and Computer Eng., Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; Clements, S., School of Elec. and Computer Eng., Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; Wills, L., School of Elec. and Computer Eng., Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; Heck, B., School of Elec. and Computer Eng., Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States; Vachtsevanos, G., School of Elec. and Computer Eng., Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA 30332, United States","This paper describes a generic pattern for performing transition management in reconfigurable hybrid control systems. This is based on an examination of hybrid systems literature as well as experience in building hybrid control systems for extreme-performance applications. The generic pattern is built upon the Open Control Platform, which is a middleware-based substrate for integrating and dynamically reconfiguring distributed control applications. The generic pattern encapsulates the reconfiguration decision logic, the rewiring strategy, and the blending function as separate modular entities that can be specified and easily changed by the control system designer. Its use is illustrated in multiple hybrid system examples.",,"Control system synthesis; Decision theory; Distributed computer systems; Genetic algorithms; Large scale systems; Mathematical models; Middleware; Object oriented programming; Real time systems; Decision logic; Open control platform; Reconfigurable hybrid control sys