"Marks M.L., Mirvis P.H.","Managing mergers, acquisitions, and alliances: Creating an effective transition structure",2000,"Organizational Dynamics",28,3,,35,47+4+5,,17,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0002193824&partnerID=40&md5=cd0b1029a1e3db225d9878cd40843dcd","California Sch. of Prof. Psychology, Los Angeles; Found. for Community Encouragement; Dept. of Strat. and Intl. Management, London Business School","Marks, M.L., California Sch. of Prof. Psychology, Los Angeles; Mirvis, P.H., Found. for Community Encouragement, Dept. of Strat. and Intl. Management, London Business School","More and more companies are using some form of transition structure to help plan and direct integration in their mergers, acquisitions, and alliances. Yet studies find that more than 80 percent of corporate combinations fail to achieve projected financial, strategic, and operational synergies. Obviously, the price paid, choice of partners, clarity of strategy, and compatibility of cultures are important factors in failure versus success. Based on the authors' experience in over 50 combinations, another success factor is the way the transition is organized and managed. This article describes key considerations and pitfalls in designing and running an effective transition structure. A transition structure is a forum in which executives from combining companies can study and plan for the ways that promised objectives can be realized in practice. It is a temporary but formal arrangement whose members represent every area of the two companies and have joint input into the integration of businesses. It also promotes ""relationship building"" between the two sides. A well-run transition structure ensures that in-depth thinking and informed decisions go into creating the new operation while the demands of running the day-today business are still met. This article first describes three elements of a transition structure - a senior leadership steering committee, transition manager, and transition task forces. It then covers tested practices for organizing, guiding, and accelerating the work of transition management.",,,,,,,,"(1998) Joining Forces: Making One Plus One Equal Three in Mergers, Acquisitions and Alliances, , Jossey-Bass; Mark, (1997) From Turmoil to Triumph: New Life after Mergers, Acquisitions and Alliances, , Lexington Books; Sirower, M., (1997) The Synergy Trap, , Free Press; Beckhard, R., Harris, R., (1977) Organizational Transitions: Managing Complex Change, , Addison-Wesley; Lewin, K., Frontiers in group dynamics (1947) Human Relations, 1 (1), pp. 5-41; Janis, I., (1997) Victims of Groupthink, , Houghton Mifflin","California Sch. of Prof. Psychology, Los Angeles",,,,,,,,00902616,,,,,"English","Organizational Dynamics",Article,Scopus
"Rogers K.A.","Transition management as an intervention for survivor syndrome.",2000,"Canadian journal of nursing leadership",13,4,,19,26,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-7244257421&partnerID=40&md5=3bdc39587d45b4fe9f02f1b633d6c609","Halton Healthcare Services, Oakville, ON.","Rogers, K.A., Halton Healthcare Services, Oakville, ON.","In today's health care environment of merged organizations, downsizing and restructuring, employees can be experiencing a debilitating syndrome called ""layoff survivor syndrome."" This syndrome can have a crippling effect on workers and organizations as employees struggle to adapt to the changed working environment. This article represents my self-reflection as a nursing unit manager who personally experienced survivor sickness and witnessed its impact on the unit staff that I was leading at the time. The work of Noer (1993) is explored to clarify the syndrome and describe how the nursing staff and I manifested the syndrome. The writings of Bridges (1991), Brockner (1992) and Noer (1993) provide timely and relevant insights into managing the impact of layoffs and downsizing on those left behind to carry on. Noer (1993) sees the adaptation to the change as the ability to make the psychological shift from the old business paradigm that perpetuated codependency to the new business paradigm of fostering empowered employees. Bridges (1991) takes us a step further in making this psychological shift to adapt to the new work environment by providing a three phase process he calls transitions. The works of these three authors hold an important message for organizations and employees working in environments that abound with constant change.",,"adaptive behavior; anger; denial; fear; health care facility; health personnel attitude; hospital subdivisions and components; hostility; human; interdisciplinary communication; methodology; nurse administrator; nursing; nursing staff; occupational health; organization; organization a