"Galor O., Moav O.","Ability-biased technological transition, wage inequality, and economic growth",2000,"Quarterly Journal of Economics",115,2,,469,497,,132,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0040016339&partnerID=40&md5=4be0f6d4e64f28d896f4f9978c158fce",,"Galor, O.; Moav, O.","This paper develops a growth model characterized by ability-biased technological transition in which the evolution of technology, education attainment, and wage inequality is consistent with the observed pattern in the United States and other advanced countries over the past several decades. It argues that an increase in the rate of technological progress raises the return to ability and simultaneously generates an increase in wage inequality between and within groups of skilled and unskilled workers, an increase in average wages of skilled workers, a temporary decline in average wages of unskilled workers, an increase in education, and a productivity transitory slowdown.",,,,,,,,"Acemoglu, D., Why do new technologies complement skills? directed technical change and wage inequality (1998) Quarterly Journal of Economics, 113, pp. 1055-1089; Changes in unemployment and inequality: An alternative theory and some evidence (1999) American Economic Review; Aghion, P., Howitt, P., Violante, G., (1999) General Purpose Technology, Knowledge and Within Group Inequality, , University College London; Autor, D.H., Katz, L.F., Krueger, A.B., Computing inequality: Have computers changed the labor market? (1998) Quarterly Journal of Economics, 113, pp. 1169-1213; Bartel, A.P., Sicherman, N., Technological change and the skill acquisitions of young workers (1998) Journal of Labor Economics, 16, pp. 718-755; Bartel, A.P., Sicherman, N., Technological change and wages: An inter-industry analysis (1999) Journal of Political Economy, 107, pp. 285-325; Berman, E., Bound, J., Machin, S., Implications of skill-biased technological change: International evidence (1998) Quarterly Journal of Economics,