"Booth H.","Pacific Island suicide in comparative perspective",1999,"Journal of Biosocial Science",31,4,,433,448,,17,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032857409&partnerID=40&md5=0c20eec697a5a17e75f3b6b552859265","Demography Program, Research School of Social Sciences, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia","Booth, H., Demography Program, Research School of Social Sciences, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia","All available data for thirteen Pacific Island nations are used in a comparative analysis of suicide levels and characteristics. Age, sex and method of suicide are examined in detail. Global comparison shows Pacific rates are amongst the highest reported. Female youth rates exceed male rates in Western Samoa and amongst Fiji Indians. Method of suicide (paraquat ingestion) is instrumental in determining high rates in Western Samoa, especially in females. The broad causal theme is societal transition. Commonality and diversity are discussed.",,"paraquat; adolescent; adult; article; comparative study; female; Fiji; human; major clinical study; male; Pacific islands; Polynesia; social adaptation; suicide; Adolescent; Adult; Age Distribution; Child; Female; Humans; Male; Middle Aged; Pacific Islands; Sex Distribution; Suicide",,,,,,"Akin, D., Suicide and women in East Kwaio, Malaita (1985) Culture, Youth and Suicide in the Pacific: Papers from An East-West Center Conference, pp. 198-210. , Edited by F. X. Hezel, D. H. Rubinstein & G. M. White. Pacific Islands Studies Program, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Honolulu; American Samoa Statistical Digest, , Economic Development and Planning Office, American Samoa; Booth, H., (1994) The Estimation of Levels and Trends in Age at First Birth and Age at First Marriage in the Pacific Islands, , Research School of Social Sciences, Australian National University, Canberra; Booth, H., The availability and quality of health indicators in the South Pacific (1998