"Keck M.","Requirements and possibilities for the maintenance of a stable rehabilitation result when optimizing the transition between phases II and III [Voraussetzungen und moglichkeiten zum erhalt eines stabilen rehabilitationsergebnisses im rahmen der schnittstellenoptimierung phase II/III]",1999,"Pravention und Rehabilitation",11,3,,102,105,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032885601&partnerID=40&md5=9d31422a399dfdded99474fd5b02f9c8","Kurhausstrasse 2, D-55583 Bad Munster Stein-Ebernburg, Germany","Keck, M., Kurhausstrasse 2, D-55583 Bad Munster Stein-Ebernburg, Germany","Optimizing the transition between phases II and III of cardiological rehabilitation has proved to be one of the decisive factors for a reliable maintenance of the rehabilitation result. It represents one of the major quality criteria when evaluating the result with regard to the objective. Apart from patient-related approaches, the family physician, relatives, job- related institutions (employer, institute of vocational promotion, employment offices etc.) as well as local and regional institutional partners (adult education centres, health insurances, sports clubs etc.) should be included in particular. The report provides incentives and practical help for managing the transition.","Cardiac rehabilitation; Communication; Patient education; Transition management","article; heart rehabilitation; human; patient education; treatment outcome; treatment planning",,,,,,,"Keck, M.Kurhausstrasse 2, D-55583 Bad Munster Stein-Ebernburg, Germany",,,,,,,,0937552X,,PREHE,,,"German","Pravention und Rehabilitation",Article,Scopus
"Straus L.G.","Iberia: Bridge or cul-de-sac? Implications of the Iberian record for the debate on the middle to upper palaeolithic transition",1999,"Human Evolution",14,1,,139,149,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0008864211&partnerID=40&md5=01bdfd6b09e91dc350228d630d2c551f","Dept. of Anthropology, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131, United States","Straus, L.G., Dept. of Anthropology, University of New Mexico, Albuquerque, NM 87131, United States","Recent discoveries and dating of materials from Spain and Portugal for the period between c. 40-30 kya highlight the fact that the Iberian Peninsula is a microcosm of the complex mosaic of conditions that characterized the middle to upper palaeolithic and Neanderthal to Cro-Magnon transitions. They would tend to suggest that the replacement of one way of life by another was far from rapid, abrupt or simple, and they call into question the ""out of Africa"" invasionist scenario. Although Iberia seems to have been a ""bridge"" between Africa and the rest of Europe during certain times (notably at the time of the first colonization(s) of Europe, perhaps in the late Lower Pleistocene, as suggested by the discoveries at Atapuerca), at other times it seems to have been cut off from Africa. Despite the presence of Aurignacian technology in Cantabria and Catalonia since 40 kya, the continued persistence of Neanderthals and of Mousterian technology for over 10 ky in southern Iberia would seem to belie the superiority and African origin of upper palaeolithic Cro-Magnon. Furthermore, even in northern Spain, where the taxonomic identity of the makers of the early Aurignacian remains unknown, the nature of the technological transition was variable: abrupt in Catalonia and gradual in Cantabria. Added to the rest of the record, which includes Neanderthals apparently making Chatelperronian tools in France, Szeletian tools in Hungary and later Aurignacian tools in Croatia, a complete lack of any fossils in definite association with early Aurignacian anywhere, evidence of subsistence and technological change during the Mousterian in certain regions of Europe, scant evidence for cultural differentiation between Neanderthals and early anatomically modern humans (Skhul & Qafzeh) in Israel, growing (albeit limited) evidence for middle palaeolithic artistic or ornamental activity, and evidence for considerable, on-going change in technology and subsistence during the upper palaeolithic, the Iberian record strongly argues for a long, uneven transition from middle to upper palaeolithic lifeways- not a simple, abrupt invasion of Europe out of Africa.","Homo sapiens sapiens; Iberia; Middle palaeolithic; Neanderthal; Portugal; Spain; Upper palaeolithic",,,,,,,"Allsworth-Jones, P., Les industries à pointes foliacées d'Europe centrale (1990) Mémoires du Musée de Préhistoire d'Ile de France, 3, pp. 79-97. , (C. Farizy, éd.) Paléolithique moyen récent et paléolithique supérieur ancien en Europe; Altuna, J., Fauna de mamíferos de los yacimientos prehistóricos de Guipúzçoa (1972) Munibe, 24, pp. 1-464; Altuna, J., Mariezkurrena, Les macromammifères du paléolithique moyen et supérieur ancien de la région cantabrique (1988) Archaeozoologia, 1 (12), pp. 179-196; Antunes, M., O homen de gruta de Figueira Brava (1990) Memorias de Academia Das Ciencias de Lisboa, 31, pp. 487-536; Antunes, M., Peixoto, J., Cardoso, J., Monge, A., Paleolitico medio e superior en Portugal (1989) Ciencias Da Terra, 10, pp. 127-138; Barandiarán, I., Industria ósea (1980) Bibliotheca Praehistorica Hispana, 17, pp. 151-191. , (J. González Echegaray, ed.) El yacimiento de la cucva de El Pendo; Bartrolí, R., Cebrià, A., Muro, I., Riu-Barrera, E., Vaquero, M., A free de ciència: L'atles d'Amador Romaní i Guerra (1995) Ajuntament de Capellades.; Bernaldo De Quirós, F., Cabrera, V., Early upper palaeolithic industries of Cantabrian Spain (1993) Before Lascaux, pp. 57-70. , (H. Knecht, A. Pike-Tay & R. White, eds.). 