"Salmond S.W.","Managing the human side of change.",1998,"Orthopaedic nursing / National Association of Orthopaedic Nurses",17,5,,38,51,,1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032151620&partnerID=40&md5=75c2311ce3710c666b61b55b83f87a6f","Department of Nursing, Kean University, Union, New Jersey, USA.","Salmond, S.W., Department of Nursing, Kean University, Union, New Jersey, USA.","Change initiatives (strategic plans) often fail, not because the idea was wrong, but because the change process failed to consider the human side of change. Achieving desired change outcomes requires an accentuation of transition management efforts or a focus on people. This article proposes 12 steps to managing transition and preparing ""change-ready"" employees and highlights strategies for both staff and managers to consider in the process.",,"adaptive behavior; education; health personnel attitude; human; interpersonal communication; methodology; nursing; nursing staff; organization; organization and management; personnel management; psychological aspect; public relations; review; Adaptation, Psychological; Attitude of Health Personnel; Communication; Humans; Interprofessional Relations; Nursing Staff, Hospital; Nursing, Supervisory; Organizational Culture; Organizational Innovation; Personnel Management",,,,,,,"Salmond, S.W.",,,,,,,,07446020,,,,9832886,"English","Orthopaedic nursing / National Association of Orthopaedic Nurses",Review,Scopus
"Van Peer P.","The nile corridor and the out-of-Africa model An examination of the archaeological record",1998,"Current Anthropology",39,SUPPL.1,,S115,S140,,49,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0000439197&partnerID=40&md5=3a630eac9736b46541f61ae2ca835127","Department of Archaeology, Catholic University of Leuven, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium","Van Peer, P., Department of Archaeology, Catholic University of Leuven, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium","This paper addresses the question of whether archaeological data - especially data from the Middle Palaeolithic - are relevant to current discussion on the origin and dispersal of modern humans. The structure of the Middle Paleolithic record of the Lower Nile Valley and adjacent deserts, a key region in the Out-of-Africa model, is examined. On the basis of the present database two archaeological complexes can be established: the Nubian complex and the Lower Nile Valley complex. In the Nubian complex, which appears in the Lower Nile Valley during the late Middle Pleistocene and coexists with a Lower Nile Valley complex issuing from the local Acheulean, hunting was a major subsistence strategy. From the last interglacial on the Nubian complex is found beyond the valley, whereas the Lower Nile Valley complex remains restricted to its riverine environment. Here, a technological transition to an Upper Palaeolithic type of production is attested as a punctuated event around 40,000 years ago at the latest. The appearance of the Nubian complex in the northern reaches of the Nile Valley would seem to correspond to the Out-of-Africa model of dispersal. However, the general reconstruction of behavioural repertoires from archaeological evidence does not satisfactorily correspond to the patterning expected according to either that model or its alternative. It is concluded that the Middle Palaeolithic record of Northeast Africa is the product of different populations with modern behavioural capacities. Their particular organisations of the subsistence domain and even their migrations are revealed in archaeological patterns of variability and change, but the record holds no evidence of anatomical constraints on this capacity for modern behaviour or of the social mechanisms by which it might have been transmitted. © 1998 by The Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research. All rights reserved.",,,,,,,,"BAR-YOSEF, O., The role of western Asia in modern human origins (1993) The origin of modern humans and the impact of Chronometric dating, pp. 132-147. , Edited by M. J. Aitken, C. B. Stringer, and P. A. Mellars, pp, Princeton: Princeton University Press; BAR-YOSEF, O., The contributions of Southwest Asia to the study of the origin of modern humans (1994) Origins of anatomically modem humans, pp. 23-66. , Edited by M. H. Nitecki and D. V. Nitecki, pp, New York and London: Plenum Press; _. 1996a. Modern humans, Neanderthals, and the Middle/Upper Palaeolithic transition in Western Asia, in The colloquia of the Thirteenth International Congress of Prehistoric and Protohistoric Sciences, 5, The Lower and Middle Palaeolithic. Edited by O. Bar-Yosef, L. L. Cavalli-Sforza, R. J. March, and M. Piperno, pp. 175-90. Forli: A.B.A.C.O. EdizioniBAR-YOSEF, O., The impact of Late-Pleistocene-Early Holocene climatic changes on humans in Southwest Asia (1996) Humans at the end of the Ice Age, pp. 61-78. , Edited by L. G. Straus, B. V. Eriksen, J. M. Erlandson, and D. R. Yesner, pp, New York and London: Plenum Press; BAR-YOSEF, O., GOREN, N., Afterthoughts following prehistoric surveys in the Levant (1980) Israel Exploration Journal, 30, pp. 1-16. , NR; BINFORD, L.R., (1981) Bones: Ancient men and modern myths, , New York: Academic Press; BINFORD, L.R., (1983) In pursuit of the past: Decoding the archaeological record, , London: Thames and Hudson; BINFORD, L.R., An Alyawara day: Making men's knives and beyond (1986) American Antiquity, 51, pp. 547-562; BINFORD, L.R., Isolating the transition to cultural adapta