"Ehrnberg E., Jacobsson S.","Managing technological discontinuities - A tentative framework",1996,"International Journal of Technology Management",11,3-4,,452,469,,4,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0042507045&partnerID=40&md5=62cd37b840bb8b00cd2c068908626cf3","Department of Industrial Management and Economics, School of Technology Management and Economics, Chalmers University of Technology, S-41296 Göteborg, Sweden","Ehrnberg, E., Department of Industrial Management and Economics, School of Technology Management and Economics, Chalmers University of Technology, S-41296 Göteborg, Sweden; Jacobsson, S., Department of Industrial Management and Economics, School of Technology Management and Economics, Chalmers University of Technology, S-41296 Göteborg, Sweden","Established firms frequently face difficulties in managing technological discontinuities, while successful firms are often found among new entrants. From the perspective of an established firm, we will identify a set of factors influencing how such a firm fares through a transition. These factors operate at different units of analysis: the technology, the firm, the industry, the technological system and the region/nation. We will explore each of these, integrate them and develop a frame of reference for analysing the conditions under which a firm will come out of a technological transition successfully. Copyright © 1996 Inderscience Enterprises Ltd.",,,,,,,,"Henderson, R.M., (1988) The Failure of Established Firms in the Face of Technical Change: A Study of Photolithographic Alignment Equipment, , Doctoral Thesis in the subject of Business Economics, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts; Foster, R.N., Timing technological transitions (1986) Technology in the Modern Corporation: A Strategic Perspective, , Horwitch (Ed.) (1986) Pergamon Press; Foster, R.N., Working the S-curve. Assessing technological threats (1986) Research Management, (JULY-AUGUST), pp. 17-22; Cooper, A., Schendel, D.