"Sundberg S.B.","A female frontier: Manitoba farm women in 1922",1991,"Prairie Forum",16,2,,185,204,,2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0026292480&partnerID=40&md5=f112843daa532e85738e863f4261bd03",,"Sundberg, S.B.","In 1922 the United Farm Women of Manitoba conducted the ""Rural Home Survey' to assess the living and working conditions of Manitoba farm women. An analysis of the results of the survey demonstrates that the impact of technological change on farm women's lives remained limited in 1922. Thus, even though farm areas were undergoing a technological transition in the early 20th century, farm women shared a continuity of tasks and concerns with their 19th century pioneer sisters. Manitoba women, as late as 1922, were part of an extended female frontier. This frontier, defined by factors related to farm women's lives at home, progressed slowly along a timetable separate from that of the agricultural frontier traditionally defined by male experiences. -Author",,"farm workers; female frontier; Rural Home Survey (1922); technological change; United Farm Women of Manitoba; women; working conditions; Canada, Manitoba",,,,,,,,,,,,,,,03176282,,,,,"English","Prairie Forum",,Scopus
