"Kopp H.","Changes in land use in northern Yemen since 1970: from the self-sufficient tribal society to a free-enterprise orientated national state [Landnutzungswandel im Nordjemen seit 1970. Von der autarken Stammesgesellschaft zum marktwirtschaftlich orientierten Nationalstaat]",1990,"Erdkunde",44,2,,136,148,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0025583848&partnerID=40&md5=1f64ffabe88dd339f0d7948d72c1016b",,"Kopp, H.","Northern Yemen up to 1970 had been marked by a sedentary, rural tribal population, who aimed at political autonomy through economic autarky. The inability of the system to take up innovations had led to a remarkable adaptation of the land use to the ecological system. Since 1970 the change in land use has been subject to a number of factors which, taken together, initiated the transition to a market-orientated production. The capitalization of agriculture, which quickly took place, led to a new assessment of the agrarian locational factors with serious effects on the ecological system, the spatial-structural and the agrarian-social conditions. The development of the infrastructure serves as an indication of the extent of the changes. -English summary",,"agricultural commercialisation; agricultural practice; capitalisation; ecological system; infrastructure; infrastructure development; land use; land-use change; locational factor; market-oriented production; political autonomy; societal transition; spatial system; tribal population; Yemen(North)",,,,,,,,,,,,,,,00140015,,,,,"German","Erdkunde",,Scopus
"Haltman K.","Reaching out to touch someone?. Reflections on a 1923 candlestick telephone",1990,"Technology in Society",12,3,,333,354,,2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-44949269366&partnerID=40&md5=ae0ac5a8ba975e5f6f7b83fef63e7f8c",,"Haltman, K.","This paper bases its analysis on close description of the 1923 candlestick telephone, in its day telecommunication technology's principal user interface. Designed to be compatible with human requirements, some functional, others emotional and psychological, the candlestick model proves more susceptible to psychocultural than to purely functional analysis. Hints of human physiology in design provide an interpretive clue of importance. Visits at a distance were both made plausible and dramatized to the user through a process of surrogacy or displacement; sympathy, even complicity, were through the illusion that one spoke to the machine instead of through it. The phone set's gaze naturalized (and rationalized) the apparent solipsism of conversation with an absent other. Its form served to compensate for what telephony itself could not provide, or could provide only in metaphor. Harmonious organic lines in combination with the anonymous female voice of the operator played their part in softening a technological transition, suggesting that intimacy in telephone communication might reside in a familiarity with the machine itself. In actuality, however, automatic telephones alienated intimacy as thoroughly as they ensured it. Though evidence of this ambiguity is discernible throughout the candlestick's design, the model's form provided reassurance, through organic contour and suggestions of familiar ritual, that touch was possible, even at a distance. © 1990.",,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,0160791X,,,,,"English","Technology in Society",Article,Scopus
