"Hunsucker John L., Loos David","Transition management: An analysis of strategic considerations for effective implementation",1989,"Engineering management international",5,3,,167,178,,8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0024607024&partnerID=40&md5=3fff6ff1ca714b42efd1d2a29c27da3d","Univ of Houston, United States","Hunsucker, John L., Univ of Houston, United States; Loos, David, Univ of Houston, United States","Management literature contains hundreds of sources dealing with various aspects of change management and there are numerous books and case studies which discuss the complete process. After reviewing this material and testing it against interviews conducted with managers of companies that have undergone change programs, the authors have identified six guidelines of facilitate successful change. These six factors are: the need for a catalyst to initiate change; organizational goals must be set which take into account the impact of technical, political, and cultural factors; transition team is required to guide the change; top management must demonstrate commitment to the change as well as to act as change agents; utilizing employee participation and good communication can help overcome employee resistance; and finally, evaluating the change program is extremely important to the success of present and future change programs.",,"Strategic Planning; Systems Engineering; Technology--Economic and Sociological Effects; Employee Participation; Organizational Change Programs; Transition Team; Industrial Management",,,,,,,"Hunsucker, John L.; Univ of HoustonUnited States",,,,,,,,01675419,,EMIND,,,"English","Engineering management international",Article,Scopus
