"Peck W.F.","LEADERSHIP TRANSITION FROM SCIENTIST TO MANAGER IN A GROWING TECHNICAL ORGANIZATION.",1986,[No source information available],,,,100,104,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0022959125&partnerID=40&md5=66a64128fce62581f9e6c9736e6895d0","Technical Management Consultants, Inc, Atlanta, GA, USA, Technical Management Consultants Inc, Atlanta, GA, USA","Peck, W.F., Technical Management Consultants, Inc, Atlanta, GA, USA, Technical Management Consultants Inc, Atlanta, GA, USA","A discussion is presented of the leadership characteristics and practice environments for technical personnel in growing scientific organizations. While much of the data and experience has been accumulated for technical organizations in private practice, the principles are applicable to institutional and public technical organizations as well. Two specific changes are thought necessary as a scientist develops into a professional manager in a growing organization. First, the leader's relationship with the product or service must change from direct to indirect involvement. The orientation changes from technical problem-solving and control to leading and teaching others to solve the technical problems and deal directly with projects. Second, as the organization grows, its leaders must recognize and support the unpopular position that more formal policies and procedures are necessary. The author also considers how a technical leader's time may change as an organization grows in terms of operations, human resources, financial management, planning, and marketing.",,"MANAGEMENT - Research and Development Application; ENGINEERING PROFESSION; RD&E MANAGEMENT; TECHNICAL LEADER; FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT; GROWTH CRITERIA; LEADERSHIP TRANSITION; MANAGEMENT TIME DISTRIBUTION; PERSONALITY-INTEREST PROFILE; TECHNICAL CAREER EVOLUTION; ENGINEERING; MANAGEMENT SCIENCE",,,,,,,"Peck, W.F.; Technical Management Consultants, Inc, Atlanta, GA, USA, Technical Management Consultants Inc, Atlanta, G